<BODY>
<HEADLINE> L.A. Jury Deadlocked Over Shootout  </HEADLINE>
By LINDA DEUTSCH, AP Special Correspondent
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The jury in the North Hollywood shootout
trial sent word Wednesday that the panel was hopelessly deadlocked
over the claim that police let a wounded gunman die.
</P>
<P>
   But the judge ordered the panel, which has deliberated for three
full days, to try again to reach a verdict.
</P>
<P>
   ''You have an obligation to reach a verdict if you can do so
without violating your own conscience,'' said U.S. District Judge
Christina Snyder.
</P>
<P>
   The jurors deliberated a few more hours and recessed for the
night. Earlier Wednesday, they had sent a note to Snyder that said:
''We all agree that additional deliberation time will be of no
use.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit against retired policemen John Futrell and James
Vojtecky and the city claims the officers let Emil Matasareanu, 30,
die due to deliberate indifference.
</P>
<P>
   Matasareanu's children are seeking unspecified damages in the
civil rights lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   The allegation cast a shadow over what had been heralded as a
day of heroism as lightly armed officers took on gunmen who blasted
a neighborhood around a Bank of America branch with automatic
weapons, wounding 11 officers and six civilians.
</P>
<P>
   The jury heard conflicting medical opinions on whether
Matasareanu could have survived. But based on testimony the jury
asked to have read back, the panel appeared to focus on whether
emergency medical help was or could have been available.
</P>
<P>
   The testimony involved an ambulance crew that arrived but left
without Matasareanu after Vojtecky allegedly told the crew to ''get
the (expletive) out of here.''
</P>
<P>
   During the trial, Vojtecky testified he did not say that but did
say something similar.
</P>
<P>
   The officers testified they tried to get the ambulance to come
back or to get another one, but the plaintiffs focused on a point
at which Futrell canceled an ambulance call and told the
dispatcher, ''I have no officers or citizens down, only a
suspect.''
</P>
<P>
   Futrell insisted the seriousness of Matasareanu's wounds were
not apparent.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs' lawyers told the jury that Matasareanu had done
a ''bad thing'' -- robbing a bank and shooting a lot of people -- but
had suffered a tortured death.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing full body armor, Matasareanu and Larry Eugene Phillips,
26, were spotted by a police unit as they tried get away from the
bank on Feb. 28, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The hooded gunmen raked the area with hundreds of rounds of
gunfire in a 44-minute battle as the nation watched on television.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips died first, shooting himself as a police bullet hit his
spine. Matasareanu drove off but was forced to take cover behind
his car in a street.
</P>
<P>
   He finally fell after a furious firefight with SWAT officers.
Shot 29 times, he bled profusely as he lay handcuffed.
</P>
<P>
   The defense argued that the scene was chaotic, many people
needed rescue, that officers did request aid for Matasareanu but
the area was too dangerous for ambulance crews as police searched
for other gunmen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
