<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 00:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Couple Wins $26M in Bronco Case  </HEADLINE>
By MARY ANN LICKTEIG, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- A jury has ordered Ford Motor Co. to pay
nearly $26 million to a man whose Bronco truck rolled over on a
freeway in 1996, leaving him quadriplegic.
</P>
<P>
   An Alameda Superior Court jury on Tuesday determined Richard
Raimondi and his wife, Dana, had suffered $52 million in damages.
But they awarded them half that amount after finding Mr. Raimondi
shared responsibility with Ford for the accident.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys for Ford said the company would ask a judge to set
aside or reduce the verdict, and would appeal if their efforts
fail.
</P>
<P>
   Raimondi was alone in his Bronco II-model truck in July 1996
when he swerved to miss debris on Interstate 880 in Fremont, a
suburb about 30 miles southeast of San Francisco. The truck scraped
a concrete median, bounced back, clipped a car and rolled over
three times.
</P>
<P>
   During a two-month trial, the couple's lawyers argued the
truck's narrow wheelbase and high center of gravity made it
unstable and prone to roll over.
</P>
<P>
   ''Their argument is these things should all be like passenger
cars,'' said Warren Platt, an attorney for Ford. ''From the
standpoint of the manufacturers, there's no way that can happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford made 700,000 Bronco IIs between 1983 and 1990. As of
January 1999, Ford had settled 679 Bronco II rollover cases,
according to the Los Angeles Times.
</P>
<P>
   About 16 lawsuits have gone to trial, Platt said. Of those, Ford
has won about 70 percent, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
