<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 00:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> McCall tells supporters he is running for governor  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT, AP Political Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Democrats who were on hand for the private
meeting say state Comptroller H. Carl McCall told supporters this
week that he is running for governor in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   McCall, the first and thus far only black ever elected to
statewide office in New York, didn't deny making such a statement
at the Tuesday night meeting in Albany.
</P>
<P>
   ''I made a long speech. I said a lot of things. But my position,
my public position, is I will make an announcement about what I'm
going to do in November, after the election'' this year, the New
York City Democrat said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you want to say people said that I said something, that's
fine,'' McCall added.
</P>
<P>
   McCall also observed to a reporter, ''You've got something to
write.''
</P>
<P>
   For months, McCall has been edging closer to a run for governor.
</P>
<P>
   Late last year, he hired a veteran fund-raising operative and in
January said that ''if we can put things in place over the next
several months, then that will decide it. It all seems to be lining
up that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican Gov. George Pataki has said he may be interested in
running for a third term.
</P>
<P>
   On the Democratic side, federal Housing Secretary Andrew Cuomo,
son of former New York Gov. Mario Cuomo, is also considering the
2002 governor's race. Pataki beat the elder Cuomo as he tried for a
fourth, four-year term.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Cuomo, who has been pressing New York Democrats not to
line up behind McCall, said through a spokesman that ''right now my
political focus is to help Al Gore become president and Hillary
Clinton become senator. Any discussion of future election campaigns
would be a distraction for the Democratic effort.''
</P>
<P>
   McCall said he told Democrats at Tuesday's meeting that their
first priority this year had to be electing Gore and the first
lady.
</P>
<P>
   At least four Democrats who attended the Tuesday night session
with McCall at an Albany hotel -- all speaking on condition of
anonymity -- said the comptroller said he was running. The session
was the first of five regional meetings being held by McCall's
gubernatorial advisory committee over the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ''He said, 'I'm not exploring it, I'm running,''' one Democrat
quoted McCall as saying.
</P>
<P>
   Another Democrat said McCall had said, ''I'm not exploring, I'm
not determining, I'm running.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Democrats who attended the meeting and were willing to
speak publicly -- although not about McCall's specific statements --
said they were confident McCall would run.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think everybody came out of that meeting clearly believing
that Carl was running,'' said state Assembly Majority Leader
Michael Bragman, a powerful Syracuse-area Democrat who is backing
McCall.
</P>
<P>
   ''Let's just say, it's looking really good,'' said state
Assemblyman Roberto Ramirez, the Bronx County Democratic chairman
who ran the Tuesday night meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was very impressed with his total forthrightness and fervor
in indicating we could come and support him for governor,'' said
state Sen. Neil Breslin of Albany, another meeting attendee. ''He
will be a wonderful governor.''
</P>
<P>
   McCall turned down opportunities to run for governor in 1998 and
for the U.S. Senate this year.
</P>
<P>
   In his second, four-year term as comptroller, McCall has an
impressive resume. An ordained minister, he has served in the state
Senate and as a deputy U.S. ambassador to the United Nations. He
was a Citibank vice president and president of the New York City
Board of Education before becoming comptroller.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
