<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Out-of-state teachers can work in N.Y. without certification  </HEADLINE>
By JESSE J. HOLLAND, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Teachers that have been approved to teach by
39 states can now teach in New York for two years before being
forced to pass the state's certification test, the state Board of
Regents has decided.
</P>
<P>
   About 54,000 teachers in New York City alone will retire over
the next five years, officials say. To help replace those teachers,
the state Education Department can grant a two-year provisional
certification to licensed teachers who move to New York from an
approved state or to those who have a national teaching
certificate.
</P>
<P>
   However, the teacher must pass the New York certification exam
within the two years to continue teaching, the Regents decided last
week.
</P>
<P>
   The plan is expected to entice teachers from more states to
think about working in New York, Education Department spokesman
Alan Ray said.
</P>
<P>
   New York already has a similar agreement in place with Rhode
Island, Massachusetts, Maine, Vermont, New Hampshire, Connecticut,
Pennsylvania and the District of Columbia. Thirty-one other states
will be added in under the new rule, said Charles Mackey, executive
coordinator of the Education Department's office of teaching.
</P>
<P>
   ''This program gives credence to the standards adopted for
teachers in those other states,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Only teachers who are licensed by the states that have signed an
interstate agreement that defines some of the qualifications that
are necessary to obtain a teaching license can participate. Also,
teachers who are licensed in any state and have a certificate from
the National Board of Professional Teaching Standards will be
eligible for the New York program.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the certification program, New York will soon
begin giving its certification test in other states to lure
teachers here, Mackey said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Right now, our tests are only administered in New York but in
the future we're expanding to other states like California and
Texas,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, uncertified New York teachers have one year to pass
the certification exam, although the state does sometimes allow
teachers in high-need districts like New York City to teach longer
with a temporary certificate. About 10,000 New York City teachers
are unlicensed.
</P>
<P>
   A new state law bans the hiring of unlicensed teachers starting
in 2003, however.
</P>
<P>
   The leader of New York City's teachers' union says the new
measure won't help unless lawmakers raise teacher pay in the city
to match the salaries of suburban teachers. ''It might help open up
the supply a bit, but it's a baby step,'' Randi Weingarten,
president of the United Federation of Teachers, told The New York
Times.
</P>
<P>
   The states that are not part of the certification agreement are
Alaska, Iowa, Kansas, Minnesota, Missouri, Nebraska, North Dakota,
South Dakota, Wisconsin and Wyoming.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have not found the standards in those states to be
compatible with those in New York at this time,'' Mackey said.
</P>
<P>
   The list of states allowed in the program will be reviewed every
five years, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-16-00 0019 </TRAILER>
