<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 00:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bruno 'disappointed' Pataki didn't give him heads-up  </HEADLINE>
By JESSE J. HOLLAND, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Senate Republican Leader Joseph Bruno says
his chamber will pass its own gun plan instead of GOP Gov. George
Pataki's nationally touted plan.
</P>
<P>
   This comes after Pataki unveiled his gun-control package without
briefing Bruno beforehand.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not angry. Why would I be angry? I mean, he briefed
everybody except me,'' a sarcastic Bruno said at a news conference
surrounded by Republican senators. ''Now, you think that disturbs
me? I appreciate his consideration knowing how busy I was ... and
he knew that I'd hear about it because I watch TV.''
</P>
<P>
   Pataki told ABC in a newscast aired Tuesday night that he would
propose a gun bill including mandatory trigger locks and the taking
of ballistic ''fingerprints'' by manufacturers of all firearms
marketed here.
</P>
<P>
   The package also calls for the minimum age for handgun purchases
in New York to go from 18 to 21, for a ban on assault weapons and
for instant background checks to be made of gun buyers at flea
markets and gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   Bruno said Wednesday his Republican majority will pass its own
gun bills next week, which includes a mandatory trigger lock plan
and a ban on assault weapons. ''We haven't seen a bill or a press
release'' from Pataki, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki spokesman Michael McKeon said the ''normal process'' was
followed with the gun proposal: the governor's office contacted the
lawyers in both the Assembly and the Senate Tuesday about the
impending announcement and there were conversations going between
all three camps all day.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're pleased that the Senate Republicans are going to give
serious consideration to Governor Pataki's comprehensive plan to
attack gun violence,'' he said. ''We look forward to getting
bipartisan support from the Legislature and signing that bill into
law this session.''
</P>
<P>
   When pressed about why Bruno wasn't personally called, McKeon
said: ''I'm not going to get bogged down ... that's my answer.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruno and Pataki are state government's most powerful
Republicans and have been allied for years on tax cuts, anti-crime
bills and other legislation.
</P>
<P>
   But Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver, a Democrat usually at odds
with Pataki, said the governor personally called him Tuesday to
inform him of the impending gun control announcement.
</P>
<P>
   ''Welcome aboard, Governor,'' Silver said Wednesday. ''Now get
your colleagues in the Senate, your Republican cohorts, to stop
being the poster boys for the NRA.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruno said Pataki talked to him twice Tuesday but never
mentioned his plans.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would have thought that the governor would have had a
conversation with some of us, with me, and just at least give us a
heads up,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Since late January, Pataki and Bruno have been fighting over
whether the state should pick up the counties' share of a new
health insurance program, plus other policy issues and perceived or
actual slights.
</P>
<P>
   Most dramatically, those slights included the firing of at least
three Bruno-sponsored state workers in the Pataki administration in
an action widely interpreted by Bruno's members as a show of
gubernatorial displeasure in Senate Republicans. GOP senators also
said the governor contacted them directly to ask about Senate
politics, instead of going through Bruno.
</P>
<P>
   The gun issue becomes especially sensitive for Bruno considering
the rash of highly-publicized shootings around the nation and the
fact that the entire Legislature is up for re-election in November.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki's plan has been supported in the past in some form by the
Democrat-dominated state Assembly but the Republican-led Senate,
despite proposals from some of its majority members from New York
City and its suburbs, has not approved any of the anti-gun
measures.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki would not be up for re-election until 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ''Now, what I am is disappointed,'' Bruno said. ''I'm
disappointed in my friend, my colleague, former senator, colleague
and friend to everyone that's here.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruno said he and Pataki had ''partnered ... through thick and
thin -- a lot of thin.''
</P>
<P>
   This also comes during the time of year when Pataki and Bruno
try to reconcile their state budget agendas for the next fiscal
year in hopes of being allied in negotiations against the
Democratic state Assembly, though in current years that has not
always happened.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
