<HEADLINE> Giuliani tells business leaders he will take personal hand inupstate economy  </HEADLINE>
By WILLIAM KATES, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) -- Keeping upstate New Yorkers working would
be a ''personal challenge,'' Rudolph Guiliani told a group of
business leaders as he courted their votes for his U.S. Senate run.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani described how he revitalized New York City and what he
would do to help the upstate region share in the downstate's
prosperity as he delivered the keynote address Wednesday night at
the Greater Syracuse Chamber of Commerce's annual dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani told an audience of more than 700 that he not only
would work for lower taxes and less government regulation, but also
would take a personal hand in bringing and keeping jobs in the
region.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would negotiate with businesses directly,'' Giuliani said in
a 30-minute speech. ''Sitting down and talking with them to solve
their problems, fighting to keep them in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said New York City's success in lowering crime, welfare
and increasing jobs could be a model for other communities in New
York. The biggest step in that success was cutting the city's taxes
by $2.3 billion, the Republican mayor said.
</P>
<P>
   ''What we did was give you your money back so you had the
freedom to decide how it would be spent. And that has a tremendous
impact on the economy, particularly in a situation like we have
with an overtaxed economy and overtaxed state,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Among his first tasks, Giuliani told his listeners, would be
reducing the $15 billion disparity in the amount of tax money New
York sends to the federal government and the amount it receives
back.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are subsidizing other parts of America. Well, OK, we're
bigger. We are per capita richer. However, we also need an
appropriate equitable share to help all the communities of New York
... who need more resurgence, who need more assistance in their
economy,'' Giuliani said.
</P>
<P>
   ''A reduction in income tax, a reduction in other forms of
general taxation, will mean more money in the economy here in
central New York. Money for businesses to grow. For businesses to
invest more in expansion,'' Giuliani said.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani also again criticized the Clinton administration for
not doing enough to curb the skyrocketing fuel prices being endured
across the nation, an escalation he said was fostered by Clinton's
lack of a ''focused, determined foreign policy'' and reluctance to
stand up against OPEC. Giuliani repeated his call for the
administration to release oil from the nation's reserves to push
prices back down.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani was scheduled to return to Syracuse again Saturday to
march along side Mayor Roy Bernardi in the city's annual St.
Patrick's Day Parade.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Rodham Clinton also was tentatively scheduled to take
part in the parade but had to drop out because of a conflicting
commitment. The first lady spent last Friday campaigning in
Cortland and Ithaca and already has made more campaign swings
through upstate New York than Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   ''He needs to really concentrate on upstate. He knows he needs
to get into the upstate area, and at least spend as much time here
as Hillary Clinton,'' observed Bernardi, a fellow Republican.
</P>
<P>
   ''People here like to be able to talk to you, to see you in
their diner, see you at their chicken barbecue. You can't do it
from afar,'' Bernardi said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
