<HEADLINE> Gov.'s Alleged Payoff Not in Video  </HEADLINE>
By NATALIE GOTT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) -- A videotape secretly taken inside the
office of former Gov. Edwin Edwards was played at his racketeering
trial on Wednesday, showing a former U.S. congressman handling cash
while Edwards talked about deals for casino licenses.
</P>
<P>
   But the tape fell short of an earlier prosecution claim that it
showed Edwards actually making a payoff.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors showed the tape of Edwards with Cleo Fields as they
continued pressing their claim that the former governor extorted
$400,000 from former San Francisco 49ers owner Edward DeBartolo Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Fields, also a former member of the Louisiana House and now a
state senator, is not charged and held no office when the tape was
made in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards, his son Stephen, state Sen. Greg Tarver and four others
have been on trial in federal court since Jan. 10.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors claim the men took part in a series of bribery and
extortion schemes aimed at manipulating the licensing of casino
riverboats during and after Edwards' fourth and final term, which
ended in January 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The tape was long awaited, but its link to the DeBartolo license
was not immediately clear. And it failed to show everything
prosecutors had earlier claimed.
</P>
<P>
   In January opening statements, they said the tape showed Edwards
handing a bundle of cash to Fields. However, the camera the FBI had
hidden in Edwards' private office was not running when Edwards
allegedly handed over the money.
</P>
<P>
   An agent monitoring the meeting neglected to turn on the camera
until after the meeting had begun, according to testimony.
</P>
<P>
   A later portion of the tape shows Edwards telling Fields that
people he is working with ''are claiming that offer they made was
contingent on getting a license,'' and shows Fields fishing a
bundle of cash out of his pocket.
</P>
</TEXT>
