<HEADLINE> Study: EMF, Suicide Risk Linked  </HEADLINE>
By RANDALL CHASE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) -- Chronic exposure to low-frequency
electromagnetic fields may be responsible for a higher suicide risk
among electric utility workers, according to a new study.
</P>
<P>
   While unable to prove that exposure causes suicide, researchers
at the University of North Carolina found electricians for five
U.S. power companies had twice the suicide rate and linemen 1{
times the rate of utility workers not employed in those jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The findings appeared Wednesday in the April issue of
Occupational and Environmental Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers studied about 6,000 men who were part of a
larger group of about 139,000 employed as utility workers between
1950 and 1986. Research involving the larger study group has shown
that some workers exposed to high magnetic fields have elevated
cancer rates, but not that EMF exposure causes cancer.
</P>
<P>
   One explanation for the possible link between exposure and
suicide is that electromagnetic fields are thought to suppress
melatonin levels in the body, said Edwin van Wijngaarden, a
doctoral student and lead author of the UNC study.
</P>
<P>
   ''The EMF-cancer link is pretty controversial,'' van Wijngaarden
said. ''This may also be controversial, but at least there is a
more plausible biological mechanism involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Melatonin, a hormone produced by the pineal gland deep in the
brain, is thought to play a key role in a person's sleep cycle and
mood.
</P>
<P>
   ''There does seem to be a link between melatonin levels and
depression,'' said study co-author David Savitz, a professor and
chair of epidemiology at UNC.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers said it isn't known exactly how electromagnetic
fields might inhibit melatonin production.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Kripke, a California researcher who has studied the
relationship between EMFs in the home and melatonin levels, said he
had not seen the UNC study but questioned the role that melatonin
might play.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is an area where there is a lot of speculation,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   A 1996 study by Canadian researchers found no link between
suicide and EMF exposure. But Savitz said the UNC study was
significantly larger than the Canadian study of workers at a Quebec
utility company.
</P>
<P>
   Van Wijngaarden said the results of the study may not be
applicable to the general population because the study group was so
selective.
</P>
<P>
   UNC researchers looked at data compiled over several years from
employees of Carolina Power &AMP; Light Co., Pacific Gas &AMP; Electric,
PECO Energy Co. (formerly Philadelphia Electric Co.), Virginia
Electric Power Co. and the Tennessee Valley Authority.
</P>
<P>
   Van Wijngaarden and his colleagues found 536 suicides among the
group between 1950 and 1986 and compared them to a control group of
5,348 non-suicides of the same race and age.
</P>
<P>
   Suicide is the eighth leading cause of death in the United
States; 30,000 people took their lives in 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-16-00 0116 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000316.0015 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 01:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Drug May Help Kids With Arthritis  </HEADLINE>
By JEFF DONN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   A genetically engineered drug works well in fighting children's
arthritis, according to a new study that promises the biggest leap
in drug therapy in more than a decade for the sometimes disabling
ailment.
</P>
<P>
   The study, published in today's New England Journal of Medicine,
was funded in part by the drug's manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   Roughly 100,000 American children suffer from the stiff joints
of juvenile rheumatoid arthritis. At least 20,000 -- and possibly
many more -- would appear to be good candidates for the new drug,
known as etanercept or by the brand name Enbrel, doctors said.
</P>
<P>
   The results suggest a long-awaited alternative for children who
don't respond to the widely used drug methotrexate, which has been
given to children for more than 10 years. Though the older drug
helps about two-thirds of children, there have been few good
choices for the rest.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's where etanercept saves the day,'' said Dr. Daniel
Lovell of Children's Hospital Medical Center in Cincinnati, the
lead author of the study.
</P>
<P>
   The research was carried out at nine institutions. Some funding
for the research came from the drug's manufacturer, Immunex Corp.
of Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   In the tests on 51 children over seven months, the new drug
appeared to control the disease for 72 percent of the patients.
Given in twice-weekly injections, it had limited side effects, the
researchers said. Though the study included only children with
inflammation in at least five joints, the drug also may work for
other types of juvenile rheumatoid arthritis.
</P>
<P>
   Partly on the strength of the study's unpublished results, the
U.S. Food and Drug Administration approved children's use of
etanercept a year ago, and some doctors have been prescribing it.
It already had been approved for adults.
</P>
<P>
   The drug is helping to spur the development of a new class of
drugs that work by binding to tumor necrosis factor, neutralizing
this hormone-like substance that promotes inflammation in human
cells. Such drugs hold promise for a range of conditions, such as
psoriasis and congestive heart failure.
</P>
<P>
   However, the new drugs are expensive. Lovell said a child's
annual treatment would cost $3,000 to $12,000, though health
insurers are generally covering the therapy to some degree.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. David Pisetsky of Duke University Medical Center cautioned
in an editorial in the journal that, ''The new era of better
treatment for arthritis will not be realized until society's
solutions to issues of cost, access, and reimbursement match the
beauty of the science.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. David Fox of the University of Michigan said that while
etanercept appears to hold great promise, some doctors are awaiting
results from longer term studies.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Journal site: www.nejm.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-16-00 0117 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000316.0016 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 01:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Easton to get free gun locks in program sponsored by gun industry  </HEADLINE>
By DENISE LAVOIE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   EASTON, Conn. (AP) -- Easton police will hand out free gun locks
as part of a national gun safety program sponsored by a sports
foundation that represents leading gun manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty cities and towns across the country are already
participating in ''Project Home Safe,'' sponsored by the National
Shooting Sports Foundation, a Newtown-based trade group
representing about 1,800 gun, munitions and accessory
manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   Under the program, cable locks are distributed by police
departments or local government officials.
</P>
<P>
   The locks, which resemble bicycle cable locks, are pulled
through gun handles or barrels to prevent the weapon from firing.
When the lock is in place, the gun cannot be loaded or fired. They
differ from trigger locks, which keep the trigger from being
pulled, but can remain loaded while the lock is in place.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Painter, executive director of the sports foundation, said
the program is aimed at homeowners who buy guns for protection and
do not have the kind of safety training that many hunters and sport
shooters do.
</P>
<P>
   Painter said he began developing the program in 1998, about a
year before more than 20 cities across the country began filing
lawsuits against the gun industry seeking to force manufacturers to
provide effective safety devices with their guns.
</P>
<P>
   ''This has nothing to do with public relations,'' he said. ''It
has to do with a substantial and very real issue of addressing
public safety.''
</P>
<P>
   The program started in September in five pilot cities, including
Las Vegas, Pittsburgh, Orlando, Fla., Augusta, Ga., and Oakland,
Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Another 90 cities and towns are ready to begin this summer,
Painter said. So far, 50,000 locks have been distributed. Painter
said the group hopes to distribute one million locks over the next
three years.
</P>
<P>
   Easton Police Chief John Solomon said police have invited local
gun owners to attend a meeting at the public library Tuesday
evening, when officers will hand out the locks and demonstrate how
to use them.
</P>
<P>
   ''For every one of those safety locks that goes into a residence
in this town, that's one less possibility of a tragedy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cromwell police Chief Anthony Salvatore, the newly elected
president of the Connecticut Police Chiefs Association, said he
expects other communities to join the program. Salvatore dismissed
complaints by critics who say the cable locks -- because they take
time to unlock -- would slow down a homeowner trying to protect
himself from an intruder.
</P>
<P>
   ''The chances of a child getting hold of a gun and accidentally
firing the weapon are far greater than you having to confront an
intruder in your house,'' Salvatore said.
</P>
<P>
   Easton is not the first community in the state to hand out free
gun locks.
</P>
<P>
   Bridgeport has handed out hundreds of free trigger locks over
the last year. The city was one of more than two dozen communities
across the country to file lawsuits against the gun industry.
Bridgeport's suit was thrown out by a judge in December, but city
officials have promised to appeal.
</P>
<P>
   What is unusual about the Easton program is that it is sponsored
by a group representing the gun industry.
</P>
<P>
   Painter said the gun industry has been promoting safety for more
than 100 years.
</P>
<P>
   Some gun manufacturers already ship locks with new guns.
</P>
<P>
   Fairfield-based Sturm, Ruger ships its pistols and revolvers in
lock boxes with padlocks. Exeter, N.H.,-based Sigarms Corp. ships
its guns with trigger locks.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Duby, a spokesman for Bridgeport Mayor Joseph P. Ganim,
called the sports foundation's gun lock program ''laudable,'' but
said it is long overdue.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's just maybe an indication that the gun industry is
beginning to get it,'' Duby said. ''The fundamentals of gun safety
require that trigger locks or other locks be used.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-16-00 0120 </TRAILER>
