<HEADLINE> High court upholds firing of prison guard  </HEADLINE>
By DONNA TOMMELLEO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Sen. Alvin Penn is ready to forgive. But
he won't forget.
</P>
<P>
   The Bridgeport Democrat, who is black, drew the wrath of a
former state prison guard who left a barrage of vulgarities and
racial slurs on Penn's voice mail during a bitter 1997 debate over
a labor contract for corrections officers.
</P>
<P>
   Guard Gregory Frederick was arrested for second-degree
harassment and fired over the incident. An arbitrator's ruling in
April, 1998 reinstated him with back pay. The state fought the
ruling and won. But Frederick's union, Council 4 of the American
Federation of State, County and Municipal Employees, took the
matter to the state Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the high court unanimously ruled that Frederick's
firing was warranted.
</P>
<P>
   ''As a Christian and a human being, I forgive him,'' said Penn.
''But as a senator, I have an obligation to make sure he's not back
in there doing any more detrimental harm to young minds.''
</P>
<P>
   Frederick worked at the John R. Manson Youth Center in Cheshire,
and was calling from work when he placed the obscenity-laced call.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was very concerned and am still concerned about that type of
behavior coming from someone who is dealing with juveniles who are
incarcerated and are looking for rehabilitation and guidance,''
said Penn.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court's decision comes nearly two years after
Frederick was ordered reinstated by the state Board of Mediation
and Arbitration, which ruled the message was ''rampant'' with
vulgarities but not ''hate-filled words.''
</P>
<P>
   The high court, in a 5-0 ruling, strongly disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is hard to imagine a more repugnant message than that left
by the employee,'' wrote Senior Justice Ellen A. Peters. ''The fact
that this egregious misconduct ... occurred while the employee was
on the job distinguishes it from other cases of employee misconduct
in which courts have upheld arbitral awards that reduced
sanctions.''
</P>
<P>
   Frederick admitted making the call from the prison to Penn's
voice mail on May 15, 1997 after Penn helped squelch new contracts
for prison guards in a vote before the General Assembly. The
message was left anonymously, but Frederick admitted to
investigators the next day that he made the call.
</P>
<P>
   Penn said the ruling sends the proper message to the rest of the
state that such matters are taken seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ''I had seen nothing in his behavior which would indicate to me
that he was sorry other than for the fact that he was sorry that he
got caught,'' said Penn. ''I'm glad he's out.''
</P>
<P>
   The arbitrator's ruling, said the justices, violated a
well-defined state policy that warrants the firing of state workers
who break the law and regulations of the Department of Correction.
</P>
<P>
   Frederick was granted a special form of probation on the
harassment charge. Under the terms of his accelerated
rehabilitation he was ordered to serve two years probation and 300
hours of community service.
</P>
<P>
   The court also noted the arbitrator tried to excuse Frederick's
behavior because of stress due to personal problems. His older
daughter had been diagnosed with diabetes and his wife was
experiencing complications in a pregnancy around the same time the
Senate rejected the contract.
</P>
<P>
   ''A lesser sanction ... would, very simply, send the message
that stress, or poor judgment, or other factors, somehow renders
the conduct permissible or excusable,'' wrote Justice Flemming
Norcutt Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Frederick could not be reached for comment. There is no
telephone listing for him in Cheshire. Calls to the union seeking
comment on the case were not returned.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-16-00 0120 </TRAILER>
