<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lawmakers get first glance of Adriaen's Landing legislation  </HEADLINE>
By ADAM GORLICK, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- House Speaker Moira Lyons says it's too
early to tell how much support there is for Gov. John G. Rowland's
plan to spend $455 million of state money on the Adriaen's Landing
development project in downtown Hartford and a 40,000-seat football
stadium in East Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   After scanning a 45-page preliminary spending bill for the first
time on Wednesday, Lyons said her colleagues need some time to
digest the fine print.
</P>
<P>
   ''We want the opportunity to read the bill carefully, and after
that we will probably have (state agency officials) come in and
address our additional questions,'' said Lyons, D-Stamford.
</P>
<P>
   Lyons said she expects a public hearing to be held on the bill
March 30. A vote in the House would come by mid-April, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader George Jepsen said he senses support for
the plan in his caucus, something Rowland is banking on.
</P>
<P>
   ''There really isn't any organized opposition,'' Rowland said.
''There will be people who say maybe the stadium should be in
Storrs, or maybe it should be facing north instead of south. But
these are small issues in the scheme of things.''
</P>
<P>
   But some lawmakers are focused on what they call bigger
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Edith Prague, D-Columbia, doesn't like the current proposal
any more than the plan to build the Patriots a stadium. Prague said
the General Assembly is rushing into spending too much money
without enough consideration of the plan.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think this is a good expenditure of taxpayer money and
I'm not going to vote for it,'' Prague said. ''I know the governor
is going to be clubbing people over the head to get the votes ...
but I don't think this is any better for Hartford than the
(Patriots) stadium was.''
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature is being asked to commit $455 million in public
funds to the development, on the condition that at least $210
million in private investment can be raised.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland has said the project has drawn about $295 million in
private corporate commitments.
</P>
<P>
   The project includes a 700-room hotel, a convention center,
260,000 square feet of entertainment and retail space and nearly
400 housing units. About 3,400 construction jobs and more than
1,100 permanent jobs are expected to be created.
</P>
<P>
   The Adriaen's Landing plan has morphed since first proposed two
years ago when it expected to revolve around a football stadium for
the New England Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   When the Patriots backed out of the deal last year, there was
talk of building a domed stadium on the site to house the
University of Connecticut's football program.
</P>
<P>
   But plans changed again when United Technologies Corp. donated
its 75-acre Rentschler Field in East Hartford for the UConn
stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The school is upgrading from Division I-AA to Division I-A and
needs at least a 35,000-seat stadium to make the transition.
</P>
</TEXT>
