<HEADLINE> Sale, possession of so-called party or date-rape drug now a felonyin Conn.  </HEADLINE>
By NATASHA GURAL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- The death of an East Lyme man blamed on a
mix of alcohol and GHB has prompted the state to make it a felony
to sell or possess the party or date-rape drug.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature this week approved an amendment placing gamma
hydroxy butyrate and similar chemical substances on the state's
roster of permanently controlled substances.
</P>
<P>
   ''It basically gives the local police departments a tool to help
control this problem,'' said Leo Roberge, director of the Drug
Control Division of the state Department of Consumer Protection.
''It isn't a huge problem here, but we've had a couple of problems
in Connecticut including the fatality.''
</P>
<P>
   The state medical examiner's office concluded that Andrew W.
Hayes of East Lyme died of the effects of combining GHB with
alcohol after a night of drinking with friends on April 4, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The state's action comes a month after President Clinton signed
legislation toughening federal laws against possessing, making or
distributing GHB. The bill is named for two teen-agers who died
after GHB was slipped into their soft drinks -- Hillory J. Farias of
Texas and 15-year-old Samantha Reid of Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, three young men were convicted in Michigan of
involuntary manslaughter in the GHB death of Reid. A fourth was
convicted of a lesser charge.
</P>
<P>
   The state Department of Consumer Protection took unprecedented
action in August, classifying GHB and similar chemical substances
as Schedule IV controlled drugs.
</P>
<P>
   GHB, when mixed into a drink can render a victim unconscious
within 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Previously sold as dietary supplements, GHB and its chemical
archetype GBL (gamma butyolactone), have gained popularity among
young people because they provide the relaxed, uninhibited feeling
of a few drinks but faster and cheaper.
</P>
<P>
   Usually sold as a colorless and odorless liquid but sometimes as
a powder, GHB can also cause vomiting, sudden comas and seizures.
First developed in Europe as a surgical anesthetic, it depresses
breathing.
</P>
<P>
   The first state case of GHB-related illness was reported to the
Connecticut Poison Control Center at the University of Connecticut
Health Center in 1996. At least seven young people were treated in
two days at Connecticut hospitals after ingesting GHB during the
second week of June.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, GHB has been linked to at least 58 deaths since 1990
and more than 5,700 recorded overdoses, according to the Drug
Enforcement Administration.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-16-00 0120 </TRAILER>
