<HEADLINE> Truckers To Protest in D.C.  </HEADLINE>
By DERRILL HOLLY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- For the second time in less than a month,
independent truckers, seeking relief from fuel prices that have
more than doubled in the past year, plan to converge on the
nation's capital.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'd like to see some immediate release of money for these
truckers,'' said John Grasso, an owner-operator from Hammonton,
N.J., explaining why he was returning to lobby members of Congress
again today.
</P>
<P>
   The National Owner Operators Trucking Association brought 283
truckers here from the northeastern United States on Feb. 22.
</P>
<P>
   The group has obtained permits for up to 2,500 demonstrators at
two sites today, but just five trucks will be allowed on the
Capitol grounds.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're trying to encourage the American public to support our
plight,'' said Thomas Pokrywka, president of the truckers'
organization.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the group plan to park their trailers at various
locations surrounding the National Mall but will still bring
hundreds of tractor cabs into Washington from six different routes
through Maryland and Virginia. They'll travel after morning
rush-hour in hopes of minimizing traffic disruptions, Pokrywka
said.
</P>
<P>
   Truckers contend that diesel prices above $2 a gallon threaten
many truckers livelihoods and will soon force price increases on
food and other merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   ''You could see it as early as this summer,'' said Pokrywka,
adding that owner-operators are pursuing new contracts with
shippers to boost rates and include fuel surcharges to offset their
rising costs.
</P>
<P>
   The truckers' group has found some members of Congress
supportive of their efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ''Costs are threatening to ruin them financially and put them
out of business,'' said Sen. Robert Torricelli, D-N.J., who backs
$100 million in emergency relief for owner-operators in the current
federal budget.
</P>
<P>
   Torricelli and Sen. Ben Nighthorse Campbell, R-Colo., have
introduced a measure that would roll back the 24-cent-per-gallon
federal tax on diesel fuel, retroactive to Jan. 1. The bill would
enable truckers to apply for rebates based upon fuel receipts
detailing their use.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell drove a truck to finance his college education and last
December attended truck driving school to renew his commercial
driver's license.
</P>
<P>
   ''Vacation and tourist spots all over the country are bracing
for a bad summer,'' if prices don't drop, said Rep. J.C. Watts,
R-Okla.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
