<HEADLINE> Kids Charged With Murder Conspiracy  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT TOWNSEND, Wash. (AP) -- A 12-year-old boy and 14-year-old
girl were charged Wednesday with conspiracy to commit murder for
allegedly plotting to shoot their middle school classmates.
</P>
<P>
   Both were charged as juveniles. If they are convicted,
prosecutors will seek to keep them in custody until they are 21.
The standard sentencing range for juveniles convicted of the felony
is 15 to 36 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said they had a note detailing the plan of Paul
Mascho and Jill Martin, written by the girl to another student.
</P>
<P>
   The note said one person would be shot 15 times in the head,
telephone lines would be cut, walkie-talkies would be used and the
shooting would start in the office of Chimacum Middle School,
according to an affidavit filed by sheriff's detective Joe Nole.
</P>
<P>
   The 12-year-old said he came up with the scheme because he was
angry at most of the students and staff, Nole's statement said.
</P>
<P>
   ''As far as we can tell, they wanted to get administration
people in general, one specific juvenile and one classroom,''
prosecutor Michael Haas said. He said it appeared the girl only
planned to participate in cutting telephone lines.
</P>
<P>
   The plan hit a snag when the boy arrived in Tacoma on Feb. 29
with a 14-year-old cousin, planning to enlist five or six of his
cousin's gang-member friends but learning they were all in jail,
Nole said.
</P>
<P>
   Chimacum District Superintendent Mary Lynne Derrington said
security was ''quadrupled'' after the plan was revealed.
</P>
</TEXT>
