<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Aviation Bill Goes To President  </HEADLINE>
By JIM ABRAMS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A $40 billion aviation bill on its way to the
president's desk promises more money for airport construction, more
flights out of major airports and higher local airport passenger
taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The massive bill, which passed the House Wednesday by 319-101,
also seeks to help smaller airports become more competitive,
requires cargo planes to install collision-avoidance systems and
even sets standards for traveling pet safety.
</P>
<P>
   House Transportation Chairman Bud Shuster, R-Pa., said the bill,
which increases spending by more than $10 billion over three years,
will address a crisis where ''our air traffic control systems must
be modernized, single airlines have gained monopolistic supremacy
at many of our large airports and flight delays and customer
complaints are increasing.''
</P>
<P>
   The compromise bill, which easily passed the Senate last week,
won wide support among lawmakers recognizing there must be a major
investment to cope with an expected growth in air passengers from
600 million last year to more than 1 billion by the end of the
decade.
</P>
<P>
   Transportation Secretary Rodney Slater said President Clinton
would sign the bill, which he said would ''expand capacity and
improve the efficiency of the system to meet the air travel needs
of the 21st century.''
</P>
<P>
   But some in Congress grumbled about the sharp increase in
funding, the proposed new flights and the new tax outlined in the
Federal Aviation Administration authorization bill.
</P>
<P>
   Aiming to increase flights to smaller markets, the bill phases
out flight limits at Chicago's O'Hare in 2002 and at New York's
LaGuardia and JFK in 2007. It permits 24 more flights out of
Washington's Reagan National, including 12 beyond the current 1,250
''perimeter rule.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., a Chicago-area lawmaker who for years
has fought the flight increases, said it would ''help create
massive gridlock and delays at O'Hare and across the nation.'' He
said it was ''only a matter of time before this increased jamming
of flights results in a disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   But lawmakers from less populated areas welcomed the change. A
roundtrip ticket from Rochester to Chicago now costs $1,200, said
Rep. Louise Slaughter, D-N.Y. ''The major carriers have a
stranglehold on these slots, effectively preventing low-cost
carriers from entering the market.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill allows airports to raise their passenger taxes, or
''passenger facility charges'' from the current ceiling of $3 to
$4.50 a person, a move which could bring in an extra $700 million a
year for local airport projects.
</P>
<P>
   Shuster insisted it was not a new tax because the local airports
had control over whether to impose it. But any association with tax
increases rankled some Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ''This legislation runs counter to our most basic principles as
Republicans,'' said Rep. John Boehner, R-Ohio, who objected to both
the tax and the increase in spending.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. David Obey of Wisconsin, ranking Democrat on the
Appropriations Committee, said Shuster's ability to corral more
money for aviation meant less money for other programs. An extra $1
billion for aviation, he said, means $1 billion less for cancer
research, special education or renovation of schools.
</P>
<P>
   The House and Senate both passed FAA bills last year, but were
unable to reach a compromise over Shuster's demand that the
Aviation Trust Fund, which takes in some $10 billion a year in user
fees, be separated from the general federal budget and its revenues
be used exclusively for airport projects.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate wouldn't go along but finally agreed to a compromise
where spending on airports every year would at least equal revenues
and interest from the fund.
</P>
<P>
   Also included in the bill are provisions to help airlines buy
regional jets if they agree to use them to serve small airports,
money to improve the training of airport screeners, requirements
for emergency locator devices on small jets and guidelines for air
tours over national parks.	   The Association of Flight Attendants said the bill
was a victory
for their members because it improves protections for
whistleblowers, increases penalties for unruly passengers and
provides a study of cabin air quality.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR'S NOTE -- The bill is H.R. 1000.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: A summary of the bill:
http://www.house.gov/transportation/air21conf/summary.html
</P>
</TEXT>
