<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Farm Bankruptcy Provision Opposed  </HEADLINE>
By PHILIP BRASHER, AP Farm Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Justice Department says it would be unfair
to let farmers escape paying capital gains taxes when they
reorganize under bankruptcy law.
</P>
<P>
   Under current law, a farmer who sells land or equipment has to
pay up front and in full any income taxes that are due on the
proceeds before settling with other creditors. Lawyers say the
resulting taxes often force farmers to liquidate when they might be
able to stay in operation by downsizing.
</P>
<P>
   A provision in a Senate-approved bankruptcy bill would allow
some or all of the taxes to be discharged as an unsecured debt.
</P>
<P>
   But in a letter this week to House and Senate negotiators, the
Justice Department said ''it would be undesirable to begin creating
exceptions for special interest groups.'' The department said the
law requiring taxes to be paid first is ''intended to deter tax
evasion.''
</P>
<P>
   The legislation would expand a section, known as Chapter 12, of
the bankruptcy code that was created for farmers during an economic
downturn in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's offensive to have the administration dismiss family
farmers in bankruptcy as nothing more than a special interest
group,'' Sen. Charles Grassley, R-Iowa, said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   It's almost pointless for farmers to sell their property if the
government takes a lot of the proceeds, said Grassley, who
co-sponsored the bill's Chapter 12 provisions with Senate
Democratic leader Tom Daschle of South Dakota.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate legislation also would make Chapter 12 a permanent
part of tax law and allow more farms to use it. Unlike Chapter 11
of the bankruptcy code, which applies to corporations, Chapter 12
does not require a farmer to obtain the consent of creditors before
reorganizing.
</P>
<P>
   Chapter 12, which was created in 1986, has twice expired and
been renewed by Congress. It is due to expire June 30 unless
Congress extends it. There have been about 20,000 filings under the
section since it was created.
</P>
<P>
   House and Senate negotiators are trying to reconcile the Senate
bill with a House version that would make Chapter 12 permanent but
wouldn't change it.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The Senate bill is S. 625. The House bill is H.R. 833.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-16-00 0153 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000316.0031 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 01:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thousands of Women To Gather in NY  </HEADLINE>
By EDITH M. LEDERER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Thousands of women from around the world
are coming to New York in June to assess what governments,
businesses and individuals have done to achieve equality of the
sexes since the U.N. women's conference in Beijing five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Beijing conference -- the largest-ever gathering of women --
brought together 6,000 delegates from 189 countries and about
30,000 activists from grass-roots organizations who took part in a
parallel Non-Governmental (NGO) Forum.
</P>
<P>
   How many people the New York gathering will draw is unclear.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are planning for something between 5,000 and 20,000 total,
including the delegations and the NGOs,'' Linda Tarr-Whelan, U.S.
ambassador to the U.N. Commission on the Status of Women, said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Delegates to the meeting -- unofficially known as ''Beijing Plus
Five'' -- will be attending a special session of the U.N. General
Assembly from June 5-9 that will take a critical look at how
governments, the private sector and individuals are tackling the
wide-ranging plan of action adopted in Beijing. A parallel NGO
meeting will start June 2.
</P>
<P>
   The Beijing platform called on governments to revise laws to
ensure women's equal rights and access to credit and employment, to
provide equal education for girls and to ensure the right of women
to decide matters of sexual and reproductive health. It also urged
governments and businesses to put women in top decision-making
positions and called for the elimination of violence against women.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is really about bringing together local and national and
international groups in support of this platform,'' said Ellen
Chesler, coordinator of the host committee.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our plans include a major celebration of the progress women
have made and also a series of forums ... to mark the progress and
hold governments accountable for the historic commitments they
made,'' said Chesler, a senior fellow at The Open Society
Institute, a foundation started by George Soros.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the U.N. Commission on the Status of Women have been
debating a declaration, to be adopted at the General Assembly
session, known as ''Women 2000: Gender Equality, Development and
Peace for the 21st Century.''
</P>
<P>
   ''In talking with other delegations there is some real feeling
that we first have to finish the declaration,'' Tarr-Whelan said.
''A lot of heads of state and ministers will make decisions based
on what it is that we are reaffirming after Beijing.''
</P>
<P>
   Organizers said it was too early to announce participants.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-16-00 0158 </TRAILER>
