<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000316.0032 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 01:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Politics, plots, subplots -- the St. Paddy's Parade  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY McSHANE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- This year, St. Patrick's Day brings more than
the usual legion of bagpipers to Fifth Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   The 239th annual soiree will feature shamrocks and ''Kiss me,
I'm Irish'' buttons. But the real attractions on Friday are the
political plots and subplots that have added an element of intrigue
to the march.
</P>
<P>
   There's Mayor Rudy, who doesn't like first lady Hillary, and
vice versa. There's the Irish Lesbian and Gay Organization, which
has little use for either one. There's Cardinal John O'Connor, who
loves everybody but seems unlikely to appear.
</P>
<P>
   Definitely missing are Sinn Fein honcho Gerry Adams, who will
spend the day in Washington, and several prominent Democrats, who
opted to stay away from the parade despite the first-ever visit
from putative New Yorker Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   It's quite a swing from last year's event, when actress Maureen
O'Hara served as grand marshal for a march that was more
celebration than spectacle.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will march up Fifth Avenue for her first time in the
nation's oldest and largest St. Patrick's Day parade, angering
ILGO, which is excluded from the march. Two weeks earlier, the
Democratic U.S. Senate candidate marched in an inclusive Queens
parade -- but that didn't pacify the Irish-gay group.
</P>
<P>
   ''It doesn't matter where else you march, how many times you
march, or what spin you put on marching -- what matters is
integrity,'' ILGO said in a statement, adding that Clinton's
decision to march brought hers into question.
</P>
<P>
   ILGO, banned from marching under its own banner for the 10th
straight year, planned a massive civil disobedience on Friday
morning. The group predicted that 2,000 protesters, including a
contingent from Ireland, would demonstrate on Fifth Avenue about 90
minutes before the official march, which is run by the Ancient
Order of Hibernians.
</P>
<P>
   ILGO somewhat irrationally blames Mayor Rudolph Giuliani for its
continued exclusion from the parade -- not that it bothers the
mayor. As usual, Giuliani will march near the start of the parade;
what's unusual is that he'll do so as Clinton's likely Republican
opponent in the November election.
</P>
<P>
   The parade marks only their second joint public appearance,
following Saturday's Inner Circle show. Don't expect them to march
arm in arm.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Clinton's debut, some prominent New York Democrats will
not accompany her along the parade route -- although none are saying
it's directly related to the ILGO flap. U.S. Sen. Charles Schumer
says he will not march; city Public Advocate Mark Green will be out
of town.
</P>
<P>
   One other major figure may be missing from this year's parade:
80-year-old Cardinal John O'Connor, a fixture at the last 15
parades, is less than 50-50 to appear on the steps of St. Patrick's
Cathedral for the parade.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor's health has been failing since he underwent brain
surgery in September 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ''Given his current weakness, it's far from certain that he'll
be there,'' said Joe Zwilling, spokesman for the archdiocese. ''But
the cardinal has surprised us before. I don't want to rule him
out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-16-00 0159 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
