<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 02:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Warns Ethnic Albanians in Kosovo  </HEADLINE>
By BARRY SCHWEID, AP Diplomatic Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration, reversing course,
is now warning leaders of ethnic Albanians in Kosovo about
cross-border attacks on Serb police.
</P>
<P>
   They ''are in danger of losing our support'' if provocations
continue, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright told a
congressional panel Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But Albright blamed persecution of Serbs on extremists and said
it did not compare with the Belgrade-directed ethnic cleansing of
Kosovar Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would say that the large majority of Kosovar Albanians are
trying to put their life together -- and this is where the
difference is -- after a systematic government-organized pillaging
by the Milosevic Serbs into Kosovo,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic tried ''to kill and
ethnically cleanse the entire Kosovo-Albanian nation,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the warning was backed up Wednesday by a raid in eastern
Kosovo in which a senior U.S. official says weapons were seized
from Albanians by U.S. peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   ''We do not believe we are drifting toward a conflict with
Kosovar Albanian insurgents,'' State Department spokesman James P.
Rubin said. ''And we are working to limit the influence of
extremists.''
</P>
<P>
   Albanian attacks on Serb police in Kosovo more than a year ago
prompted Milosevic to crack down fiercely on ethnic Albanians.
Hundreds of thousands were expelled from their homes.
</P>
<P>
   American and NATO bombardment of the Serbs forced Milosevic to
retreat, and the province effectively came under Albanian control.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Rubin delivered a stern message to ethnic Albanian
leaders in an effort to head off any attempt to repeat the scenario
across Kosovo's eastern border in Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   ''I believe they understand the seriousness of the situation and
that we are coming at them as a friend,'' Rubin said in an
interview Wednesday after returning from what will likely be his
last diplomatic mission. ''I hope they will do more to prevent
these things from happening.''
</P>
<P>
   Rubin met with Ibrahim Rugova, the president of Kosovo's largest
political party; Hashim Thaci, the former political leader of
Kosovo's rebels; and others.
</P>
<P>
   While current forays against Serbs in the Presevo Valley are on
a smaller scale than the earlier Albanian provocation in Kosovo,
the violence worries the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are determined to police the border and not allow this kind
of cross-border activity,'' Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
   The Kosovo Liberation Army, which spearheaded the rebellion
against Belgrade, ''doesn't want a confrontation'' with the
peacekeeping troops, Rubin said. ''They are very careful of this.''
</P>
<P>
   The Albanians have turned in their heavy weapons, but ''there
are more weapons out there that we are still looking for,'' Rubin
said.
</P>
<P>
   The three-day mission to Kosovo was Rubin's second unusual
assignment for a spokesman. Last June, he met with Thachi in
Macedonia, Kosovo and Albania and helped work out an agreement in
which the ethnic Albanians drew back from their demand for a
postwar army.
</P>
<P>
   His regular appearances on television, briefing reporters at the
State Department, made him well-known to the Albanians and he
apparently has built up their trust in him.
</P>
<P>
   On this week's trip, he made stops in Pristina, the provincial
capital; Kosovoska Mitrovica, where violence flared again
Wednesday; and several villages.
</P>
<P>
   ''There were very warm and emotional moments, with people
thanking America for saving them,'' Rubin said. ''It's very
touching when elderly men kiss your hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Rubin said he told Albanian leaders they were not doing
enough to promote democracy in Kosovo. They understood that the
message -- and ''a stern message to avoid provocation of the Serbs''
-- came from a friend, he said.
</P>
<P>
   At the Pentagon, Air Force spokesman, Lt. Col. Vic Warzinski
said, ''What we are trying to do now is defuse the situation before
it gets out of control.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard N. Haass, director of foreign policy studies at the
Brookings Institution, took a dark view of the situation.
</P>
<P>
   ''We entered Kosovo under the guise of peacemaking, and that
context no longer exists,'' he said in an interview.
''Increasingly, we have to face the challenge of peacemaking, not
peacekeeping.''
</P>
<P>
   Haass said a larger U.S. presence along the border will be
required, ''and giving U.S. troops a more aggressive role to go
after the guerrillas, if need be.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: The State Department's Kosovo site:
http://www.state.gov/www/regions/eur/kosovo--hp.html
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
