<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000316.0038 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 02:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Commuters Search for Cheap Gas  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID PITT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- They're trading in their gas guzzlers for economy
cars. They're driving miles out of their way for cheaper gas
prices. And in some cases, they're not paying at all.
</P>
<P>
   Americans hit with sticker shock at the pumps are finding
solutions -- conventional and unconventional -- to ease the high cost
of filling up their vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's just ridiculous,'' said Bob Swift, 32, a stone mason from
Antioch, Calif., who sold two V8 vehicles and bought a Ford Ranger
''in order to get a gas economizer.''
</P>
<P>
   Vivian Martin drives the seven miles from her home in Eufaula,
Ala., to buy gas in Georgia, where she saves 10 to 15 cents per
gallon because of Georgia's lower gasoline tax.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a lot cheaper,'' she said. ''It's not out of your way
when you want to save a little money.''
</P>
<P>
   The AAA Auto Club said its survey of U.S. gas stations released
Tuesday showed that the average price for a gallon of regular
unleaded gas was $1.54. The main cause is OPEC's decision over the
past two years to cut back on production to raise low prices.
</P>
<P>
   While the oil cartel is expected to boost production later this
month, lower prices aren't expected at American pumps for at least
six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta radio station WSTR was overwhelmed last week by the
response to its promotion offering free gas to the first 94
customers at a local Amoco. Within 30 minutes of the announcement,
more than 200 cars were waiting, said Alan Hennes, the radio
station's operations director.
</P>
<P>
   ''They were driving from 10 miles away to get the gas,'' Hennes
said. ''And it was everybody. You had everything from a Pinto to a
Lexus.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Cattaraugus Indian Reservation in New York, gasoline
business has increased 10 percent in the last two weeks. Gas sells
for $1.29 a gallon on the reservation, where vendors pay only the
federal tax on gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've seen a lot of new faces,'' said Morgan Reid, general
manager of JR's, a reservation convenience store.
</P>
<P>
   At Bruce's Mobil in St. Louis County, Mo., customers were
grumbling Wednesday after the station raised the price of a gallon
of unleaded regular to $1.53 from $1.45.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't like it, either,'' manager Keith Steinrauf said.
''It's not us, it's the people that send us the gas. And the more
the price goes up, the less we make.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackie Harris has a worse problem. As the manager of Bucky's
Amoco in Council Bluffs, Iowa, she said the solution for some
drivers is simply not to pay at all.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're seeing a big problem with drive-offs. People are just
coming in, filling up and driving off,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Winslow, a courier from San Jose, Calif., said he stopped
buying clothes so he could afford to run his classic guzzler, a
1969 Chevrolet Malibu equipped with a new 9.2 liter 350 horsepower
engine.
</P>
<P>
   ''Lately, I've been spending $100 on gas a day,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some commuters have even started simply leaving their cars at
home.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Fulton, a spokesman for the Maryland Mass Transit
Administration, said ridership on light rail and commuter buses has
risen between 3 percent and 7 percent since February.
</P>
<P>
   And the Metropolitan Atlanta Rapid Transit Authority has
experienced two consecutive months of increased usage. Spokesman
Bobby Harper said ridership was up 2.7 percent in January from the
same month a year ago and February figures indicate a 3.2 percent
increase.
</P>
<P>
   ''Two months back to back certainly indicates something is going
on,'' he said. ''You can assume some of those people are saying,
'I'm just going to save some money by taking the train.'''
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: American Automobile Association: http://www.aaa.com
</P>
<P>
   U.S Energy Information Administration: http://www.eia.doe.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
