<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Spat Puts Spotlight on House Race  </HEADLINE>
By JENNIFER LOVEN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   RANTOUL, Ill. (AP) -- Tom Ewing wants to see his son follow in
his footsteps -- right to his seat in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   But Sam Ewing is a political novice who works for an insurance
company, and nearly all the elder Ewing has gained so far is an
ugly public spat with one of his oldest and closest allies, House
Speaker Dennis Hastert.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert has endorsed one of Sam Ewing's rivals in Illinois'
March 21 primary. The speaker called three-term state Rep. Bill
Brady a better bet for Republicans trying to retain control of the
House in the fall election.
</P>
<P>
   The feud has put a national spotlight on a race that would have
been ignored outside the largely rural eastern Illinois district,
where most consider the front-runner to be a third candidate,
veteran state Rep. Tim Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   He is a tireless campaigner who has never been defeated. But
Johnson's lucrative trial law practice and his three divorces make
some conservatives nervous.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP tension began when Tom Ewing appeared to delay
announcing his retirement until after his son had moved back from
Texas. Some saw Ewing's retirement as an annoying distraction for
the party -- and Hastert. And they resented Sam Ewing's
unwillingness to run for a lower office first.
</P>
<P>
   Tongues also wagged at Hastert's decision to get involved when
the district isn't deemed crucial to the GOP's bid to at least hold
their 11-seat House majority. The elder Ewing is one of 23
Republicans retiring this year, compared with only seven Democrats,
and a Democrat hasn't won in his district since 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, two Democrats are competing for the party's
nomination: Laurel Prussing, a former state representative who ran
twice against the elder Ewing, and Mike Kelleher, a former
congressional aide.
</P>
<P>
   While the Hastert-Ewing tiff has been the subject of gossip
within the local party establishment and second-guessing by
Washington insiders, it doesn't appear to be weighing heavily on
voters' minds.
</P>
<P>
   ''It might make a difference to some, but for John Q. Citizen --
I don't think that it matters much,'' said Glenn Stanko, a
Republican running for circuit judge in Champaign. ''It has caused
some hard feelings, but that's normal I guess for a primary.''
</P>
<P>
   The race will probably not be decided by money, though Johnson
had spent the most with three weeks left. The Republicans --
including Jeffrey Jones, a dentist new to politics -- have personal
resources they are willing to use.
</P>
<P>
   The candidates also differ little on the issues, staking out
mostly conservative positions similar to those of the elder Ewing.
They are against abortion and for smaller government, lower taxes,
help for farmers and high-tech development.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing, 29, whose family owns several large farming operations,
touts his familiarity with agricultural and rural issues. He says
his success as a disaster team manager for State Farm Insurance Co.
has provided great training for representative politics.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, he's also hoping to capitalize on his father's
popularity while persuading voters he's able himself.
</P>
<P>
   ''Being Tom Ewing's son is a huge asset for me,'' he said to
diners in Watseka, near the Indiana line. ''But it just gets my
foot in the door. ... I didn't expect this to be handed to me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-16-00 0214 </TRAILER>
