<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mighty Ducks 2, Kings 2  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) -- Bryan Smolinski had his second two-goal
game of the season as the Los Angeles Kings rallied from two goals
down to tie the Anaheim Mighty Ducks 2-2 on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Jamie Storr stopped the last 34 shots he faced -- three during a
power play in overtime -- and finished with 37 saves to help extend
the Kings' unbeaten streak to four games.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Rucchin and Oleg Tverdovsky scored less than five minutes
apart on Anaheim's first two power plays of the game. Goalie Guy
Hebert made 20 saves and extended his unbeaten streak against the
Kings to 6-0-2.
</P>
<P>
   This was be the 10th time the Ducks and Kings have played
overtime in their 7-year-old series, with the Kings holding a 3-1-6
advantage. They have three more meetings scheduled with Anaheim
during the final three weeks of the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings began their comeback just 47 seconds after Tverdovsky
increased Anaheim's lead to 2-0. Nelson Emerson, playing his first
game since being acquired from Atlanta, pinched along the right
boards to keep the puck in the Anaheim zone and fed it behind the
net to Glen Murray, whose centering pass found Smolinski at the
edge of the crease at 9:40 of the first period.
</P>
<P>
   Smolinski, whose entire offensive contribution during the Kings'
previous 13 games consisted of an empty-net goal, tied the score 59
seconds into the second period as he beat Hebert through the pads
with a 35-foot slap shot for his 20th of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Smolinski also had two goals on Jan. 13 in a 3-2 loss to St.
Louis.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks, 18th on power-play conversions, scored on two of
their first three shots against Storr, who had allowed only six
goals on 103 shots in his previous four starts.
</P>
<P>
   After Dan Bylsma was sent off for holding Paul Kariya, Fredrik
Olausson played the puck off the right boards and sent a soft shot
toward the net that Rucchin redirected past Storr at the 4:02 mark
for his 100th NHL goal and 16th of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Tverdovsky got his 13th goal just 19 seconds after Ian
Laperriere went to the penalty box for elbowing Jeff Nielsen. The
Ducks' defenseman was 15 feet from Storr in the left circle when he
converted Teemu Selanne's pass from behind the net.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
