<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 02:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First Dog Death in 2000 Iditarod  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) -- As mushers continued to stream into
Nome, a dog belonging to Michigan musher Al Hardman died Wednesday
in the Iditarod Trail Sled Dog Race, according to a race official.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first dog death of the 1,100-mile race this year.
</P>
<P>
   Race marshal Mark Nordman told radio station KNOM that the dog
died on the trail between Koyuk and Elim. A necropsy was ordered
for the animal and Hardman was allowed to continue in the race,
according to KNOM.
</P>
<P>
   Hardman was in 36th place Wednesday night. As of 9 p.m., 24
mushers had crossed the finish line.
</P>
<P>
   Defending champion Doug Swingley of Lincoln, Mont., claimed his
third Iditarod victory Tuesday morning. He finished in a record 9
days and 58 minutes to best his own 1995 record of 9 days, 2 hours
and 42 minutes. Ramy Brooks of Healy crossed the finish line about
five hours later to claim second place.
</P>
<P>
   A record 81 teams began the race, which had its ceremonial start
in Anchorage on March 4. By 9 p.m. Wednesday, 45 teams remained on
the trail.
</P>
</TEXT>
