<HEADLINE> Dollar Slips, Japan Stocks Rebound  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo share prices rebounded Thursday as traders
looked for bargains in technology stocks and other issues sold
heavily in recent sessions. The dollar fell against the yen.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar bought 105.72 yen in early afternoon trading, down
0.34 yen from late Wednesday but above its overnight level of
105.57 yen late in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average rose 174.63, or
0.92 percent, to 19,253.23. On Wednesday, the average closed down
63.24 points, or 0.33 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In Toyko currency dealings, the dollar slipped as domestic
investors and exporters converted their overseas assets into yen
ahead of the end of the Japanese fiscal year on March 31.
</P>
<P>
   ''Repatriation will create a glut of dollars,'' said Shuji
Takano, assistant manager of foreign exchange at ABN AMRO Bank.
''It's getting harder for the dollar to stay above 105 yen.''
</P>
<P>
   The market shrugged off threats by government officials to
intensify their campaign to weaken the yen.
</P>
<P>
   Traders estimated Japan's central bank on Wednesday bought as
much as dlrs 3 billion in an attempt to bring down the yen -- its
second intervention in a week.
</P>
<P>
   Zembei Mizoguchi, the head of the international bureau at
Japan's Finance Ministry, said Thursday that the ministry would
take ''appropriate measures'' if needed to counter a sudden rise by
the yen.
</P>
<P>
   A rising yen cuts into the value of Japanese exporters' earnings
in dollars, and in some cases makes their products more expensive
for overseas customers.
</P>
<P>
   In other currencies, the euro traded at 102.42 yen, down
marginally from 102.46 yen late Wednesday in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   On the stock market, the Nikkei index rebounded midway through
the session.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street provided some encouragement. In New York overnight,
the Dow Jones industrials soared 320.17 points, or 3.3 percent, to
10,131.41.
</P>
<P>
   But the technology-rich Nasdaq composite index remained a
concern. It dropped 124.01 points on Wednesday to end at 4,582.62,
bringing its loss for the past three days to 9.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Financial markets in Japan will be closed Monday for a national
holiday.
</P>
<P>
   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the
first section closed up 40.14 points, or 2.5 percent, at 1,654.47.
The TOPIX closed up 23.46 points, or 1.41 percent, the day before.
</P>
<P>
   The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond rose
to 1.8300 percent from Wednesday's finish of 1.8100 percent. Its
price fell 0.17 points to 99.74.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
