<HEADLINE> Grand Jury Indicts Man Using DNA  </HEADLINE>
By SAMUEL MAULL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Police may not know the name of the East Side
rapist, what he looks like or where to find him. But they say they
have his genetic profile and have indicted him for three attacks.
</P>
<P>
   District Attorney Robert Morgenthau said the indictment was
filed four days before the five-year statute of limitations lapsed
for the first attack.
</P>
<P>
   Morgenthau said the rapist has attacked at least 16 women, the
last on Sept. 15, 1998. The indictment cites two rapes in 1995 and
another in 1997, but Morgenthau said the rapist's DNA was collected
at four rape sites and he expects at least one more charge will be
filed.
</P>
<P>
   ''Although this is New York state's first grand jury indictment
of a 'John Doe' identified by DNA, I am certain it will not be the
last,'' he said Wednesday. He said his office is reviewing hundreds
of open cases that DNA technology might help solve.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Thompson, Morgenthau's spokeswoman, said she knew of two
states, Wisconsin and Utah, in which the DNA profile of a ''John
Doe'' was used to get arrest warrants. She said she knows of no
state other than New York in which a DNA profile has been used to
obtain an indictment.
</P>
<P>
   A ''John Doe'' indictment is legal if it contains a sufficient
description of the suspect, said H. Richard Uviller, a Columbia
University Law School professor.
</P>
<P>
   ''DNA certainly fits that bill,'' Uviller said about the
''genetic fingerprint,'' as it is called. ''You can change your
name, physical features, but you can't change your DNA.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
