<HEADLINE> Former Jaycees head wanted on sexual assault charges  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   MIDDLETOWN, Conn. (AP) -- A man who resigned as president of the
Greater Hartford Jaycees last week after registering with police as
a convicted sex offender will be charged with new counts of sexual
assault and kidnapping, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Robert L. Walker, 31, is accused of repeatedly raping his
ex-girlfriend after they broke up, The Hartford Courant reported
today, citing police sources it did not identify.
</P>
<P>
   A Superior Court judge signed an arrest warrant March 9, the day
after Walker resigned from the community service organization best
known for running the Canon Greater Hartford Open golf tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Walker will be charged with four counts of aggravated sexual
assault in the first degree, three counts of aggravated kidnapping
in the first degree, four counts of first-degree sexual assault,
two counts of first-degree kidnapping and threatening.
</P>
<P>
   He allegedly displayed a gun or threatened the use of a weapon,
police sources said, which accounts for the aggravated assault and
kidnapping charges.
</P>
<P>
   When he resigned last week, Walker said he stepped down because
he didn't want media attention to reflect badly on the Jaycees, a
national organization for professionals aged 21 to 39.
</P>
<P>
   Walker has been known to Jaycees as a gifted public speaker and
dedicated leader and was named outstanding local vice president at
last year's national convention.
</P>
<P>
   He was elected president of the 650-member Greater Hartford
chapter in an uncontested race in March 1999 and began his term
Jan. 1 -- becoming chief executive officer of the organization and
its $1 million operating budget.
</P>
<P>
   Walker's leadership was soon called into question when, on Feb.
24, he registered as a convicted sex offender after being contacted
by state police.
</P>
<P>
   Jaycees officials, who knew Walker had a criminal history, did
not know he had been sentenced to nine years in prison in
connection with a March 1989 sexual assault on a flight attendant
at the Ramada Inn near Bradley International Airport.
</P>
</TEXT>
