<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 03:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan To Hasten Pollution Solutions  </HEADLINE>
By ROBERT BURNS, AP Military Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Seeking to remove an irritant in U.S.-Japan
relations, the Japanese government said today it will expedite a
solution to air pollution around an air base where 3,000 U.S.
servicemen and their families live.
</P>
<P>
   The government also pledged to provide temporary off-base
housing to as many as request it while steps are taken to reduce
the level of toxic emissions from the Shinkampo incinerator, a
privately owned plant that sits just outside the gate of Atsugi
Naval Air Facility, about 25 miles west of Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Navy has complained about the pollution for more than
10 years.
</P>
<P>
   To announce the new arrangement, Tsutomu Kawara, chief of the
Japan Defense Agency, read a prepared statement to reporters in
which he said the government agrees that air pollution surrounding
Atsugi is ''a problem affecting the health'' of American as well as
Japanese residents in the area.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Kawara nor U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen, who
appeared with his Japanese counterpart to announce the deal, would
take questions from reporters. Cohen thanked Kawara and Prime
Minister Keizo Obuchi for their personal involvement, and he
lavished praise on the new arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are most appreciative,'' Cohen said. ''This is something
that affects the health and welfare and well-being of not only
American citizens who are at Atsugi but also of Japanese
citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen later paid a courtesy call on the prime minister at his
official residence.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to meeting with Kawara to go over details of the
agreement, Cohen was driven to Atsugi and given a first-hand look
at the plume of emissions from the incinerator. During much of the
year, winds drive the plume -- which contains relatively high levels
of dioxin -- directly into Atsugi housing areas.
</P>
<P>
   ''If it can't be cleaned up then it should be closed down,''
Cohen said at Atsugi, where he also addressed several hundred
sailors and told them he was doing his best to eliminate this
health hazard.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Japan's Environment Agency said the levels of
carcinogenic dioxin were dangerously high near Atsugi, which is
home to the air wing assigned to the USS Kitty Hawk carrier battle
group.
</P>
<P>
   A study conducted last summer by the Japanese government and the
U.S. Navy found dioxin in concentrations 10 times above Japanese
standards, Navy spokesman Lt. Cmdr. James Graybeal said today. He
said the plant's owner has escaped penalty by finding loopholes in
Japan's environmental laws.
</P>
<P>
   The deal as described by Kawara -- and elaborated on by a senior
U.S. official who declined to be identified -- contains five main
elements, starting with Tokyo's promise to expedite the legal and
bureaucratic process of constructing a 300-foot smokestack at the
incinerator to reduce harmful emissions.
</P>
<P>
   No specific deadline was set, but Kawara said Japan would make
sure the smokestack is completed ''expeditiously.''
</P>
<P>
   The four other elements are:
</P>
<P>
   -- A government pledge to make sure that Shinkampo's owner
completes installation of special filters on two of its burners by
the end of March and then shuts down the third burner so it can be
fitted with a filter.
</P>
<P>
   -- A joint U.S.-Japan monitoring plan to survey the ambient air
around the plant for as long as deemed necessary.
</P>
<P>
   -- The government will not object to the U.S. government's
efforts to sue Shinkampo for violation of environmental laws. The
U.S. official told reporters that Washington plans to file such a
suit this spring and would ask the Japanese court for an injunction
to halt the plant's operations in the meantime.
</P>
<P>
   -- The government will provide temporary off-base housing for all
who wish it, at no cost to U.S. personnel. This would be provided
until the 300-foot smokestack is completed.
</P>
<P>
   Together the measures are likely to cost the Japanese government
hundreds of millions of dollars, the U.S. official said. There is
an informal understanding, the official said, that if the measures
announced today fail to eliminate the pollution problem the
government will close down the plant.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen and Kawara also discussed the status of negotiations on a
new five-year agreement under which the government pays part of the
cost of having 47,000 American troops on its soil. Japanese
officials have indicated they may want to reduce the $5 billion a
year that Tokyo pays under the current arrangement, which expires
in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon officials have said they are hopeful of reaching a new
''host nation support'' agreement by this summer, when President
Clinton will travel to Japan for an international summit conference
in Okinawa.
</P>
</TEXT>
