<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 3 a.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Thursday, March 16, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Pakistani Killer To Be Executed
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LAHORE, Pakistan (AP) -- A court on Thursday sentenced Javed Iqbal to death
in the country's worst serial killing, saying he would be strangled in front of
the parents whose children he was convicted of murdering. Iqbal was sentenced to
be publicly executed in a Lahore park for killing as many as 100 children. He
can appeal his conviction and sentence. After he is strangled, Judge Allah Baksh
Ranja said Iqbal's body ''will then be cut into a 100 pieces and put in acid the
same way you killed the children.'' Iqbal told the court he was innocent.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
NASA: Defective Engine Seals Found
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) -- In another embarrassing mix-up for NASA, flawed
engine seals that should have been thrown away are believed to be in space
shuttle Atlantis. It's the second time in a few months that defective seals have
turned up on a space shuttle instead of in the trash. Two seals intended for the
garbage are apparently in one of Atlantis' main engines, chief engineer Len
Worlund said Wednesday. As a result, NASA will replace that engine before the
shuttle blasts off next month with supplies for the international space station.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Truckers To Protest in D.C.
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- For the second time in less than a month, independent
truckers, seeking relief from fuel prices that have more than doubled in the
past year, plan to converge on the nation's capital. The National Owner
Operators Trucking Association brought 283 truckers here from the northeastern
United States on Feb. 22. The group has obtained permits for up to 2,500
demonstrators at two sites Thursday, but just five trucks will be allowed on the
Capitol grounds.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Fossils of Tiny Primates Found
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   Anthropologists have discovered fossils from two species of ''teeny, tiny
primates,'' thumb-sized creatures smaller than any other known primate on the
family tree leading to monkeys, apes and humans. The fossilized foot bones, each
about the size of a grain of rice, were sifted from tons of muddy rubbish at a
limestone mine in eastern China. About 45 million years ago, the fragile
primates lived in a rain forest, feeding on insects and sap. Scientists from
Northern Illinois, Northwestern and Beijing's Chinese Academy of Sciences detail
the species in this week's Journal of Human Evolution.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Study: EMF, Suicide Risk Linked
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) -- Chronic exposure to low-frequency electromagnetic
fields may be responsible for a higher suicide risk among electric utility
workers, according to researchers at the University of North Carolina at Chapel
Hill. While unable to prove that exposure causes suicide, researchers found
electricians for five U.S. power companies had twice the suicide rate and
linemen 1{ times the rate of utility workers not employed in those jobs. The
findings appeared Wednesday in the April issue of Occupational and Environmental
Medicine.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Couple Wins $26M in Ford Case
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- A jury has ordered Ford Motor Co. to pay nearly $26
million to a man whose Bronco truck rolled over on a freeway in 1996, leaving
him quadriplegic. An Alameda Superior Court jury on Tuesday determined Richard
Raimondi and his wife, Dana, had suffered $52 million in damages. But they
awarded them half that amount after finding Mr. Raimondi shared responsibility
with Ford for the accident. Attorneys for Ford said the company would ask a
judge to set aside or reduce the verdict, and would appeal if their efforts
fail.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Man Arrested in Florida Abduction
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   GAINESVILLE, Fla. (AP) -- A 38-year-old man was arrested Wednesday and
charged with the abduction of a 10-year-old girl who was held three days before
being released last week at a Wal-Mart, police said. Alachua County Sheriff's
investigators identified the suspect as James Paul Johnson. Johnson is charged
with one count of kidnapping and one count of kidnapping with special
circumstances. The special circumstances are lewd and lascivious acts against a
child under the age of 13. He also was charged with one count of sexual battery
on a child under the age of 11 years old.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Japanese Stock Prices Rebound
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo share prices rebounded Thursday as traders looked for
bargains in technology stocks and other issues sold heavily in recent sessions.
The Nikkei gained 174.63 points to close at 19,253.23.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Kings 98, Clippers 78
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Chris Webber scored 25 points and had eight
rebounds Wednesday night as the Sacramento Kings cruised past the Los Angeles
Clippers 98-78. Vlade Divac scored 12 points and had 15 rebounds for the Kings.
Rookie Lamar Odom had his third triple-double of the year, getting 21 points, 10
rebounds and 10 assists for the Clippers.
</P>
