<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 03:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> House Committee Passes 2001 Budget  </HEADLINE>
By ALAN FRAM, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- House Republicans are downplaying the
difference between the tax cuts they have put in their fiscal 2001
budget and the deeper reductions advanced by their party's likely
presidential nominee, George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats, looking to drive a wedge between Bush and
congressional Republicans, are criticizing the Texas governor's tax
cut plan as too costly -- and daring GOP lawmakers to support it. On
Wednesday, Republicans eluded a Democratic effort to force a House
Budget Committee vote on whether they would include the Bush
proposal in next year's federal budget.
</P>
<P>
   The maneuvering came as Republicans pushed a $1.82 trillion
budget for next year through the budget panel. On the near
party-line 23-18 vote, only Rep. Mac Collins, R-Ga., defected.
</P>
<P>
   The measure -- a blueprint for fiscal 2001 spending and tax bills
Congress will work on later -- contains about $50 billion more in
tax cuts than President Clinton wants, and less domestic spending.
It would provide $307 billion for next year's defense budget, $1
billion higher than Clinton's plan. Its $290 billion for domestic
programs is nearly $30 billion less than Clinton prefers.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is the wrong approach for America,'' Clinton said in a
written statement.
</P>
<P>
   But the budget also spotlighted the warring political needs of
Bush and GOP lawmakers in this election year.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has made a five-year, $483 billion tax cut a defining issue
of his campaign in a bid to rally conservatives to his cause.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional Republicans would specifically set aside $150
billion for tax cuts, though they would leave room for perhaps $90
billion more. They want to avoid another veto fight with Clinton
and save a major tax-cut push for next year, when they hope Bush
will be president, as well as satisfy internal demands for more
spending for defense and some domestic programs.
</P>
<P>
   The congressional GOP plan covers fiscal 2001 through 2005,
while Bush's would not begin until 2002. House Budget Committee
Chairman John Kasich, R-Ohio, estimated that through 2005, Bush's
package would cost about $300 billion, leaving the two plans in
what he called ''close proximity.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Get us a Republican president'' and we'll fight for tax cuts
as large as Bush's, Kasich said.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, underlining the differences between the two sides, Bush
spokeswoman Mindy Tucker distanced the governor from the House GOP
package.
</P>
<P>
   ''We believe it's possible to meet basic needs, fund priorities
and return money to the taxpayers without increasing spending as
rapidly as this proposal contemplates,'' Tucker said.
</P>
<P>
   She also said Bush ''does recognize the pressure Congress
currently has with a Democrat president who is pressuring them to
spend money on bigger government. That will not be a problem with a
President Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has contrasted himself with the GOP-run Congress before.
Last year, he accused Republicans of trying to ''balance their
budget on the backs of the poor'' with a plan to squeeze savings
from working families collecting the earned income tax credit.
</P>
<P>
   Tucker said the Bush campaign ''has not directed'' congressional
GOP budget-writing efforts in an effort to make their tax cut
larger.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, Kasich fought and lost a battle with House GOP
leaders to include Bush's tax plan in the budget. Sen. Phil Gramm,
R-Texas, is waging that same fight in the Senate Budget Committee,
where Chairman Pete Domenici, R-N.M., plans votes on a budget like
Kasich's next week.
</P>
<P>
   At the budget committee, Rep. Jim McDermott, D-Wash., tried
forcing the budget committee to vote on whether to accept Bush's
tax cuts in full. He said it is so expensive that it would erode
Social Security surpluses, something both parties have vowed to
avoid.
</P>
<P>
   But McDermott was outmaneuvered when by voice vote, Republicans
altered his amendment to call for unearthing federal waste, fraud
and abuse and using the money for tax cuts and debt reduction. No
direct vote on the Bush tax cuts was taken.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not walking away from the Bush tax cut and neither are the
Republicans on this committee,'' Kasich said. ''We can't get all
the way there with this president.''
</P>
<P>
   As the budget panel worked on the plan, Democrats tried
repeatedly -- and unsuccessfully -- to shrink the tax cut, beef up
the Social Security and Medicare trust funds and boost spending for
debt reduction and education. The votes were mostly party line.
</P>
<P>
   Both Clinton and congressional Republicans would set aside all
$977 billion in projected Social Security surpluses through 2005
for debt reduction.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Congressional Budget Office http://www.cbo.gov
</P>
<P>
   White House Office of Management and Budget
http://www.whitehouse.gov/OMB
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
