<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 04:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Symbolic Gun Control Victory  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House has voted narrowly to urge
House-Senate negotiators to meet within two weeks to consider
long-stalled gun controlled legislation.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate voted last year to institute 72-hour background
checks on gun show sales, but the House rejected that provision in
favor of a 24-hour wait and gun control has been on the back burner
since then.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiators are to resolve differences between the two
bills, which also contain a number of other provisions.
</P>
<P>
   Hours before the 218-205 House vote Wednesday, 12 female members
of Congress made an emotional appeal at the White House for their
colleagues to move on the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Approval of the non-binding House resolution constituted a rare
victory for gun control and the White House cheered the vote,
calling it a defeat for the National Rifle Association.
</P>
<P>
   ''The NRA's influence on Republicans may be beginning to
break,'' said White House spokesman Joe Lockhart. In all, 46
Republicans supported the measure; 32 Democrats opposed it.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, New York Gov. George Pataki called Wednesday for a
series of gun control measures in his state that include making
trigger locks mandatory, taking ballistic ''fingerprints'' of guns,
requiring dealers and manufacturers to send to a state lab a test
bullet and shell casing from every handgun they sell in the state,
raising the age for handgun ownership from 18 to 21 and requiring
instant background checks of gun buyers at flea markets and gun
shows.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, 100 religious leaders sent a letter to Congress
supporting Clinton's efforts to reduce gun violence, and the
National Opinion Research Center issued a study that said the 25
percent of Americans who own handguns are far outnumbered by the 37
percent who favor a handgun ban for all except ''police and other
authorized persons.''
</P>
<P>
   Meeting with House members, President Clinton repeated his
complaint that the NRA has stalled gun legislation with pressure
tactics and an argument against lengthier background checks that he
deemed senseless.
</P>
<P>
   ''Taking a little time and a little inconvenience to save a lot
of lives is a good deal for America,'' Clinton said. ''Why should
this be the only area of our national life where we say no
prevention, only punishment?''
</P>
<P>
   In response, NRA Executive Vice President Wayne LaPierre said
the White House was trying to ''demonize'' the NRA to distract
attention from ''the complete collapse of enforcement'' of existing
gun laws by the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   ''They try to focus on anything except what they are vulnerable
on,'' LaPierre said. ''What does a criminal have to fear from these
guys? Nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration contends the NRA attack on gun
prosecutions misses the point. Federal policy is to keep the
biggest gun cases and refer lesser ones to state authorities, and
even so, the federal prosecutions rose 25.3 percent in one year, it
says.
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: White House: www.whitehouse.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-16-00 0438 </TRAILER>
