<P>
U.S. Muslims protest NBC-TV's comedy series on God
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A Muslim organization has been the first
religious group to publicly protest ''God, the Devil and Bob,'' a
new animated comedy series on NBC-TV.
</P>
<P>
   ''This kind of tasteless and trivial portrayal of God does a
disservice to the millions of American television viewers who have
deeply felt religious beliefs,'' declared Nihad Awad, executive
director of the Council on American-Islamic Relations.
</P>
<P>
   The council is urging viewers to contact the network and
affiliated stations and express concern about companies that buy
ads on the show.
</P>
<P>
   The series deals with a Detroit auto worker named Bob who meets
God in a bar and discusses moral questions and whether mankind is
worth saving.
</P>
<P>
   At least nine of NBC's 215 affiliates have refused to carry the
sitcom saying it contains offensive matter. They include KSL in
Salt Lake City, owned by the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day
Saints.
</P>
