</P>
<P>
Orthodox Jews launch ''virtual Purim'' Web site
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- An Orthodox Jewish group has posted a Web site
to help believers around the world observe the festival of Purim.
</P>
<P>
   Purin, which celebrates Haman's failure to annihilate the Jews
as recorded in the biblical book of Esther, falls on March 20-21.
</P>
<P>
   The site, www.virtualpurim.com, is sponsored by the Lubavitch
branch of Hasidic Jews and its Chabad centers.
</P>
<P>
   It gives detailed information about the holiday and how to
celebrate it, with an interactive Ask-the-Rabbi section, children's
games, recipes, prayer and study guides, a worldwide on-line
costume contest and an audio selection of holiday songs.
</P>
