<HEADLINE> Dow Up 435.90; Nasdaq Takes Drop  </HEADLINE>
By EILEEN GLANTON, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The Dow industrials surged more than 400 points
Thursday, as more bargain-hunting among ''old'' economy issues
helped extend sharp gains for blue-chip stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The technology-focused Nasdaq Stock Market, which had been
adding to its recent swoon from record heights, reversed course in
the afternoon and was rising.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average was up 435.90 points, or by 4.3
percent, at 10,567.31 by early afternoon. If it held through
closing, it would be the sharpest point gain ever for Wall Street's
best-known indicator. Even with the gain, the Dow remained 9.9
percent below its Jan. 14 record of 11,722.98.
</P>
<P>
   Investors' willingness to dump blue-chip stocks in favor of
technology stocks pushed the Dow into a ''correction'' in
mid-February, and the index has struggled until this week.
</P>
<P>
   But traders are once more paying attention to old-line
companies, and companies like American Express, Johnson &AMP; Johnson
and 3M were leading the Dow higher Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index, which closed last Friday at a record
5,048.62, was up 23.61 at 4,606.23 in afternoon trading. At its low
point of the day, the Nasdaq was down 127 points and its decline
from last Friday was 11.8 percent. But with the gain, its decline
was 8.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   A drop of more than 10 percent is considered a signal of a
correction, or downturn in a rising market.
</P>
<P>
   ''A lot of these high-growth stocks had gotten to such extreme
valuations,'' said Matt Finn, chief investment officer of the
growth and income group at Evergreen Funds in Boston. ''They were
due to come down.''
</P>
<P>
   Blue-chip shares rose even after the Labor Department's Producer
Price Index showed that wholesale prices surged 1 percent in
February, the largest gain in nearly 10 years, as gasoline, home
heating oil and other energy costs rose.
</P>
<P>
   Still, investors were heartened by the fact that the ''core''
rate of inflation at the wholesale level, which excludes the
volatile energy and food categories, matched expectations with a
0.3 percent gain in Thursday's report.
</P>
<P>
   Inflation figures, including the Consumer Price Index due for
release on Friday, are sure to be closely watched by the Federal
Reserve as it weighs whether still higher interest rates are needed
to cool the economy. In a continuing effort to keep inflation at
bay, the Fed has raised rates four times since last June, and it
meets again Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
