<HEADLINE> Faith Hubley Gets TV Showcase  </HEADLINE>
By LYNN ELBER, AP Television Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- In filmmaker Faith Hubley's world, children
joust happily with bathroom dragons, musical notes transform into
jazz dancers, and a woman and a goat play pattycake.
</P>
<P>
   Also part of Hubley's animated vision: a whale ensnared in an
oil-soaked sea, a husband snatched away by death, and brutal
snapshots of European witchhunts that targeted vast numbers of
women.
</P>
<P>
   Both the charm and pain of her ongoing work are on display this
month on Sundance Channel, which is showcasing the films of Hubley,
her late husband, John, and their daughter, Emily.
</P>
<P>
   It is a well-deserved tribute, said Charles Silver, a curator in
the film and video department of New York's Museum of Modern Art.
Faith and John Hubley were bold pioneers in animation beginning in
the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   ''They really broke away from the tradition of cartoons as
Saturday afternoon entertainment for children and turned animation
into a much more mature medium, opening all kinds of possibilities
for other filmmakers to make personal films,'' Silver said.
</P>
<P>
   The Hubley images combine touches of Klee, Matisse and other
modern painters with elements of ancient cultures. The messages
range from unabashedly political and philosophical to ruminations
on life, both sweet and sad.
</P>
<P>
   Hubley films have won three Academy Awards, and numerous film
festival and other honors.
</P>
<P>
   Sundance's ''Spotlight on the Hubleys'' packages the family's
short films -- most running about 10 minutes -- to showcase their
solo and collaborative efforts. Among them: Emily Hubley's memory
piece ''Pigeon Within'' (11:50 a.m. EST Friday) and Faith Hubley's
''Everybody Rides the Carousel,'' about human development (9 p.m.
EST Saturday).
</P>
<P>
   Faith Hubley, speaking from her home studio in Manhattan, ''a
lovely room on Central Park South,'' seems to embody her films: She
is by turns droll and somber, playful and exacting. And, at age 75,
as zestful as her celluloid imagery.
</P>
<P>
   She remains committed to one film project a year, her pattern
since 1955.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can't stop. It's like an obsession. When Johnny and I got
married, we had two wedding vows. One was to make a personal film a
year. ... When Johnny died (in 1977), I continued because I had
that vow.''
</P>
<P>
   ''And by then, all my genes and my little cells were accustomed
to this rhythm. It would have been cruel to stop,'' Hubley added.
</P>
<P>
   The daughter of a dentist and a homemaker, Hubley had to find
her own creative path.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think my father wanted to write, but that isn't what he did.
My mother had a kind of classical dilettante approach -- a little
bit of music, a little bit of that. The last thing she wanted me to
be was an artist. I didn't care. I had no respect for the things
they were into, money and security.''
</P>
<P>
   The family values that Faith Hubley passed on to her four
children are far different. She has forged a creative partnership
with Emily, who helps animate and inks her mother's films in
addition to making her own distinctive animated movies.
</P>
<P>
   Another daughter, Georgia, has joined in as an animator and
music composer on Faith Hubley's films and is a member of the band
Yo La Tengo. One son works outside the movie field, as a horse
trainer, but the other is a film editor.
</P>
<P>
   Has she created an artistic empire? ''No, just a family,'' Faith
Hubley replies.
</P>
<P>
   Her days are full but orderly: She teaches a class at Yale in
storyboard, showing students how to create a series of drawings
that will reflect the arc of a film. She works on her own yearly
film project at a measured pace.
</P>
<P>
   ''I practice the cello every day and I paint and I play with my
grandchildren -- and anybody else who will play with me,'' Hubley
says. Then she adds: ''I work very hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Artistic fervor is her driving force.
</P>
<P>
   ''I completely believe that art is necessary for life. I'm so
fortunate to be able to express myself every day. In tribal
societies, so-called primitive societies, much of the energy is
spent in ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   ''We can't turn back the clock, but there's no reason we can't
have a society in which everybody can spend enough time taking art
in and breathing it out,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She acknowledges there can be indifference and even hostility
toward artistic expression, but is undaunted. ''We'll see. We will
see. The party's not over,'' Hubley says.
</P>
<P>
   That's the same kind of hope that lights even her darkest films,
an optimism she traces to her early New York childhood.
</P>
<P>
   ''Growing up in Hell's Kitchen, being exposed to really serious
poverty and seeing the beautiful spirit of my classmates. Having
the librarian, Margaret M. Ward -- I wrote to her until she died --
take us to the public library, a raggedy bunch of kids, and say,
'There's the universe. Everything in the universe is there, and
it's yours.'
</P>
<P>
   ''How could you not believe?''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in television ....
</P>
<P>
   GLOBETROTTERS: Armchair adventurers can reach the far corners of
the world Sunday via Travel Channel's ''Expedition Night.'' The
three one-hour specials airing from 8-11 p.m. EST include ''The
Land of Fear,'' a journey across the Sahara; ''Gasherbrum: Ascent
on G-2,'' which pits climber Christine Boskoff against Pakistan's
Karakorum mountain range, and ''Quest for the Cloud People,'' a
Peruvian Andes search for a forgotten people.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: ''Spotlight Hubley'' page can be linked through
http://sundancechannel.com
</P>
<P>
   Lynn Elber can be reached at lelber''at''ap.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-16-00 1301 </TRAILER>
