<HEADLINE> Clinton: Take Steps on Gas Prices  </HEADLINE>
By ANNE GEARAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton said today that while he
hopes oil producing countries will move to lower gasoline and oil
prices, there is more the United States can do in the meantime.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also said continued instability in the oil market could
end up ''cratering the economies of other countries and hurting
ours.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I do believe we need to do more here on our own, here in
America,'' to deal with rising petroleum costs, Clinton said at the
White House.
</P>
<P>
   The president did not provide details of anything his
administration might do to ease gas prices that now average $1.54
for a gallon of regular unleaded.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he met with Energy Secretary Bill Richardson on the
subject at the White House this morning.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have talked about the present difficulties that Americans
are facing because of the price of gasoline and the high price of
oil, and what our short and longer-term options are,'' Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've been working very hard on this now for several weeks and
... we hope to have some things to say about it over the next few
days,'' Clinton said before leaving the White House for a
bipartisan luncheon on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   The main cause for a sharp increase in petroleum costs is OPEC's
decision to cut back on production to raise oil prices that Clinton
said were ''way too low'' last year.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it is in the interests of the OPEC nations and in the
interest of the consuming nations to have a stable price of oil,''
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Too low and the oil producers cannot manage their domestic
economies, Clinton said. Oil prices that are too high could end up
''cratering'' the economies of some consuming countries, ''and hurt
a lot of innocent people in the process,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials have repeatedly said they expect the
OPEC oil producers to increase production. The oil ministers meet
March 27 to consider production levels.
</P>
<P>
   More oil on the market would have a trickle-down effect that
could lower gas and oil prices over several weeks, although man
analysts say pump prices will probably stay high through the
summer.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm encouraged by a lot of the developments that are going
on,'' Clinton said. ''I hope there will be some relief soon when
the OPEC meeting occurs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-16-00 1327 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000316.0087 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 13:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asbestos Bill Clears House Panel  </HEADLINE>
By JIM ABRAMS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House Judiciary Committee on Thursday
narrowly approved legislation that would set up a new government
agency to speed legal relief to the hundreds of thousands of people
sickened by exposure to asbestos.
</P>
<P>
   The 18-15 vote, with most Republicans supporting and Democrats
against, sends the bill to the House floor, where its prospects are
uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed Justice Department agency would be responsible for
certifying the eligibility of all asbestos victim claims and coming
up with settlement offers within months, in contrast to the years
it takes many claims to go through the courts.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, sponsored by Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry Hyde,
R-Ill., is backed by business groups, including companies facing
lawsuits over asbestos exposure, some of which occurred three and
four decades ago. The Supreme Court has urged Congress to take
legislative action to deal with what it said was a serious backlog
in asbestos cases.
</P>
<P>
   The measure is opposed by trial lawyers and environmental and
consumer groups that contend the legislation would deprive victims
of their legal rights to compensation.
</P>
<P>
   Asbestos is a fibrous mineral once commonly used in insulation
and fireproofing material. The inhaling of asbestos fibers can
cause lung cancer and other deadly respiratory ailments, sometimes
decades after the exposure.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde has argued that a fairer and more efficient system is
needed because 200,000 cases are still pending and there are as
many as 40,000 new lawsuits filed every year.
</P>
<P>
   Under the bill, claimants would have to go to the proposed
Office of Asbestos Compensation in the Justice Department, which
would determine if they are medically eligible. Only people who are
sick could make claims. Those who have signs of asbestos disease,
such as lung scarring, but are otherwise in good health could be
retested at government expense.
</P>
<P>
   Those declared eligible would receive a settlement offer within
a month, with the money coming from a fund paid for by defendant
companies. The claimant could either accept the settlement, proceed
to an administrative court for a ruling within 90 days, or return
to the traditional route of a lawsuit in a state or federal court.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The bill is H.R. 1283.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-16-00 1337 </TRAILER>
