<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Saliva, Urine May Give Cancer Clues  </HEADLINE>
By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Simple saliva and urine tests could one day
replace complicated biopsies in detecting the presence of at least
some types of cancer, a new study indicates.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers at Johns Hopkins University in Baltimore report in
Friday's edition of the journal Science that cancer-related changes
in a part of human cells called mitochondria can be detected in
related body fluids.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the team was able to detect bladder cancer by
testing urine from cancer victims, and saliva showed changes
associated with head and neck cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Lung fluids also showed changes related to lung cancer, though
that test was somewhat more complicated, said Dr. David Sidransky
of the research team.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers had been studying cell changes associated with
cancer for several years, but detecting cancer-related changes in
the cell nucleus proved ''very challenging,'' Sidransky said in a
telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   When they tried looking for changes in mitochondria instead,
they were surprised. ''We never imagined that the mitochondria
would have as many mutations as we found,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mitochondria are parts of human cells that provide energy for
the cell. Like the nucleus they contain DNA, the complex set of
instructions for the cell. But unlike the cell nucleus, which gets
DNA from each parent, mitochondria are inherited only from the
mother.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers have known that mitochondria were important in
cancer, as far as giving energy to the tumor, Sidransky said.
</P>
<P>
   ''To our surprise we found that about two-thirds of all the
cancers we looked at had mitochondrial mutations,'' he said.
Mitochondrial changes didn't occur in all tumors, he noted, ''but
when they are there we can find it.''
</P>
<P>
   The next thing is to perfect the tests for use in the general
population, which could take six months to a year, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he added, the team wants to extend their research
to a much larger population. Their paper was based on tests in
about 15 patients each with bladder, lung and head and neck cancer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
