<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nissan USA President Stepping Down  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SMYRNA, Tenn. (AP) -- Jerry Benefield, Nissan USA's president and
chief executive officer for the past 12 years, announced his
retirement Thursday, saying he leaves the company in good shape and
eyeing more models.
</P>
<P>
   Benefield, 60, will retire April 1 and be succeeded by Dan
Gaudette, senior vice president of operations of U.S. manufacturing
for Nissan North America Inc.
</P>
<P>
   He described the future of the company as ''very bright.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Our volumes are increasing. I think job security is in good
shape and in the next three or four years, we will add volume and
models,'' he said in a brief telephone interview. He did not
elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Benefield, as a member of the company's startup team, was
instrumental in building Nissan Motor Manufacturing Corp. USA's
first U.S. manufacturing venture and hiring the plant's first
employees.
</P>
<P>
   Benefield departs at a time when strong sales of the Nissan
Xterra are expected to boost production of the sports utility
vehicle 22 percent next year and could produce more jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's been a great product, even more popular than we expected.
We're at the maximum capacity now and hope to raise that to more
than 100,000,'' he said. It's 80,000 now.
</P>
<P>
   The Xterra has reinvigorated Nissan's sales, becoming one of the
hottest-selling foreign cars in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Nissan Motor Co., the second-largest Japanese automaker, has
announced plans to slash costs worldwide by consolidating offices,
attrition and layoffs. Nissan Motor Manufacturing Corp. USA is
being consolidated into Nissan North America on April 1 as part of
the cost-cutting.
</P>
<P>
   Separately Thursday, Nissan Motor Co. announced it plans to
appoint Carlos Ghosn, the onetime Renault executive who is leading
the Japanese automaker's restructuring drive, as its president.
</P>
<P>
   Ghosn will keep his title as chief operating officer as he
succeeds president Yoshikazu Hanawa, who continues as chief
executive, Nissan officials said Thursday. The management change
will take effect in June after approval at a board meeting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
