<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 14:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Replica of 1800s emigrant ship to tour U.S., but Albany visit indoubt  </HEADLINE>
By CHRIS CAROLA, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- This city's deep-rooted Irish-American
community thought it had another reason to celebrate St. Patrick's
Day: the arrival later this year of a full-size replica of a ship
that brought Irish immigrants to America.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, some of Albany's Irish are seeing red as they don their
green.
</P>
<P>
   The brouhaha stems from an itinerary change that threatens the
scheduled visit by the Jeanie Johnston. The 150-foot-long,
triple-masted barque is fashioned after a storied ship of the same
name that carried Irish potato famine survivors to North America in
the mid-1800s.
</P>
<P>
   The replica ship was originally scheduled to spend four days
docked on the Hudson River in Albany in mid-June. School field
trips, a parade and an Irish music festival were some of the
activities planned in conjunction with the ship's expected four-day
stay in New York's capital.
</P>
<P>
   But the Tralee, Ireland-based organizers who built the ship and
set its 27-city tour schedule have bumped the Albany arrival to
early November, when upstate weather is chancy, at best. They blame
shipbuilding delays for the change, and feel students will have a
better opportunity to visit the ship in the fall as opposed to the
final days of the school year.
</P>
<P>
   To the man responsible for landing Albany a coveted berth on the
Jeanie's tight schedule, the change threatens to wipe out three
years of planning for he event.
</P>
<P>
   ''All of the things we had planned -- a festival, a dockside
Mass, an Irish famine exhibit -- all those things are of
questionable value now to the overall program,'' said an angry
Joseph Dolan, chairman of the Irish American Heritage Museum in
East Durham, 25 miles south of Albany.
</P>
<P>
   ''What's the difference between June and November? Maybe none in
Ireland, but in Albany, New York ...'' he said Thursday. ''We have
all these eggs in the basket and now they're being trodden on.''
</P>
<P>
   Dolan said Albany's host committee is considering canceling the
Jeanie's visit here. A decision will be made after the dozens of
Albany Irish-Americans who ''jumped into this headfirst'' have a
chance to meet, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Jeanie Johnston is a $7 million project funded by
international bodies such as the European Union and the U.S.-led
International Fund for Ireland and by corporations with plants in
Ireland, chiefly Dublin-based Elan Corp. pharmaceuticals.
</P>
<P>
   The original ship made 16 voyages to North America in between
1847 and 1858. It was notable for never losing a passenger to
disease, unlike other Irish emigrant ships of the era that were
dubbed ''coffin ships.''
</P>
<P>
   The replica ship was originally scheduled to sail from Ireland
in mid-April. Delays have pushed back its departure date to May 7.
It's first port of call is Washington, D.C., on June 7, followed by
a summer and fall tour of major ports in the Northeast, Canada and
the Great Lakes, including Buffalo in September.
</P>
<P>
   Dolan, a retired state corrections official, said the Jeanie's
visit had the potential to be Albany's biggest Irish-themed event
ever. In a city of 100,000 where nearly a third claimed at least
some Irish heritage in the 1990 census, that's saying a lot.
</P>
<P>
   Albany prides itself on supporting all things Irish, whether
they be Celtic music festivals, homegrown writers such as William
Kennedy or Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams, who received a hero's
welcome here during visits in 1995 and '98.
</P>
<P>
   ''Ten years ago if you did an Irish festival in Albany, you'd
get 200 of the loyal Irish families,'' said Kevin McKrell, a
musician who got his start singing in Albany numerous Irish bars.
''Now any Irish-related event is packed around here.''
</P>
<P>
   Dolan doubts that will be the case if the Jeanie Johnston heads
up the Hudson in November. One of the purposes of bringing the ship
to Albany was to link its visit with classroom lessons on the
potato famine and Irish immigration, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Albany's docks don't include facilities where people can
wait in line protected from the elements, Dolan said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Do you ask 8- and 9-year-olds to stand on the dock in Albany
in November?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Turlough McConnell, who's coordinating the ship's itinerary,
said Albany and the other cities were aware that the scheduling was
contingent on the Jeanie being built on time and the vagaries of a
trans-Atlantic voyage.
</P>
<P>
   And, he added, much larger port cities are being bypassed while
Albany -- a 300-mile roundtrip from Manhattan -- was scheduled from
the start.
</P>
<P>
   ''We want to be everywhere, but it's only one ship. It's not a
fleet,'' McConnell said. ''There are huge ports that the ship won't
be able to go to.''
</P>
<P>
   McConnell said the schedule could be changed yet again. But with
the Jeanie committed to appear at tall-ship events in New York City
and Boston in July, it's unlikely Albany will see the ship in a
warm-weather month, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Albany is still very much in the plan for the millennium
voyage,'' he said. ''If the date doesn't work for Albany, it's
Albany's prerogative to cancel the visit.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Jeanie Johnston Project:
http://www.jeaniejohnston.com/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
