<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 15:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Euro Bank Raises Lending Rate  </HEADLINE>
By HANS GREIMEL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) -- Taking action for the second time this
year to stem inflation in the 11 euro countries, the European
Central Bank raised its key interest rate Thursday by a
quarter-point to 3.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, the European Union announced that inflation
hit 2 percent for January -- the upper limit for inflation according
to the ECB's own rules.
</P>
<P>
   ''Economic conditions and prospects for the euro area appear to
be better at present than at any other time in the past decade,''
the governing board said in a statement released after Thursday's
meeting. ''At the same time, upside risk to price stability were
seen as a reason for vigilance.''
</P>
<P>
   The ECB said the resurgent European economy and high oil prices
were fueling inflation, but also acknowledged that the weak euro
was prodding prices upward as well.
</P>
<P>
   A weak currency can spur inflation by making imports more
expensive, and the sliding euro has been a concern since it fell to
a new low of 93.90 cents just before the last ECB meeting March 2.
</P>
<P>
   Economists said the central bank held off changing rates earlier
this month, in order to avoid giving the impression it was trying
to bolster the currency, a move seen as damaging the reputation of
the year-old bank.
</P>
<P>
   But ECB President Wim Duisenberg had made it clear then that the
bank was eyeing a rate hike, saying that ''there can be no doubt in
anybody's mind what direction monetary policy will take in the very
near future.''
</P>
<P>
   Since bottoming out, the euro has largely stabilized in a range
of 96-97 cents -- making it easier for the ECB to raise rates
without being seen as a slave to currency fluctuations, analysts
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Now they can say the rate hike has nothing to do with short
term adjustments for the euro and is in line with the long term
goals outlined two weeks ago, that is, concern about inflation,''
said Stefan Schneider, chief euro analyst at Deutsche Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Raising interest rates tends to cool off an overheated economy
by making it more expensive to borrow money. But it also has the
added effect of buoying the local currency because it increases
returns on investments in euro-denominated bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Investors were largely unfazed by Thursday's rate increase,
having already factored it into the market. Stock markets rose 1
percent in London and Paris, and 2.3 percent in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   The euro currency barely moved after the rate announcement
Thursday, heading slightly upward but then settling back. In late
trading in New York, the euro was at 97.13 cents, slightly below
the 97.15 cents in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The ECB also changed Thursday two other key rates which form the
floor and ceiling for the money market -- the overnight deposit rate
and the marginal lending rate. They were also raised by 0.25
percentage point, to 2.5 percent for the deposit rate and 4.5
percent for marginal lending.
</P>
<P>
   The bank's last rate increase was Feb. 3, pushing its
refinancing rate by a quarter percentage point to 3.25 percent. The
refinancing rate is the interest the ECB charges commercial banks
for buying back short-term securities when banks need cash.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
