<HEADLINE> Grains, Soybeans Finish Mixed  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean futures turned in a mixed
performance Thursday on the Chicago Board of Trade as investors
split between profit-taking and betting on higher prices due to
drought.
</P>
<P>
   Wheat took the biggest tumble, declining on improving prospects
for the U.S. winter wheat crop, which accounts for about 70 percent
of the nation's production. A midsession rally in corn and soybeans
also supported the price.
</P>
<P>
   Corn also retreated as cautious investors took profits ahead of
a long-range forecast due out later Thursday. Any sign of heavy
rains ahead in the Midwest could easily wipe out the week's strong
gains, market-watchers said.
</P>
<P>
   Soybeans forged to a six-week high on continuing speculation
that the ongoing drought will hurt crops, then fell to near even by
the close.
</P>
<P>
   Wheat for May delivery fell 2{ cents to $2.66\ a bushel; May
corn fell } cent to $2.35\ a bushel; May oats rose } cent to $1.20{
a bushel; May soybeans rose { cent to $5.25{ a bushel.
</P>
<P>
   Beef futures retreated on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, while
pork futures were mixed.
</P>
<P>
   April live cattle fell .65 cent to 72.12 cents a pound; May
feeder cattle fell .45 cent to 83.22 cents a pound; April lean hogs
fell .47 cent to 61.80 cents a pound; May pork bellies rose 1.27
cent to 93.32 cents a pound.
</P>
