<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Soldier Arraigned in N. Ireland  </HEADLINE>
By SHAWN POGATCHNIK, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) -- A former British soldier was
arraigned on terrorist charges Thursday following an inquiry into
the 1999 assassination of a prominent Catholic attorney, a case
that captured worldwide attention.
</P>
<P>
   Also Thursday, police prevented Irish Republican Army dissidents
from shattering Northern Ireland's uneasy peace. They intercepted a
car packed with explosives -- the first such seizure since a 1998
attack claimed 29 lives. Three people were arrested, including a
convict paroled under terms of the province's 1998 Good Friday
peace accord.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1999 slaying case, Protestant militant William Thompson,
28, was in court facing charges of possessing an Uzi submachine
gun, a sawed-off shotgun, ammunition and explosive powder. He also
was charged with membership in an outlawed anti-Catholic gang, the
Loyalist Volunteer Force.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson -- who resigned last year from the Royal Irish Regiment,
the British army's locally recruited unit -- is the first person to
face charges as a result of a special investigation into the March
1999 death of lawyer Rosemary Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   The English-led team of detectives suspects that Thompson was
involved in the killing. But it interrogated Thompson for a week --
the maximum allowed under anti-terrorist law -- and didn't gather
evidence that would allow him to be charged specifically with
Nelson's murder.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson, 40, bled to death after a booby-trap bomb exploded
beneath her car, blowing off her legs. She had represented
prominent Irish Republican Army suspects and filed civil lawsuits
against the province's predominantly Protestant police force.
</P>
<P>
   The sophistication of the bomb, plus her claims that police
officers had issued verbal death threats to her face, fueled
allegations that individual officers helped her killers.
</P>
<P>
   In the car seizure, police found 500 pounds of fertilizer-based
explosives hidden in one of two cars apparently bound for Belfast.
They linked the operation to the Real IRA, a dissident band
responsible for the August 1998 car-bombing in the town of Omagh,
the most lethal attack in Northern Irish history.
</P>
<P>
   The convict among the three arrested was previously linked to
another IRA splinter group, the Irish National Liberation Army, or
INLA. He received a five-year sentence in 1998 for mailing letter
bombs to senior Protestant politicians, but was paroled last
summer.
</P>
<P>
   Like the IRA, both the Real IRA and INLA are supposed to be
observing cease-fires.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking in Washington, Britain's Northern Ireland secretary,
Peter Mandelson, said police had ''prevented another potential
atrocity'' by seizing the explosives.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's developments came as Northern Ireland's senior
politicians gathered in Washington to debate their continuing
failure to forge a workable Protestant-Catholic administration, the
key goal of the province's peace accord.
</P>
<P>
   A four-party coalition government took office Dec. 2, but
Britain stripped it of power Feb. 11 after the IRA refused to make
any commitment to disarm. The group was supposed to begin scrapping
its hidden weapons stockpiles as part of an American-brokered deal
that got the IRA-linked Sinn Fein party two seats in the 12-member
coalition.
</P>
<P>
   The IRA called a cease-fire in 1997 after killing about 1,800
people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-16-00 1605 </TRAILER>
