<HEADLINE> Yale professor creates system to pick Final Four winners, losers  </HEADLINE>
By NATASHA GURAL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) -- Yale University mathematician Edward H.
Kaplan is just trying to have fun with March Madness.
</P>
<P>
   The professor spent hours-- mostly in hotel rooms in Rome and
Jerusalem-- mulling over ways to beat the odds in NCAA men's college
basketball tournament pools. Then suddenly, a system of computer
betting became obvious.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's just a hard enough problem that I had to sit down and
really think,'' he said. ''But once you see it, it follows
immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   The real test will come as Kaplan's picks on about 10 pools are
tested on the tournament which started Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In one Internet pool run by a professor at Mesa State College in
Colorado, Kaplan used ratings by Jeff Sagarin which appear in USA
Today, to select Texas as the underdog, Michigan State, Duke and
Stanford. In that pool, he has Stanford beating Texas in the final.
</P>
<P>
   The picks vary depending on the specific rules of each pool,
Kaplan said. Input including regular season records, expert
ratings, Las Vegas odds and market statements is put into various
models.
</P>
<P>
   ''The object is to come up with a set of picks before the
tournament begins that would maximize the expected number of points
in the pool,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In more complicated pools, points increase as the tournament
moves ahead and participants are rewarded for going deeper into the
pool.
</P>
<P>
   ''Pools like that encourage you to pick favorites,'' he said.
''It will be very hard for most people to do better than the
seeds.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, it could be that the rankings don't reflect the
teams potential if a top player is injured.
</P>
<P>
   The most complicated pools are ''wild in that they offer
incentives for picking upsets,'' Kaplan said.
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan's first test came over the summer when he calculated the
winners of last year's Final Four using only data available before
the tournament started. In that case, he correctly choose 41 games.
</P>
<P>
   With his model, he expects to correctly identify winners in 38
of the 63 games. Last year was easier than most because the top
seeds were ''overwhelming,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know much about basketball,'' the 44-year-old Hamden
resident said. ''I never did it systematically before. I always let
my sentiments get in the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Scientific considerations aside, Kaplan said he would probably
pick Duke or Michigan State this year.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, his sentiments would have served him as well as the
model. He said he had choose Connecticut as he's lived in the state
since coming to Yale in 1987. He is a professor at the Yale School
of Management.
</P>
<P>
   His 6-year-old daughter, however, could have benefiting from the
model.
</P>
<P>
   ''She said, 'Daddy, I want Godzilla.' I said, 'It's not
Godzilla, it's Gonzaga!'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-16-00 1610 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000316.0121 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 16:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Vietnam Plaque Location Opposed  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A plaque honoring those who died as a result
of the Vietnam War -- but not during the conflict -- should be placed
in Arlington National Cemetery and not near the Vietnam memorial,
the chairman of a federal commission said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The plaque belongs on military property rather than the National
Mall, said John G. Parsons, chairman of the National Capital
Memorial Commission and an associate regional director of the
National Park Service.
</P>
<P>
   The plaque would honor soldiers and civilians who died of
wounds, illnesses or stress-related problems that were attributed
to the war.
</P>
<P>
   The memorial ''would seem comfortable'' in the cemetary because
''many of the fallen comrades are there,'' Parsons told a House
committee.
</P>
<P>
   Parsons' panel joined recently with the Commission of Fine Arts
and the National Capital Planning Commission to ban new memorials
on the National Mall between the Capitol and the Lincoln Memorial.
</P>
<P>
   ''I fully understand what's trying to be done here,'' he said.
''I've also spent the last 20 years fending off proposals just like
this to not proliferate the area with memorials.''
</P>
<P>
   The House Resources Committee's subcommittee on national parks
and public lands is considering legislation that would authorize a
plaque three-feet square on the grounds of the Vietnam memorial.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is vital for us to have a place to honor all the men and
women who have served and died for their country,'' said Rep. Elton
Gallegly, who is sponsoring the measure.
</P>
<P>
   The plaque would not go on the wall or in front of it, the
California Republican said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-16-00 1612 </TRAILER>
