<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 16:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Has Record Gain of 495.47  </HEADLINE>
By EILEEN GLANTON, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The Dow industrials rocketed a record 495 points
in heavy trading Thursday on top of Wednesday's 320-point surge as
a bargain-hunting spree among ''old'' economy issues engineered a
stunning reversal of fortunes for Wall Street's best-known
indicator.
</P>
<P>
   The technology-focused Nasdaq Stock Market, which this week was
swooning sharply from record heights, rode the Dow's coattails to a
sharp gain.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average rose 495.47 points, or 4.9
percent, to close at 10,626.88, according to preliminary figures.
Wall Street's best-known indicator easily beat the record for the
sharpest one-day Dow point rise ever -- 380.53 -- which was set Sept.
8, 1998. It was not near a record for the biggest daily percentage
gain, however.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's too soon to tell whether this is anything more than a
short-term head fake,'' said David G. Sowerby, vice president at
Loomis, Sayles &AMP; Co. ''But a wide range of stocks are participating
and it looks very good.''
</P>
<P>
   But even with its unprecedented two-day rally, the Dow remained
9.4 percent below its Jan. 14 record of 11,722.98.
</P>
<P>
   Investors' willingness to dump blue-chip stocks in favor of
technology stocks pushed the Dow into a ''correction'' in
mid-February, and the index has struggled until this week.
</P>
<P>
   But traders are once more paying attention to old-line
businesses, and companies like General Electric, American Express,
Johnson &AMP; Johnson and 3M were leading the Dow higher Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index, which closed last Friday at a record
5,048.62, was up 135.06 at 4,717.68 at the closing bell after being
down as much as 127 earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
   At the depths of its decline Thursday, the Nasdaq was down 11.8
percent from last Friday. With its recovery later in the day
Thursday, its decline was 6.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   A drop of more than 10 percent is considered a signal of a
correction, or downturn in a rising market.
</P>
<P>
   ''A lot of these high-growth stocks had gotten to such extreme
valuations,'' said Matt Finn, chief investment officer of the
growth and income group at Evergreen Funds in Boston. ''They were
due to come down.''
</P>
<P>
   Blue-chip shares rose even after the Labor Department's Producer
Price Index showed that wholesale prices surged 1 percent in
February, the largest gain in nearly 10 years, as gasoline, home
heating oil and other energy costs rose.
</P>
<P>
   Still, investors were heartened by the fact that the ''core''
rate of inflation at the wholesale level, which excludes the
volatile energy and food categories, matched expectations with a
0.3 percent gain in Thursday's report.
</P>
<P>
   Inflation figures, including the Consumer Price Index due for
release on Friday, are sure to be closely watched by the Federal
Reserve as it weighs whether still higher interest rates are needed
to cool the economy. In a continuing effort to keep inflation at
bay, the Fed has raised rates four times since last June, and it
meets again Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Volatility Thursday was magnified because it is the eve of a
''triple-witching'' session, a once-a-quarter event when contracts
on stock options, index options, and index futures all expire.
Those expirations generally cause increased gyrations on Wall
Street.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-16-00 1613 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000316.0123 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 16:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Money Urged for Bag Screeners  </HEADLINE>
By PAUL SHEPARD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Airline baggage screeners, who provide a
crucial line of defense in the nation's airline safety program,
often quit their jobs to make more money flipping hamburgers.
</P>
<P>
   ''Screeners are a critical link in the performance chain,''
Cathal Flynn, the Federal Aviation Administration's associate chief
for security, said during a hearing Thursday of a House Aviation
subcommittee panel.
</P>
<P>
   ''While it is difficult to verify a correlation between better
pay and better performance, we can all agree that properly trained
and qualified people who are on the job longer tend to perform
better,'' Flynn said.
</P>
<P>
   The testimony had subcommittee members searching for ways to
improve the pay and training for screeners and other ways of
beefing up airport security.
</P>
<P>
   Highly complex and expensive bomb detection machines are often
operated by people making $5.75 to $6.75 an hour, said subcommittee
chairman Rep. John Duncan, R-Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   ''They can go to fast-food operations for better job
opportunities,'' Duncan said. ''It leads to an extremely high
turnover rate.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Eddie Bernice Johnson, D-Texas, added ''You get what you
pay for.''
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Dillingham, a transportation expert at the General
Accounting Office, said a department study in Belgium, Canada,
France and the United Kingdom found airport screeners had to meet
more rigorous requirements for the job but were paid more and got
better benefits.
</P>
<P>
   In those countries, responsibility for airport screening rests
with the individual airports or a government entity, as opposed to
the air carriers as done in the U.S., Dillingham said.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA has several programs underway to address screener
problems including the start up of a screening company
certification program and automated monitoring of screener
performance. However, Dillingham said the FAA certification program
is two years behind schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ''The FAA has fallen short of meeting its screener goals,''
Dillingham said.
</P>
<P>
   FAA spokeswoman Rebecca Trexler said the delay was unavoidable
but that the department is moving as swiftly on the self-imposed
goals as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Alexis M. Stefani, deputy assistant inspector general for
aviation, criticized the FAA for weak background investigation
requirements for airport workers in secure areas.
</P>
<P>
   While individuals convicted of one of 25 types of serious crimes
within a 10 year period are denied airport identification, some
airport employees have been found to have committed crimes ranging
from assault with a deadly weapon, robbery and larceny, Stefani
said.
</P>
<P>
   Trexler said the FAA supports expanding the crime categories.
</P>
<P>
   Stefani suggested expanding the list of crimes beyond 25 and she
seemed to have support for that notion from the committee members.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is amazing to me that we let the system continue this
way,'' said Rep. Peter DeFazio, D-Ore. ''By the grace of God, we
have good equipment and most people are honest. But why have a weak
link?''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the House approved and sent to the president
legislation that would significantly increase spending on airport
safety and modernization. It also could mean higher taxes on
tickets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
