<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Johns Hopkins Students End Sit-in  </HEADLINE>
By ALEX DOMINGUEZ, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE (AP) -- Students ended a 17-day sit-in at Johns Hopkins
University on Thursday, claiming progress in their fight for a
''living wage'' for university employees and contract workers.
</P>
<P>
   The university did not agree to increase wages or hold
contractors to the ''living wage'' pay scale, but signed an
agreement calling for the formation of a committee to ''discuss the
causes and consequences of poverty, including compensation.''
</P>
<P>
   ''What we've got here is not a victory, but something that
allows us to move beyond a sit-in,'' said Vikram Kambampati, a
member of the Student Labor Action Committee. ''We realize this is
what we can get from a sit-in at this point, and we are ready to
move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Between a dozen and three dozen protesters had been sitting and
sleeping in shifts on couches and the floor of the lobby of Garland
Hall, the university's administration building, since Feb. 29.
</P>
<P>
   Students cheered Thursday morning when Jim McGill, the
university's senior vice president for finance and administration,
descended the stairs to the lobby and signed the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   University officials have said they cannot agree to a living
wage, the amount needed to keep a family of four over the federal
poverty line, since that varies with inflation and other factors
and creates ''an unpredictable moving target.''
</P>
<P>
   The students had called on the school to match Baltimore's
living wage standard of $7.90 an hour. The federal minimum wage is
$5.15 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Hopkins set $7.75 an hour as a target wage by July
2002. Spokesman Dennis O'Shea said the university is ahead of
schedule on the commitment.
</P>
<P>
   All direct employees of the university are at that level. The
lowest paid on-campus contract employees now make $6 an hour and
will make $6.50 an hour beginning July 1, the university said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
