<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Newspaper Circulation Change Mulled  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The main record-keeper of circulation data for
the newspaper industry is considering adjustments in the way
publishers report their circulation figures.
</P>
<P>
   One of the main changes being considered by the Audit Bureau of
Circulations concerns a rule over pricing, which prevents
newspapers and other publications from counting as paid circulation
any copies that are sold for less than half of their set price,
either on newsstands or by subscription.
</P>
<P>
   Some newspaper publishers want to do away with the so-called
''50 percent rule'' to allow themselves more flexibility in the way
they reach out to new readers through marketing and promotion
efforts, such as offering discounted copies.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Lavery, president of the Schaumburg, Ill.-based
organization, said the ABC's board agreed last week to assemble a
team to study the issue of how to redefine the category of paid
circulation.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Lavery said the organization also wants to
ensure that advertisers are provided specific breakdowns of
different categories of circulation, including copies that are
bought by individuals, copies that are bought by third parties such
as hotels and then distributed to readers, and copies that are
given away.
</P>
<P>
   The ABC, which also compiles circulation data for magazines and
professional publications, has set up committees to study issues of
pricing and reporting circulation.
</P>
<P>
   The committees are expected to report their results in July. A
decision by the ABC board could come as early as November.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
