<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 16:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FTC Charges 2 Drug Cos.  </HEADLINE>
By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Federal Trade Commission charged two drug
companies on Thursday with conspiring to keep generic versions of a
popular blood pressure drug off the market.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time the commission said two other companies have
agreed to settle a similar complaint.
</P>
<P>
   The Commission charged that Hoechst Marion Roussel -- now known
as Aventis Pharmaceuticals -- paid Andrx Corporation to keep that
company from marketing a generic version of Cardizem CD, a widely
prescribed drug for treatment of hypertension and chest pain.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies denied any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are confident that we acted in an appropriate manner and
did not violate any laws in the manner in which we negotiated the
stipulation or otherwise handled our dispute with Andrx,'' said
Aventis' spokesman Charles F. Rouse.
</P>
<P>
   Andrx issued a statement saying the deal actually benefited
consumers by providing it funds to change its product to avoid
patent infringement charges. That meant Andrx could market Cartia
XT, a generic version of Cardizem, before it would otherwise have
been able to do so, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   When the patent on a manufacturer's drug expires generic
versions of the product are usually sold by other companies at
lower prices, sharply reducing the sales of the original maker.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the Aventis-Andrx case, the commission also
reported a settlement with Abbott Laboratories and Geneva
Pharmaceuticals, Inc., resolving charges that the companies entered
into a similar agreement in which Abbott paid Geneva substantial
sums to delay bringing to market a generic alternative to Abbott's
brand-name hypertension and prostate drug, Hytrin. In that case the
companies signed a 10-year agreement to avoid such anticompetitive
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ''The financial arrangements between the branded and generic
manufacturers were designed to keep generic versions of Cardizem CD
and Hytrin off the market for an extended period of time,'' said
Richard Parker, Director of the FTC's Bureau of Competition.
</P>
<P>
   ''These types of agreements have the potential to cost consumers
hundreds of millions of dollars each year, Parker said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the law the first company that wins government approval to
sell a generic drug receives a 180-day exclusive right to merket
the product before other companies can launch their generic
versions.
</P>
<P>
   When Andrx was preparing to launch a generic form of Cardizem
CD, the commission said, Aventis filed a patent infringement suit.
</P>
<P>
   According to the FTC charges, in September 1997 Hoechst and
Andrx entered into an agreement in which Andrx would not market its
product when it received FDA approval and would not give up or
transfer its 180-day exclusivity right.
</P>
<P>
   In return, the FTC said, Hoechst paid Andrx $10 million per
quarter, beginning in July 1998, when Andrx gained FDA approval for
its product.
</P>
<P>
   The FTC charged that the agreement acted as a bottleneck that
prevented any other potential competitors from entering the market
because, since Andrx did not market its product, its 180 days of
exclusive right to sales did not begin to run.
---
</P>
<P>
   On the net: Federal Trade Commission: http://www.ftc.gov.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-16-00 1644 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
