<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 16:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> BMW To Cast Off Part of Rover Unit  </HEADLINE>
By HANS GREIMEL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) -- Automaker BMW announced plans Thursday
to cast off its money-losing Rover passenger car unit, even though
it could cost up to $3 billion in restructuring charges to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, British investment group Alchemy Partners Ltd.,
will take on the Rover and MG brand cars, including their plant in
Longbridge, England, and recast the venture under the new name MG
Car Co.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past five years, those operations have burdened BMW
with $1.25 billion in red ink and dragged down profit an estimated
28 percent last year alone.
</P>
<P>
   The deal's price remained a matter of contention late Thursday,
and BMW said the two sides were still negotiating the fine print of
the arrangement after the company's supervisory board approved its
outline.
</P>
<P>
   BMW did say, however, that shifting the operations to Alchemy
will set the company back $3 billion, in the form of a one-time
restructuring charge.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said it was unclear whether the price of the deal was
rolled into that charge. Some even speculated BMW wooed Alchemy
into taking the loss-making venture by throwing in a cash
incentive.
</P>
<P>
   ''Even getting Rover for free would not be attractive to most
people. It's a cash-eating company,'' said Christian Breitsprecher,
an auto analyst with Deutsche Bank. ''I'm pretty sure Alchemy's not
paying anything for the deal and is getting something on top.''
</P>
<P>
   While shedding Rover's passenger car division, the fate of its
''crown jewel,'' the popular and pricey Land Rover line of
four-wheel-drive vehicles is unclear. Alchemy said it would not be
buying the SUV line; however, the New York Times reported Thursday
that Ford Motor Co was going to purchase it, citing executives
close to the talks.
</P>
<P>
   Ford declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   A London official also said BMW was casting about for buyers.
</P>
<P>
   ''BMW are looking to see if an alternative owner will come
forward,'' said Britain's Secretary of State for Trade and Industry
Stephen Byers during a House of Commons debate.
</P>
<P>
   BMW would only say: ''We are making no statement about Land
Rover today.''
</P>
<P>
   BMW did unveil plans Thursday to roll out a new line of the
sporty, subcompact Minis from its Oxford plant in early summer 2001
and continue building the Rover 75 luxury model in Oxford on a
contract basis for Alchemy. The company also plans to finish
construction of its new Hams Hall engine factory in Birmingham and
begin production there.
</P>
<P>
   Investors largely applauded Thursday's announcement sending BMW
stock up 2.25 percent Thursday to close at 31.75 euros ($30.80) in
Frankfurt.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the proposal to shed Rover caused strife at BMW, leading
to the resignation of three members of the management board. The
board has already filled two of those spots, with the third being
shared by Milberg and chief financial officer Helmut Panke.
</P>
<P>
   The Rover line -- headquartered in Warwick, central England -- was
bought by BMW in 1994 mainly to gain access to Rover's popular
sport utility line and flesh out BMW's models at the less-expensive
end of the car market. BMW has already pumped $3.4 billion into
Rover since buying the group for $1.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The strengthening of the British pound since 1997 has made it
more expensive for the German company to build Rover vehicles in
Britain and export them to other countries in Europe where it earns
revenues in weaker currencies.
</P>
<P>
   Worried about BMW closing down plants or pulling out operations,
the British government has earmarked a $240 million subsidy for the
company, which the European Union Commission is currently
scrutinizing under EU competition rules.
</P>
<P>
   Without the subsidy, union leaders say 16,000 of Rover's 30,000
jobs could be at risk.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-16-00 1645 </TRAILER>
