<DOCNO> APW20000316.0132 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 16:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pentagon Overpaid for Plane Parts  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN M. DONNELLY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Pentagon paid nearly triple the fair and
reasonable price for a part that keeps the propellers on C-130
Hercules transport planes from icing over, according to two
government officials familiar with an internal military audit.
</P>
<P>
   The report is ''for official use only'' by the Pentagon and has
not been released publicly. But Robert Lieberman, the Pentagon's
assistant inspector general for audits, told a House panel Thursday
the ''propeller blade heaters'' were an ''egregious'' example of a
wider problem that has long beset the military: Overpaying for
aircraft parts. Under the contract that included the propeller
heater, the Pentagon paid 38 percent more than it should have for a
variety of parts, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The two other officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
provided more detail. They said the Defense Logistics Agency last
year bought 1,803 of the propeller heaters from United Technology's
Hamilton Standard -- now Hamilton Sundstrand -- at a cost of roughly
$555 apiece, when the fair price was closer to $200 each.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the military paid just over $1 million for the
parts, instead of about $365,000, they said.
</P>
<P>
   However, Stan Soloway, the Pentagon's deputy undersecretary for
acquisition reform, told the House Government Reform subcommittee
on government management, the audit is ''questionable.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not at all convinced the prices are unreasonable and
unfair,'' he told subcommittee chairman Rep. Steve Horn, R-Calif.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Windsor Locks, Conn.-based Hamilton
Sundstrand, Peg Hashem, said it would be ''inappropriate'' to
comment on an internal Pentagon report. But, she said, ''The blade
heater is only one of approximately 1,500 parts, together with
logistic support services, covered by the contract. ... We believe
the pricing of the contract was fair and reasonable.''
</P>
<P>
   Under a new way of doing business adopted in the 1990s, the
Pentagon pays companies not just for parts but for providing a
range of services the military used to do itself, from supply
management to inventory to warehousing, the Pentagon's Soloway
said. On balance, the arrangement saves the government money even
if some parts cost more, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''That would be fine if you really need those services,''
Lieberman responded, but in many cases, the government doesn't need
a ''middle man'' to manage spares. Notwithstanding Soloway's
defense of the arrangement, Lieberman pointed out that the Pentagon
has already agreed to make changes in this approach.
</P>
<P>
   Soloway said the audit ''is a matter that has been under
significant discussion and debate between us (in the secretary of
defense's office) and the inspector general for some months now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-16-00 1648 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000316.0133 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 16:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Port Authority head: I'll fight politically motivated fraud charge  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY McSHANE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The chief of the Port Authority of New York and
New Jersey, an appointee and longtime ally of Gov. George Pataki,
charged Thursday that the state attorney general was politically
motivated in accusing him of real estate fraud.
</P>
<P>
   The move by prosecutor Eliot Spitzer, a Democrat, was based on
''incomplete and inaccurate allegations that go back 10 years,''
Port Authority head Robert E. Boyle said in an angry
three-paragraph statement. Pataki is a Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer, through spokesman Darren Dopp, replied that the
attorney general had ''rock solid evidence. ... We'll prove it in
court.''
</P>
<P>
   Boyle dismissed the 26-page civil complaint as ''a political
lawsuit,'' announced that he would not resign his $165,000-a-year
job, and promised to fight charges that he profited from an
allegedly shady 1990s real estate deal involving a nonprofit
hospital where he served as chairman.
</P>
<P>
   ''We intend to ... petition the court for dismissal of all
allegations,'' Boyle said shortly after Spitzer described his
actions as ''a very serious civil violation.''
</P>
<P>
   Pataki appointed Boyle to the Port Authority job in early 1997.
Prior to that, Boyle had served as president of the Javits Center --
another job provided by the governor.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, as treasurer for Pataki's inaugural and transition
committees, Boyle helped raise more than $2.5 million for the newly
elected governor, who defended his friend on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm a little shocked that something dating from 1990, 1991,
was brought up,'' Pataki said about the suit. ''I'm surprised by
that.''
</P>
<P>
   But Pataki stopped short of saying that Spitzer was politically
motivated. The governor said he would not ask Boyle to resign, and
expressed support for Boyle's reappointment when his current term
expires next month.
</P>
<P>
   Boyle allegedly cashed in by hiding his financial interest in a
Westchester County building, then using his position as chairman of
the Hudson Valley Hospital Center to influence its decision to
lease and then buy the property, the complaint said.
</P>
<P>
   Due to Boyle's ''improper conduct,'' hospital officials -- after
paying $530,000 to renovate the Croton Building -- paid $550,000
more for the building in 1993 than it would have cost two years
earlier, said the complaint by Spitzer.
</P>
<P>
   ''He benefitted to the tune of several thousands dollars -- a
benefit that is illegal and improper,'' Spitzer said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   According to Spitzer's complaint, Boyle ''fraudulently concealed
material facts'' and ''breached his duty of loyalty'' with his
conduct in the leasing and sale of the property.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint seeks an unspecified amount in damages,
restitution and interest to be determined at trial.
</P>
<P>
   Also named in the complaint were two people who served on the
board at Hudson Valley Hospital Center, Arthur Clements and Ruth
Woolfe.
</P>
<P>
   The charge against Boyle, 63, of Croton-on-Hudson, first emerged
in the federal tax-fraud case of Albert J. Pirro, a prominent
Republican lobbyist and the husband of Westchester District
Attorney Jeanine Pirro.
</P>
<P>
   The allegation -- later dropped by the U.S. attorney's office --
described a real estate deal that he and Albert Pirro entered into
with the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer's suit, which covers the same transaction, alleges that
Boyle ignored his legal obligations to protect the hospital in
favor of his desire to turn a profit.
</P>
<P>
   According to the suit, Boyle learned two things in early 1991:
that the hospital was looking for new office space and that a
building in nearby Croton-on-Hudson was up for sale.
</P>
<P>
   Boyle, after allegedly telling Pirro to buy the building, became
a secret 45 percent partner in Pirro's real estate company,
Distinctive Properties. Boyle then arranged for the hospital to
lease space in the building, which Distinctive Properties had
purchased in April 1991 for $950,000, the suit said.
</P>
<P>
   The hospital spent $530,000 to renovate the building and hired
Rogene Industries, a construction company owned by Boyle, as
construction manager. The building was sold to the hospital by
Distinctive Properties in 1993 at a $550,000 profit.
</P>
<P>
   The bi-state Port Authority oversees the region's three airports
along with many of its bridges and tunnels.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-16-00 1652 </TRAILER>
