<BODY>
<HEADLINE> DAs in 5 counties won't prosecute for babies left in safe havens  </HEADLINE>
By LYNN BREZOSKY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- District attorneys in five counties have
agreed to not lodge child abandonment charges on mothers who leave
their unwanted newborns in hospitals or other safe places.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement between district attorneys in Schenectady, Albany,
Rensselaer, Saratoga and Washington counties followed a meeting
hosted by Rensselaer County District Attorney Kenneth Bruno. Bruno
says he hopes to gain similar cooperation from prosecutors around
the state, in an effort to reduce incidences of ''dumpster
babies.''
</P>
<P>
   Westchester County District Attorney Jeanine Pirro, head of the
New York State District Attorneys Association, said that
prosecutors can decide on a case-by-case basis whether to press
charges against mothers.
</P>
<P>
   ''The reality is that teen-age mothers give birth every day of
the week, and there are those who put their self-interest over the
health and the life of their newborn,'' Pirro said.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, she said she did not know of any other district
attorneys who had announced they would not prosecute such cases.
</P>
<P>
   Bruno's efforts got statewide attention from his father, Senate
Majority Leader Joseph Bruno, who in a news conference last week
touted the plan as a step against dead babies turning up in trash
bins, bathroom stalls, and wooded patches.
</P>
<P>
   The elder Bruno says he is working on statewide legislation that
would decriminalize child abandonment, provided steps are taken to
ensure the infant is cared for. He said he was cautious of creating
loopholes that could be used to defend child abusers.
</P>
<P>
   Child abandonment is a felony under state law, carrying a
penalty of up to four years in state prison.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities in the Syracuse-area district of Republican Sen.
Nancy Larraine Hoffmann have been lenient toward mothers who take
advantage of services, such as ''Jane Doe'' hospital admissions,
for decades. Hoffmann began a campaign as a Syracuse city councilor
in the 1980s, following three deaths in the span of just a few
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Federal statistics show that unwanted babies are turning up dead
at an increasing and alarming rate. Of 105 known abandoned babies
in 1998, 33 were found dead. In 1991, 65 babies were left in public
places and eight died.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
