<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Criticizes GOP Budget Plan  </HEADLINE>
By ANNE GEARAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton said Thursday a budget
blueprint emerging in the House is risky and unrealistic, and asked
Republican leaders to reconsider.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is the wrong path for America,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I ask the leadership to change course, to go back and write a
budget that maintains our fiscal discipline and meets our most
pressing priorities.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans pushed a $1.82 trillion budget for next year through
the House Budget Committee on Wednesday. On the near party-line
23-18 vote, only Rep. Mac Collins, R-Ga., defected.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also alluded to last year's budget fight over a $792
billion tax cut proposed by Republicans, and issued a veiled veto
threat.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is unrealistic, unwise,'' Clinton said before leaving the
White House for a bipartisan luncheon on Capitol Hill. ''The risks
it poses are unconscionable. It is as risky and costly as the
budget they proposed last year that I vetoed.''
</P>
<P>
   Cabinet members met at the White House on Thursday morning to
discuss the GOP spending plan, which they said wouldn't shore up
Social Security or Medicare, provide a prescription drug benefit
for Medicare recipients, or adequately invest in education.
</P>
<P>
   ''All I can say is here we go again,'' Health and Human Services
Secretary Donna Shalala said afterward. ''They pick on women, on
kids and on old people.''
</P>
<P>
   At issue is how to balance spending priorities with a tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP measure -- a roadmap for fiscal 2001 spending and tax
bills Congress will work on later -- contains about $50 billion more
in tax cuts than Clinton wants, and less domestic spending. It
would provide $307 billion for next year's defense budget, $1
billion higher than Clinton's plan. Its $290 billion for domestic
programs is nearly $30 billion less than Clinton prefers.
</P>
<P>
   ''This budget is in stark contrast to the Clinton-Gore tax and
spend approach,'' said Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, who chairs the
tax-writing Ways and Means Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Archer said Republicans are trying to contain new spending while
taking responsible steps to preserve the Social Security system.
</P>
<P>
   ''While the president's budget and rhetoric continue to divide
our country and pit one American against another, our balanced
budget unites Americans, no matter their age or station in life,''
Archer said.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional Republicans would set aside $150 billion for tax
cuts, though they would leave room for perhaps $90 billion more.
They want to avoid another veto fight with Clinton and save a major
tax-cut push for next year, when they hope Texas Gov. George W.
Bush will be in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has made a five-year, $483 billion tax cut a defining issue
of his presidential campaign.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
