<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Political Notebook  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID ESPO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- One of the most curious sagas of the two-year
election cycle involves Rep. Merrill Cook of Utah, an endangered
Republican with a history of erratic behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Numerous Republicans, speaking on condition of anonymity, say
Cook would be a serious underdog this fall, particularly given the
presence on the ballot of Democrat Jim Matheson, son of a former
two-term governor.
</P>
<P>
   But acting in part out of tactical concerns, the GOP high
command has embraced Cook's candidacy, most visibly when Speaker
Dennis Hastert visited Utah for a fund-raising event. To assure the
leadership's support, these Republicans say, Cook has threatened
several times to run as an independent. That would create a
three-way race that almost certainly would lead to the GOP losing
the seat.
</P>
<P>
   But Cook's leverage may run out with Friday's filing deadline.
If he files as a Republican, he and any GOP challengers move to the
next round, which involves a party convention. A candidate must
gain the support of 40 percent of the convention delegates to
qualify for a primary election.
</P>
<P>
   Several Republicans, all of whom spoke on condition of
anonymity, said there has been talk of backing an alternative at
the convention in hopes of holding Cook below the 40 percent
threshold.
</P>
<P>
   But Jim Wilkinson, spokesman for the GOP campaign committee,
denied such plans exist. ''We are 100 percent behind Merrill Cook,
all the way to the end,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Connie Humphrey, a spokeswoman for Cook, dismissed the idea.
</P>
<P>
   ''Washington leadership doesn't really have a lot of pull with
Utah convention delegates,'' she said. ''That's not a concern of
ours.''
</P>
<P>
   She added, ''Frankly, he's their best candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, Cook has one Republican rival, Jeff Wright, although
others are possible.
</P>
<P>
   Cook, a Republican who ran unsuccessfully for office three times
as an independent, returned to the GOP fold in the mid-1990s. He is
in his second term in the House.
</P>
<P>
   Days before his 1998 re-election, Cook was thrown out of state
GOP party headquarters following an obscenity-laced tantrum over a
get-out-the-vote campaign message.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters later obtained interoffice e-mail messages written by
Cook's chief of staff, Janet Jenson, who was fired the day after
the election. She alleged the congressman was paranoid, delusional
and unable even to grasp that he had won.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview at the time, Cook said that while he sometimes
uses profanity and has a temper, he has no emotional, psychological
or physical problem that would make him unfit to hold office.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am in very good health, mentally and physically,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   In the seesaw battle for control of the House this fall,
Democrats are inching up and Republicans down -- this week, at
least.
</P>
<P>
   Top GOP leaders have weighed in on opposite sides of a contested
primary to pick a challenger to first-termer Rush Holt of New
Jersey, complicating efforts to defeat one of the nation's most
vulnerable Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert and Rep. Tom Davis of Virginia, chairman of the GOP
campaign committee, are supporting former Rep. Dick Zimmer, who
left the House in 1996 to run unsuccessfully for the Senate.
Majority Leader Dick Armey and GOP Whip Tom DeLay support another
former House member, Mike Pappas, who replaced Zimmer, then lost
his seat to Holt in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ''These are the types of developments that you would try to
avoid when you have a tenuous hold on a House majority,'' said Erik
Smith, a spokesman for the House Democratic Campaign Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Wilkinson in rebuttal, pointed to encouraging polls and said no
Republican ''will suffer for lack of resources this fall.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, meanwhile, were cheered by the results of
California's open primary a week ago, when several candidates ran
well against Republicans listed on the same ballot. In particular,
they noted that challenger Adam Schiff outpolled incumbent GOP Rep.
Jim Rogan, 49 percent to 47 percent.
</P>
<P>
   And they claimed a record $7 million at their big fund-raiser of
the year Wednesday, a performance that sent GOP leaders scurrying
to match the total at the dinner they had arranged for Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   These developments -- all incremental, none definitive -- mark a
turnabout from a few weeks ago. That was when Democratic Virginia
Rep. Owen Pickett unexpectedly announced his retirement, handing
the GOP a good chance to pick up his seat.
</P>
<P>
   And when then-Democratic Rep. Virgil Goode of Virginia announced
plans to become an independent and said he would support the
Republican choice for speaker next year.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Ohio Democratic Rep. Jim Traficant went out of his
way to praise Republican Speaker Hastert publicly, raising the
possibility he might support him over Democrat Richard Gephardt
when the new Congress convenes in January.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans' current majority is 222-211, with two
independents, one favoring each party.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-16-00 1703 </TRAILER>
