</P>
<P>
   Wholesale Prices Pushed Up By Fuel
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Huge increases in the price of gasoline and
home heating oil catapulted wholesale prices up by 1 percent in
February -- the biggest one-month surge in nearly a decade. The
worrisome jump in inflation didn't faze Wall Street, however, as
bargain hunters sent the Dow Jones industrial average soaring. The
bigger-than-expected spike in the Producer Price Index, which
measures inflation pressures before they reach consumers, came
after wholesale prices showed no change in January, the Labor
Department said today.
</P>
<P>
   After Dip, Mortgage Rates Inch Up
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Mortgage rates inched up this week after
having slipped for three straight weeks. The average interest rate
on 30-year mortgages rose to 8.24 percent for the week ending
Friday, up from 8.23 percent the week ended March 10, according to
a weekly survey released by Freddie Mac, the mortgage company. In
mid-February, the rates on 30-year mortgages hit a 3{-year high of
8.38 percent. That was the highest since a 8.42 percent rate for
the week ended July 12, 1996.
</P>
<P>
   US Buys Back Part of National Debt
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Treasury, its coffers filled because of
budget surpluses, bought back another $1 billion of the national
debt today, one week after the first such repurchases in 70 years.
Because the government bought back older, outstanding 30-year
Treasury bonds that carry higher yields than the current market
yield on comparable securities, the Treasury Department paid
sellers $268 million in premiums to cash in their bonds early.
Treasury bought back 11 issues of 30-year bonds sold between May
1988 and November 1991. The bonds carried yields ranging from 7.875
percent to 9.125 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Euro Bank Raises Lending Rate
</P>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) -- Taking action for the second time this
year to stem inflation in the 11 euro countries, the European
Central Bank raised its key interest rate today by a quarter-point
to 3.5 percent. Earlier this month, the European Union announced
that inflation hit 2 percent for January -- the upper limit for
inflation according to the ECB's own rules. ''Economic conditions
and prospects for the euro area appear to be better at present than
at any other time in the past decade,'' the governing board said in
a statement released after today's meeting. ''At the same time,
upside risk to price stability were seen as a reason for
vigilance.''
</P>
<P>
   BMW To Cast Off Part of Rover Unit
</P>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) -- Automaker BMW announced plans today to
cast off its money-losing Rover passenger car unit, even though it
could cost up to $3 billion in restructuring charges to do so.
Under the plan, British investment group Alchemy Partners Ltd.,
will take on the Rover and MG brand cars, including their plant in
Longbridge, England, and recast the venture under the new name MG
Car Co. Over the past five years, those operations have burdened
BMW with $1.25 billion in red ink and dragged down profit an
estimated 28 percent last year alone. Alchemy said it would not be
buying the SUV line; however, the New York Times reported today
that Ford Motor Co was going to purchase it, citing executives
close to the talks. Ford declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   FTC Charges 2 Drug Cos.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Federal Trade Commission charged two drug
companies today with conspiring to keep generic versions of a
popular blood pressure drug off the market. At the same time the
commission said two other companies have agreed to settle a similar
complaint. The FTC charged that Hoechst Marion Roussel -- now known
as Aventis Pharmaceuticals -- paid Andrx Corporation to keep that
company from marketing a generic version of Cardizem CD, a widely
prescribed drug for treatment of hypertension and chest pain. Both
companies denied any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   United Air Courts Gay Travelers
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Call them the Gay-Friendly Skies. United
Airlines, eager to mend a rift caused by a two-year boycott that
ended last summer when it agreed to offer domestic partner
benefits, is trying to become the ''official airline'' of gay men
and lesbians. ''Without a doubt, that's definitely the goal,'' said
Mario Baldessari, co-director of United's marketing effort to reach
gays. In doing so, United hopes to overtake American Airlines,
which many consider the airline of choice among gays. The marketing
effort, which includes an ad campaign launched in gay newspapers
late last year, has as much to do with business as with public
relations.
</P>
<P>
   Newspaper Circulation Change Mulled
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The main record-keeper of circulation data for
the newspaper industry is considering adjustments in the way
publishers report their circulation figures. One of the main
changes being considered by the Audit Bureau of Circulations
concerns a rule over pricing, which prevents newspapers and other
publications from counting as paid circulation any copies that are
sold for less than half of their set price, either on newsstands or
by subscription. Some newspaper publishers want to do away with the
so-called ''50 percent rule'' to allow themselves more flexibility
in the way they reach out to new readers through marketing and
promotion efforts, such as offering discounted copies.
</P>
<P>
   Toy Co. Takes Robot Boom Underwater
</P>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- First there were robot dogs. Then robot cats. Now
Japan's third-largest toymaker is betting that the craze for
cyber-pets will take to the water. At a Tokyo toy fair today,
Takara Co. showed off a school of robot fish it says will swim into
Japanese stores this fall. In addition to finned fish, the
''Aquaroid Fish'' line includes a jellyfish and a crab. Fins,
tentacles and pincers are all solar powered, and a computer brain
keeps collisions with other marine life and aquarium walls to a
minimum.
</P>
<P>
   Economic Reports
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Economic reports:
</P>
<P>
   Producer price index: up 1 percent
</P>
<P>
   Housing starts: up 1.3 percent
</P>
<P>
   Jobless claims: down 19,000 to 262,000
</P>
<P>
   Tomorrow: Consumer price index
</P>
<P>
   AP Financial NewsBrief by BRADLEY BROOKS
