<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Calif. Monument Bill Could Face Veto  </HEADLINE>
By MATT KELLEY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- An effort to protect a mountain range
overlooking Palm Springs, Calif., is well-intentioned but may still
generate a presidential veto, Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In testimony before a House Resources subcommittee, Babbitt
praised Republican lawmakers for offering bills to create the Santa
Rosa and San Jacinto Mountains National Monument and to give more
protection to a desert area near Tucson, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   But Babbitt said the bill creating the monument fails to address
water issues and unnecessarily freezes current management practices
for three years. Babbitt said that would not allow federal land
managers to respond to changing conditions such as drought or
floods.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Mary Bono, sponsor of the measure, said she was
disappointed but willing to work on a compromise.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would hate to see good legislation, that has been crafted
with the input of people who will be impacted the most, cast aside
in the pursuit of a bill that reflects only the Interior
Department's policies,'' said Bono, R-Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed monument would encompass 272,000 acres of mountains
reaching to the edge of Palm Springs and neighboring communities.
National monuments include land-use restrictions, such as a ban on
mining, but are open to other uses, such as hunting, which is
banned in national parks.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Rep. Jim Kolbe, R-Ariz., is pushing legislation that
would create the Las Cienegas National Conservation Area in
southeastern Arizona. That designation does not include as many
land-use restrictions as a national monument.
</P>
<P>
   The Las Cienegas proposal would encompass about 207,000 acres,
although conservation rules would only apply to about 50,000 acres
of federal land in the area.
</P>
<P>
   Babbitt said he found it ''strange and objectionable'' that the
bill would ban the federal government from buying any private land
in the conservation area, even if the owner was willing to sell.
However, he promised to work with Kolbe and did not threaten a
veto.
</P>
<P>
   National monument status can be granted either unilaterally by
the president or through an act of Congress. Clinton has created
three monuments on his own this year -- in Arizona and California.
</P>
<P>
   Republican critics say the president failed to get adequate
input from local residents before instituting land restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   ''Nothing upsets the Western members (of Congress) more than
that (monument issue),'' said subcommittee Chairman Jim Hansen,
R-Utah. ''Members are very uptight about it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-16-00 1743 </TRAILER>
