<HEADLINE> European Stocks Mostly Higher  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Investors focused Thursday on old favorites stocks
instead of technology and telecommunications, pushing European
shares broadly higher.
</P>
<P>
   The European Central Bank's decision to increase a key rate by a
quarter-point had little effect on the markets, as a rise had been
expected this month.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones Euro Stoxx Index, which tracks companies in
countries that joined the single currency, ended 5.71 points, or
1.3 percent higher, at 443.03. The Dow Jones Euro Stoxx 50 Index
was up 92.1 points, or 1.8 percent, at 5,175.2.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones Stoxx Index of shares in European companies rose
5.02 points, or 1.3 percent, to 390.38, while the Dow Jones Stoxx
50 Index rose 65.9 points to 4933.9.
</P>
<P>
   Media, technology and telecommunications shares suffered, but
drugs, financials, food and beverage, consumer and non-cyclicals
rose.
</P>
<P>
   Brussels-based technology index Easdaq ended down 3.9 percent,
with ActivCard down 16.1 percent, while Check Point Software
Technologies lost 16 percent. London's TechMARK was down 5.7
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch and Morgan Stanley Dean Witter have said they
expect a correction in new economy stocks, and Morgan Stanley has
called several ''old economy'' sectors very good value.
</P>
<P>
   In domestic markets, London's FTSE-100 Share Index rose 1.7
percent, to 6557.2.
</P>
<P>
   In Paris, the CAC-40 Index was up 1.1 percent to 6,258.53.
Frankfurt's Xetra DAX Index rose 2.3 percent to 7,583.96, while and
Amsterdam's AEX Index was up 3.0 percent to 663.39.
</P>
</TEXT>
