<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Devils agree to sell to affiliate of YankeeNets  </HEADLINE>
By TOM CANAVAN, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. (AP) -- An affiliate of the company that
owns the New York Yankees and the New Jersey Nets agreed Thursday
to buy the New Jersey Devils for $175 million.
</P>
<P>
   The deal seems to clear the way for the NBA's Nets and NHL's
Devils to move from the Continental Airlines Arena in the
Meadowlands sports complex to a proposed arena to be built in
Newark, the state's largest city.
</P>
<P>
   However, sources familiar with negotiations told The Associated
Press that YankeeNets would consider a move to another spot in the
Garden State or a move out of New Jersey if the state did not
provide enough funding for a new arena.
</P>
<P>
   The deal between Puck Holdings and John J. McMullen is expected
to be finalized after the Eastern Conference-leading Devils finish
the hockey season, which would be no later than June. The NHL would
have to approve the sale.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our first goal is to be in Newark,'' said Harvey Schiller,
chairman and CEO of YankeeNets. But, he said, ''if Newark is not
possible, and that could be for a variety of reasons ... there are
other opportunities, yes, that's true.''
</P>
<P>
   The source told the AP that if Gov. Christie Whitman or Newark
officials don't provide enough funds for the Newark arena, ''the
Meadowlands is an alternative and out of state is an alternative.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitman said Thursday that the state would commit funds,
although probably not more than the $75 million initially requested
by YankeeNets, to an arena with two teams.
</P>
<P>
   ''The most important thing for me was to keep the two teams in
New Jersey,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The owners of the Devils and Nets have been asking the state for
years to help build a new arena to replace the 18-year-old
Continental Airlines Arena, but they have differed on where it
should be built. The Nets' new owners, led by philanthropist
Raymond Chambers, wanted it in Newark, while McMullen preferred
Hoboken.
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey Sports and Exposition Authority, the quasi-state
organization that operates the Meadowlands, is proposing a new
arena in East Rutherford. The Nets have a lease with the authority
that expires in 2004 and the Devils have a lease until 2006-7, but
both teams can leave sooner if they pay penalties.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets began negotiations about a year ago to buy the Devils
after Whitman said the state would not likely fund an arena unless
both teams agreed on one site.
</P>
<P>
   ''The decision to sell the team was a very difficult one, but it
is clear that the future success of the franchise can be assured
only by joining forces with the Nets in a new arena for the two
teams,'' McMullen said.
</P>
<P>
   Schiller said that Chambers and co-owner Lewis Katz formed Puck
Holdings last year as a vehicle to purchase the Devils.
</P>
<P>
   Puck Holdings on Thursday wired a money transfer to McMullen
covering about half the sale price, the source told the AP.
</P>
<P>
   The source said Puck Holdings was formed because neither the
Nets nor YankeeNets had any more debt capacity, and the Yankees did
not want to take on any more debt.
</P>
<P>
   The source added that the company that applies to the NHL for
approval may not be called Puck Holdings, and it just may be
YankeeNets.
</P>
<P>
   Sports authority spokesman Dan Emmer said the agency would
present its new arena plans to both teams and called the sale good
for the state.
</P>
<P>
   ''There was a chance both teams might have left New Jersey, and
now under one umbrella, it's virtually assured that they'll stay,''
Emmer said.
</P>
<P>
   McMullen, the only owner in the Devils' 18-year history, bought
the Colorado Rockies in 1982 and moved them to New Jersey, renaming
them the Devils. The 82-year-old almost sold the team to a
Nashville contingent in 1995, the only year the Devils won the
Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Newark Mayor Sharpe James said the arena should be built in the
area of Market, Lafayette and Mulberry streets to be close to
Newark Penn Station.
</P>
<P>
   ''It would be irresponsible not to build a state-of-the-art
arena in the new millennium in an area where 90,000 people enter
the city of Newark from New York every day,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
