<HEADLINE> Euro Gets Boost Against Dollar  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- A rate increase from the European Central Bank
gave the euro a much-needed boost against the dollar Thursday,
while the dollar was caught in a tight range against the yen.
</P>
<P>
   The euro was trading at 97.10 cents in late New York dealings,
up from 96.73 cents Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Europe's common currency rose against the dollar after the ECB
raised its key interest rate by a quarter-point to 3.5 percent
Thursday. It was the second rate increase the bank has made this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Traders said, however, that the euro's gains may be short-lived
since the Federal Reserve is expected to raise U.S. rates at its
meeting next Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar was stuck in a tight range against the Japanese yen
amid the threat of further market intervention from the Bank of
Japan. The bank has bought dollars for yen twice over the past two
weeks in order to stem the rise in the yen, which was threatening
to choke the profits of Japanese exporters.
</P>
<P>
   In late New York trading the dollar was quoted at 105.56
Japanese yen, off slightly from its late Wednesday level of 105.57
yen.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar also was quoted at 1.6600 Swiss francs, down from
1.6657, and 1.4743 Canadian dollars, up from 1.4667. The British
pound rose to $1.5758 from $1.5726.
</P>
<P>
   Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no
longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate.
Based on Thursday's euro rate, the dollar was worth: 2.0142 German
marks, down from 2.0221; 6.7555 French francs, down from 6.7817;
and 1,994.08 Italian lire, down from 2,001.83.
</P>
</TEXT>
