<HEADLINE> Helicopters Needed in Madagascar  </HEADLINE>
By KATYA ROBINSON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANTANANARIVO, Madagascar (AP) -- Only about one-third of hundreds
of tons of food donated to flood-ravaged Madagascar has been
delivered to hungry victims because of a lack of aircraft, aid
officials said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Many roads on this Indian Ocean island nation are washed out or
blocked by landslides. The government and the U.N. World Food
Program has appealed for more aircraft to bring food and supplies
to people in isolated areas.
</P>
<P>
   Only 151 tons of 435 tons of donated food have been distributed,
the national disaster committee said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The largest concentration of homeless people -- more than 11,000
-- were in the Vatomandy area about 90 miles southeast of the
capital of Antananarivo, said WFP spokeswoman Heather Hill.
</P>
<P>
   ''We urgently need to get food there to stop people from
suffering any more than they have,'' Hill said.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday afternoon, a French plane took off for a parachute
drop of 7 tons of sugar, beans and rice over Anosibe an'Ala, a town
about 80 miles southeast of Antananarivo.
</P>
<P>
   The road leading to Anosibe an'Ala has been cut by landslides in
30 places, stranding the population of 75,000, the Adventist
Development and Relief Agency said.
</P>
<P>
   While flooding has not been as severe in Madagascar as in
Mozambique to the west, it has killed at least 130 people on the
island and damaged much of the country's agricultural land. The
floods have also worsened a cholera epidemic that has killed more
than 1,350 people in one year.
</P>
<P>
   The French aircraft carrier Jeanne d'Arc left Madagascar on
Thursday after a three-day mission in the north. Two of its
helicopters brought food into some flooded regions early on
Tuesday, but two days of rain prevented further missions, French
military officials said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
