<HEADLINE> Koehler Appears Likely To Head IMF  </HEADLINE>
By MARTIN CRUTSINGER, AP Economics Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers, trying to
patch damaged relations with a major ally, said he had a ''warm''
initial meeting Thursday with Horst Koehler, the second German
official put forward to head the International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Summers said the two discussed a range of international economic
issues pending before the IMF. Summers said he knew of no remaining
opposition to Koehler's candidacy, which was expected to be
approved in coming days by the IMF's executive board.
</P>
<P>
   ''We had a very warm meeting and a good discussion,'' Summers
told reporters after congressional testimony. ''I said at the end
that I expected it to be the first of many, and I look forward to
our subsequent meetings.''
</P>
<P>
   Summers said he did not discuss any specific reform proposals
for the IMF, which has come under heavy criticism in Congress for
its handling of the Asian currency crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Koehler arrived in Washington on Wednesday for a round of talks
with the Clinton administration, IMF officials and representatives
of Third World countries.
</P>
<P>
   It was expected that the IMF's 24-member executive board will
now move quickly to endorse Koehler, who was put forward by German
Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder after Germany's first candidate for
the post, Caio Koch-Weser, was rejected by the United States as
lacking sufficient stature.
</P>
<P>
   By unwritten rules over the past half-century, the IMF job has
always been held by a European while an American has occupied the
top job at the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
   But a number of countries, including Japan, expressed
unhappiness at this state of affairs and indicated they wanted a
more open nominating process the next time around.
</P>
<P>
   IMF Deputy Managing Director Stanley Fischer, the only remaining
candidate in the race, officially withdrew Thursday. His candidacy
had been put forward by African nations contending the views of
developing countries were being ignored in the IMF leadership
battle.
</P>
<P>
   Fischer described his meeting with Koehler as ''excellent'' and
said, ''I am confident under his leadership the fund will become an
even more effective institution.''
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Jose Pedro de Marais, the IMF executive board
member representing the 20 African nations who had nominated
Fischer, said they would continue to push for changes. He said the
current process ''seriously detracts from the serious work we are
engaged in.''
</P>
<P>
   Japan, the world's second largest economy, on Wednesday withdrew
its candidate, former finance ministry official Eisuke Sakakibara,
but issued a strong statement that Japan also would push for
changes.
</P>
<P>
   ''Japan is not going to keep silent about the monopolization of
that position by European candidates,'' said Akitaka Saiki, a
spokesman for Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi.
</P>
<P>
   Koehler, a former official in Germany's finance ministry, is
currently the head of the European Bank for Reconstruction and
Development, the London-based lending institution created to help
Russia and other former communist nations in Europe transform to
capitalist economies. Koehler would succeed Michel Camdessus, who
stepped down in mid-February after 13 years as head of the IMF.
</P>
<P>
   Fischer, a naturalized American who was born in what is now
Zambia, was Camdessus' deputy and right-hand man in dealing with
the financial crises that hit Asia in the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   ----
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   International Monetary Fund site: http://www.imf.org
</P>
<P>
   World Bank site: http://www.worldbank.org.
</P>
<P>
   Institute for International Economics: http://www.iee.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-16-00 1823 </TRAILER>
