<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Money Funds Rose in Latest Week  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Assets of the nation's retail money market
mutual funds rose by $7.56 billion in the latest week to $997.47
billion, the Investment Company Institute said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Assets of taxable money market funds in the retail category rose
by $6.94 billion to $830.01 billion for the week ended Wednesday,
the Washington-based mutual fund trade group said. Tax-exempt fund
assets rose by $618.2 million to $167.46 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Assets of institutional money market funds fell by $9.29 billion
to $707.31 billion for the same period. Among institutional funds,
taxable money market fund assets fell by $9.53 billion to $654.99
billion; assets of tax-exempt funds rose by $237.8 million to
$52.32 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Total money market assets stood at $1.705 trillion for the week.
</P>
<P>
   Assets for the previous week were revised to $1.707 trillion to
reflect reporting errors and a change in the number of funds
reporting.
</P>
<P>
   The seven-day average yield on money market mutual funds rose in
the week ended Tuesday to 5.28 percent from 5.26 percent the
previous week, said IBC's Money Fund Report, a trade journal
published in Ashland, Mass., by IBC Financial Data Inc. The 30-day
average yield rose to 5.26 percent from 5.24 percent, IBC Financial
Data said.
</P>
<P>
   The seven-day compounded yield rose to 5.42 percent from 5.40
percent the previous week, and the 30-day compounded yield rose to
5.40 percent from 5.38 percent, IBC Financial Data said.
</P>
<P>
   The average maturity of the portfolios held by money funds
remained unchanged at 48 days, IBC Financial Data said.
</P>
<P>
   The online service bankrate.com said its survey of 100 leading
commercial banks, savings and loan associations and savings banks
in the nation's 10 largest markets showed the annual percentage
yield available on money market accounts held steady at 2.04
percent as of Wednesday from a week earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The North Palm Beach, Fla.-based unit of Intelligent Life Corp.
said the annual percentage yield available on interest-bearing
checking accounts kept at 0.83 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Bankrate.com said the annual percentage yield held steady at
4.85 percent on six-month certificates of deposit, unchanged from
the previous week. Yields were 5.28 percent on 1-year CDs, up from
5.25 percent; 5.56 percent on 2{-year CDs, up from 5.54 percent;
and 5.93 percent on 5-year CDs, up from 5.91 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
