<HEADLINE> Musician Plugs Child Support Bill  </HEADLINE>
By G. STEPHEN BIERMAN Jr., Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Rep. Lynn Woolsey, D-Calif., and the mother of
rock group Everclear singer Art Alexakis have one thing in common --
deadbeat husbands drove both to welfare by refusing to pay child
support.
</P>
<P>
   Alexakis flew here Thursday from California to talk about his
father in an effort to plug a bill that would require employers to
deduct child support, like taxes, from a worker's paycheck. The
deduction would appear on an employee's W-4 form and would be
enforced by the IRS.
</P>
<P>
   The IRS has a much better record collecting what it's owed than
the states do at enforcing child support collections, said Woolsey,
who co-authored the bill with House Judiciary Committee Chairman
Henry Hyde, R-Ill.
</P>
<P>
   ''We know that the IRS gives many people heartburn, but the
Hyde-Woolsey bill will take advantage of that heartburn and the
power of the IRS and put that power behind our children,'' Woolsey
said.
</P>
<P>
   Delinquent parents currently owe 30 million children nearly $50
billion, said Geraldine Jensen President of the Association for
Children for Enforcement of Support.
</P>
<P>
   Everclear's song ''Father of Mine,'' which told the story of
Alexakis' father's desertion, garnered an award from Jensen's
association and drew the attention of legislators.
</P>
<P>
   ''This isn't a sexy issue,'' Alexakis said. ''It isn't hanging
out with Sting in the rain forests; it just ain't the same. This is
our children, our future. We complain about the way things are
going today. It's not going to get any better until we teach our
children responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexakis battled problems with drugs and the law before getting
sober and writing songs.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The bill number is H.R. 1488.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
