<HEADLINE> Irish gays and lesbians welcomed by Manhattan borough president  </HEADLINE>
By VERENA DOBNIK, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Gay people in Ireland have one right they don't
have in New York: They're allowed to march as official groups in
St. Patrick's Day parades.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm lesbian, queer, Irish,'' announced Ailbhe Smyth, head of
women's studies at University College in Dublin. ''But I have to
say that in Ireland, we no longer have this kind of intolerance,
this kind of homophobia, this kind of discrimination.''
</P>
<P>
   She and 52 other Irish gays and lesbians were welcomed by the
Manhattan borough president on Thursday, the eve of America's
oldest and biggest St. Patrick's Day parade.
</P>
<P>
   This year marks the 10th time that the New York-based ILGO, the
Irish Lesbian and Gay Organization, has been banned from making the
march up Fifth Avenue under its own banner.
</P>
<P>
   The group's members aren't taking it calmly.
</P>
<P>
   Joined by the Irish contingent, ILGO planned a massive civil
disobedience march down Fifth Avenue -- the opposite direction -- for
about an hour before the official parade starts Friday morning.
ILGO predicted participation by thousands in its protest from 59th
Street to 42nd Street.
</P>
<P>
   As has become traditional, some will then turn around and try to
join the actual parade. Those who fail to heed police warnings face
arrest.
</P>
<P>
   The 239th annual march will feature shamrocks and ''Kiss me, I'm
Irish'' buttons.
</P>
<P>
   But many of the protesters are expected to wear ''Kiss me, I'm
queer'' buttons -- as they did Thursday afternoon for the reception
in the office of Manhattan Borough President C. Virginia Fields.
</P>
<P>
   She said she had marched with Martin Luther King in the 1960s.
And now, she said, she's fighting for passage of state hate crimes
legislation that would ''strongly demonstrate that society will not
allow people to be victimized and attacked.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ancient Order of Hibernians, a fraternal Catholic group that
runs the official parade, has repeatedly maintained its right to
exclude ILGO. And in February, a Manhattan federal jury ruled that
the city had not violated the group's First Amendment rights by
denying it a marching permit.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani will be toward the front of the
parade.
</P>
<P>
   This year, he'll have a new political opponent following him.
U.S. Senate candidate Hillary Rodham Clinton will walk up Fifth on
St. Patrick's for her first time -- against ILGO's wishes.
</P>
<P>
   Though she joined an inclusive Queens parade recently, ''it
doesn't matter where else you march, how many times you march, or
what spin you put on marching -- what matters is integrity,'' ILGO
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   One major figure may be missing this year: 80-year-old Cardinal
John O'Connor, whose health has been failing since he underwent
brain surgery in September. Church officials said he probably will
not greet marchers as he usually does.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday in Fields' office, Catholicism was not missing from
the gathering.
</P>
<P>
   Bridget Roche, a lesbian from Cork, Ireland, wore a gold cross
around her neck and noted, ''I go to Mass.''
</P>
<P>
   At home in Ireland, said the 30-year-old chef, ''there's not
that much discrimination. Here, we're hidden away.''
</P>
<P>
   ILGO supporter David Robinson, who was master of ceremonies for
the borough president's reception, reminded the more than 100
guests that in New York, ''people are fond of saying that on St.
Patrick's Day, everyone is Irish. That is, unless you're lesbian or
gay.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
