<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kohl Aide Refuses To Testify  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- The first witness in a parliamentary inquiry
remained silent Thursday on allegations that he managed a web of
secret accounts at the heart of the slush fund scandal surrounding
former Chancellor Helmut Kohl.
</P>
<P>
   Horst Weyrauch, the Christian Democratic party's former
financial adviser, said he could not discuss whether donors bought
political favors because he faces possible criminal charges.
</P>
<P>
   Weyrauch, 67, was called before the parliamentary investigating
committee set up after Kohl admitted in December that he accepted
undeclared -- and thus illegal -- campaign donations while he was
chancellor in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors are examining allegations that Weyrauch funneled
millions of dollars to and from secret accounts in Switzerland and
Liechtenstein to avoid reporting requirements under German party
financing laws.
</P>
<P>
   Among the questions Weyrauch refused to answer was whether he
wrote a 1978 study on party financing that concluded that laws at
the time had a loophole because they contained no provisions for
punishing violators.
</P>
<P>
   Committee members from the Social Democrat-led governing
coalition argued that Weyrauch had no blanket immunity from
testifying. The panel summoned Weyrauch again for March 23.
</P>
<P>
   In hopes of further clearing up the scandal, the Christian
Democrats released a report Thursday by auditors that found an
additional $4.7 million was held in secret accounts between 1989
and 1992. An earlier audit found more than $6 million from
undetermined sources from 1989-1998.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have laid everything out on the table and done everything
that is possible,'' party general manager Willi Hausmann said.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl, meanwhile, was to return Friday to his seat in parliament,
three months after withdrawing into seclusion because of the
scandal. He has rejected demands by his own party to give up his
seat, noting that it gives him immunity from prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl has also refused to reveal the sources of $1 million he
says he secretly accepted from supporters in the 1990s. He says he
gave them his word.
</P>
<P>
   His stance has led to speculation that government favors were
traded for campaign donations, something Kohl denies.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl was German chancellor for 16 years until 1998 and led the
Christian Democrats for 25 years,
</P>
<P>
   Last week, he announced he had collected $2.1 million from
supporters to cover potential fines against his party for his
action.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
