<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Halt to Serb Media Crackdown Urged  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- After Yugoslav officials shut down
the sixth independent broadcaster in just over a week, Serbian
opposition parties and media called for action Friday to halt the
media crackdown.
</P>
<P>
   President Slobodan Milosevic's government shut down the local
television station in the opposition-run southeastern town of Pirot
Thursday morning and police carted away its transmission equipment,
B2-92 radio in Belgrade reported.
</P>
<P>
   Staff arriving at the transmitter station found barbed wire
around the facility cut, the door lock broken and the equipment
missing.
</P>
<P>
   Radio manager Boban Nikolic said the station had received no
prior notice about the shutdown.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday evening, about 1,000 citizens rallied in Pirot to
protest the closure of their television, Beta news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
   The Pirot television the sixth independent TV or radio station
to have been closed or had its equipment confiscated by the
telecommunications ministry since last Thursday. The government has
claimed the stations worked without license or owed money to the
state.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement Thursday, carried by the official Tanjug news
agency, the ministry said the Pirot television would be allowed to
operate once it fulfilled unspecified legal conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic's opponents gained control over dozens of local media
outlets after they won municipal elections in many Serbian cities
in 1996. The government crackdown against independent media is
widely seen as Milosevic's attempt to minimize critical reporting
ahead of municipal elections later this year.
</P>
<P>
   Veran Maric, head of an independent network of local television
and radio stations, called Thursday for urgent action to prevent
the government from closing down any more stations. Matic announced
formation of a team to plot strategy against the crackdown.
</P>
<P>
   In the central Serbian town of Cacak, the opposition mayor
Velimir Ilic warned that if the government tried to close down the
local television the citizens would ''block the town.'' He added
the local authorities in Cacak have already organized guards around
the transmission facilities.
</P>
<P>
   ''The regime continues with the confrontation with its citizens
and it is time that those in opposition who bear responsibility for
the destiny of their own country, come up with a more radical
response to the government terror,'' opposition leader Zarko Korac
said.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of opposition parties have joined forces in their efforts
to oust Milosevic, but have so far had little result.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
