<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fuel Costs Push Wholesale Prices Up  </HEADLINE>
By JEANNINE AVERSA, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Huge increases in the price of gasoline and
home heating oil catapulted wholesale prices up by 1 percent in
February -- the biggest one-month surge in nearly a decade. The
worrisome jump in inflation didn't faze Wall Street, however, as
bargain hunters sent the Dow Jones industrial average soaring to
its biggest one-day point gain in history.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow rose 499.19 points, or 4.9 percent, to close at
10,630.60. On the heels of Wednesday's 320-point gain, the rally
helped the Dow gain back a stunning 42 percent of the losses
recorded since it peaked at 11,722.98 on Jan. 14.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street's best-known indicator easily beat the record for
the sharpest one-day Dow point rise ever -- 380.53 -- which was set
Sept. 8, 1998. It was not near a record for the biggest daily
percentage gain, however. Nasdaq, which this week was swooning
sharply from record heights, rode the Dow's coattails to a sharp
gain. The index closed up 134.77 at 4,717.39, after being down as
much as 127 points early in the day.
</P>
<P>
   The bigger-than-expected spike in the Producer Price Index,
which measures inflation pressures before they reach consumers,
came after wholesale prices showed no change in January, the Labor
Department said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''Inflation is heating up but the kettle is far from a boil,''
said economist Joel Naroff of Naroff Economic Advisors. ''Instead,
there are nagging signs that maybe the pleasant non-inflationary
world that we have been living in is just a bit less friendly.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month's leap in wholesale prices, the worst showing on
inflation since a 1 percent rise in October 1990, justifies the
Federal Reserve boosting interest rates again by at least a quarter
of a percentage point at its meeting Tuesday, economists said.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed has raised rates four times since June to slow the
white-hot economy and keep inflation at bay, but economists said
those actions have had little impact.
</P>
<P>
   The jolt in February's wholesale prices came from a whopping 5.2
percent jump in energy costs, the largest gain in nearly 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am monitoring the impact that energy prices are having on
our economy,'' said Labor Secretary Alexis Herman. ''Today's
report, however, continues to show that inflationary pressure
remains limited to the energy sector.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside the volatile energy and food categories, the ''core''
rate of inflation, having fallen 0.2 percent in January, rose 0.3
percent last month. Some Wall Street investors took comfort in the
modest gain because it was right on target with many analysts'
projections.
</P>
<P>
   The government said the increase in the core inflation rate
mostly stemmed from a hefty 6.3 percent rise in cigarette prices,
the biggest gain in five months. economists said. Excluding
cigarettes, the core would have shown no change.
</P>
<P>
   On the energy front, home heating oil prices soared 30.6 percent
in February, the largest rise since a record 37.7 percent increase
in August 1990, leading the jump in overall energy costs. Gasoline
prices rose 12.9 percent, their biggest gain since April.
</P>
<P>
   Surging gasoline prices could have the effect of slowing the
economy if it forces consumers to pull back on their spending,
which is the locomotive of the economy, some economists said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Because consumers cannot easily cut back on gasoline
purchases, they are left with less money to spend on everything
else,'' said First Union economist Mark Vitner. ''That should
ultimately slow the economy and help contain inflation pressures,
making the Fed's job a little easier.''
</P>
<P>
   Food prices, meanwhile, went up by 0.4 percent in February as a
record 24.6 percent rise in egg prices dwarfed falling prices for
chickens, turkeys and fresh vegetables. The previous record jump of
22.1 percent was recorded in October 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Higher gasoline and diesel bills boosted costs to transport eggs
from farms to grocery stores and may explain the big increase in
February's egg prices, said economist Mark Zandi of RFA Dismal
Sciences. Chicken prices, on the other hand, fell reflecting
slackened demand as beef consumption picked up, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Food prices could become a new problem,'' said Paul Kasriel,
chief economist for the Northern Trust Co. ''If we have a drought
this year, as some predict, and increased demand from recovering
Asian economies, food prices may be pushed higher.''
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in the report, car prices fell 1.2 percent, the
biggest drop since July 1997, and truck prices declined 0.1
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The government will report on prices pressures at the consumer
level Friday and many analysts are estimating a February rise of
0.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In other reports:
</P>
<P>
   -- The number of Americans filing new claims for unemployment
benefits last week fell by 19,000 to 262,000, the lowest level
since Dec. 1, 1973, suggesting employers are scrambling to find
workers.
</P>
<P>
   -- Housing construction rose 1.3 percent in February to a
seasonally adjusted annual rate of 1.78 million units, additional
evidence the economy continues to power ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   The PPI report: http://stats.bls.gov/ppihome.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-16-00 1853 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
