<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 19:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bill paying doctors, hospitals, for failed HMOs passes Assembly  </HEADLINE>
By KATHLEEN CANNON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- Legislation reimbursing hospitals and
doctors who were owed money after two managed care companies went
belly up is one step closer to becoming law.
</P>
<P>
   The controversial package to pay those who provided services for
the now-defunct HIP Healthcare of New Jersey and the American
Preferred Provider Plan would use $50 million in state funds and
$50 million from a new assessment on the state's surviving HMOs.
Doctors and hospitals have agreed to forgive $50 million of the
total $150 million debt.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, A-1890, passed the Assembly on Thursday by a 64-7 vote
with six abstentions. Attention now shifts to the Senate, which is
expected to act on the bill next week. Gov. Christie Whitman
supports it.
</P>
<P>
   Health insurance representatives call the plan a dangerous
precedent that forces surviving HMOs to bail out competitors by
paying their debts to healthcare providers. Representatives from
hospitals and doctors, however, maintain that they stepped in when
patients and the state needed help, and should be compensated.
</P>
<P>
   The managed care industry lobbied furiously against the bill.
The group has also waged a media campaign to have the bill changed.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the head of the New Jersey Association of Health
Plans said a lawsuit is likely.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's no question. We've had serious discussions about
litigation, what form it would take and who the parties would be,''
said Paul Langevin.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, ''we'll continue to try to make our case in the
Senate,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Langevin said a provision in the bill that would prevent HMOs
from passing on their added costs to ratepayers is
unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Lillo of the New Jersey Hospital Association said he was
pleased that the bill passed the Assembly in a largely bipartisan
vote.
</P>
<P>
   ''This may not be the best compromise, but it's the fairest,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Assembly Speaker Jack Collins said the bill represents a
compromise that will not overburden taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it's time to pay those people,'' he said of the
doctors and hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   He agreed that the bill closes the door on a troubling incident
some believe merits more investigation.
</P>
<P>
   State regulators approved a deal in July 1997 to have HIP turn
over most of its assets to a for-profit company, PHP Healthcare
Corp., which agreed to provide care to HIP members. Within eight
months of the transaction, though, PHP stopped paying health care
providers, leaving HIP heavily in debt.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
