<HEADLINE> Reuters Reaches Deal With Union  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Reuters, the financial news and information
provider, reached a tentative settlement Thursday with the union
representing its U.S. employees after two years of often tense
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're very pleased,'' said company spokeswoman Nancy
Bobrowitz.
</P>
<P>
   Bobrowitz did not release details of the accord, which was still
being reviewed by union officials. A spokesman for the Newspaper
Guild of New York did not return a request for comment.
</P>
<P>
   The main points of contention in the drawn-out talks were
related to job security. The company was seeking greater
flexibility in handling layoffs and making staff assignments, but
the union had called the proposals unreasonable.
</P>
<P>
   The talks have been going on for 2{ years, and the employees had
been working without a contract since early 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Tensions had been rising in recent weeks and members of the
union, which represents 600 U.S.-based reporters and technicians,
authorized union leaders to declare a strike.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Reuters reporters went on a 12-day byline strike,
and in January all but 30 of the company's 120 journalists in New
York called in sick just as U.S. companies began reporting
first-quarter earnings. Management personnel were called upon to
help put out the report that day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
