<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Attorney general's office raises alarm about open records bill  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- Efforts to rewrite the state's law on
public access to government records hit a bump Thursday as the
attorney general's office raised concerns about police records.
</P>
<P>
   First Assistant Attorney General Paul H. Zoubek told the Senate
Judiciary Committee the proposed legislation carries risks of
exposing sensitive investigative files.
</P>
<P>
   ''Access would have a chilling effect on the willingness of
witnesses to come forward to provide relevant and often critical
information,'' Zoubek said. He said, for instance, members of
organized crime groups could use records to identify confidential
informants.
</P>
<P>
   The existing Public Records Law mandates that any document
required under statute be maintained as a public record. But it
does not apply to vast banks of information at all levels of
government, from consulting reports to land appraisals to bill
receipts, for which there is no specific mention in any state law.
</P>
<P>
   The main bill under consideration now, S-866, expands the 1963
law to create a presumption that all government documents are to be
regarded as public records unless a specific law or executive order
from the governor says otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Assembly Speaker Jack Collins held his version of the bill to
give him time to evaluate Zoubek's concerns. It had been scheduled
for Assembly consideration Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
