<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Officer Charged in Kidnappings  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) -- A retired army general was
arrested Thursday in connection with the kidnapping of children
born in captivity during Argentina's ''dirty war.''
</P>
<P>
   Juan Sasiain was arrested as part of an investigation into
whether members of the armed forces kidnapped babies born to
leftist inmates held in clandestine detention centers during the
1976-1983 military dictatorship.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights group charge the military organized a systematic
plan for the illegal adoption of more than 200 children born to
dissidents held captive during the military's seven-year campaign
against leftists and political opponents.
</P>
<P>
   As least 10 former officers have been arrested in the course of
the investigation. Among them are Jorge Videla, the regime's first
president, and retired Adm. Emilior Massera. Both were leaders of
the military junta that overthrew President Isabel Peron in 1976
and ruled until 1983.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest arrest, authorities charged Sasiain with child
kidnapping and detained him in a military barracks. During the
military rule, Sasiain reportedly was in charge of several
detention centers housing pregnant women.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Sasiain, 73, immediately asked that he be placed
under house arrest.
</P>
<P>
   The children's mothers were among at least 9,000 Argentines who
vanished during the ''dirty war''; human rights groups say the
figure is closer to 30,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
