<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 20:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Highway rebuilding to shut down key ramp  </HEADLINE>
sfcpng
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) -- Thousands of visitors to the city will
be going from the Bridgeport Bluefish to a tour of Bridgeport
blight because of a rebuilding project involving Interstate 95.
</P>
<P>
   As part of a more than $100 million project to rebuild I-95
through the city, the only southbound, downtown on-ramp to the
highway will be closed for at least 14 months.
</P>
<P>
   That means downtown traffic headed south onto I-95 will have to
be detoured onto Railroad Avenue which travels behind a series of
run-down, little used former factories and buildings.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are concerned,'' Mickey Herbert, principal owner of the
Bridgeport Bluefish, said Wednesday. The baseball team attracted
more than 350,000 fans to downtown Bridgeport last season.
</P>
<P>
   ''Right now, we just don't know what this will do. A lot of fans
come from south of us, so they use that ramp'' to head home via
I-95, Herbert said.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Rolfe, a roadway designer with the state Department of
Transportation, said there is no way to rebuild the ramp without
shutting it down.
</P>
<P>
   ''We cannot safely maintain traffic and reconstruct the ramp,''
Rolfe said. ''We will have to close it for about 14 months.''
</P>
<P>
   Rolfe said Railroad Avenue will be resurfaced while the downtown
on-ramp is closed.
</P>
<P>
   There are some concerns that traffic tie-ups, and the foreboding
character of blighted areas along Railroad Avenue, could discourage
customers and baseball fans from visiting downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Garland, a spokesman for the University of Bridgeport, said
many students come from towns south of Bridgeport, so the closed
ramp also will affect them.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are concerned about access,'' Garland said. ''Many come at
night.''
</P>
<P>
   However, others say that the project is needed.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's going to cause discomfort, but the end result will be
good,'' said Paul Timpanelli, president of the Bridgeport Regional
Business Council. ''Still, people will get frustrated.''
</P>
<P>
   The Myrtle Avenue ramp will close later this month or early in
April.
</P>
</TEXT>
