<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 20:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Psychologists fired, corrections chief admits errors led torapist's release  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- Two psychologists hired by the state to
review inmate records were dismissed Thursday because of their
roles in the release of a convicted rapist who is the target of a
nationwide manhunt.
</P>
<P>
   Department of Corrections Commissioner Jack Terhune acknowledged
that state corrections employees violated numerous procedures
before releasing Raymond Alves, 57, from the Southern State
Correctional Center in Cumberland County on March 9.
</P>
<P>
   Alves, who is being investigated in connection with several
unsolved murders, remained at large Thursday. The television
program ''America's Most Wanted'' will feature a bulletin on Alves
on Saturday night, Bergen County Prosecutor William Schmidt said.
Two investigators will be in Washington when the program airs to
receive any tips, the prosecutor said.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Corrections and the state Attorney General's
office are investigating why Alves was released before law
enforcement authorities were notified.
</P>
<P>
   Corrections officials have acknowledged that they notified the
Bergen County Prosecutor's office of Alves' release too late for
prosecutors to be able to object.
</P>
<P>
   Terhune said letters sent by the Bergen County prosecutor's
office to the state Parole Board offering evidence that Alves is a
suspect in several murders and claims that he raped and killed more
than a dozen women might not even have been considered by
corrections officials before his release.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Alves, who as a convicted sex offender must notify
authorities of his address upon release from prison, gave
corrections officials a bogus address.
</P>
<P>
   ''Specifically and regrettably, there were a whole host of
procedures that were not followed,'' Terhune said. ''The policy and
procedure was there. It just wasn't followed.''
</P>
<P>
   Terhune admitted the errors before a state Senate committee
whose members demanded to know exactly how the convict was released
and who authorized it.
</P>
<P>
   Terhune offered no names or details at the hearing, only a
vigorous apology and the promise that in the future, no sex
offender would be released until a prison administrator personally
reviews the convict's entire record.
</P>
<P>
   Terhune released the names of the private psychologists -- Dr.
Judith Frankel and Dr. Jack Gibbons -- only after senators told him
they wanted the names of those involved and threatened to hire a
special counsel and fight to have the records opened if he did not
comply.
</P>
<P>
   Alves served less than half of a 47-year sentence for the 1976
rape of a teen in Fair Lawn and the assault of a Clifton teen.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Alves was again imprisoned in New Jersey for violating
his parole after an arrest in Flagstaff, Ariz., on charges of
possession of a handgun, Terhune said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The corrections department must begin reviewing a prisoner's
records 150 days before the scheduled release and must notify the
county prosecutor between 90 and 30 days in advance, Terhune said.
The corrections department began Alves' review on Jan. 11 and he
was released March 9.
</P>
<P>
   ''We did something wrong. We had procedures in place and our
very own procedures were not followed,'' Terhune said.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Judiciary Committee Chairman William L. Gormley,
R-Atlantic, said he wants to know how Alves was released.
</P>
<P>
   ''The question is not what happened,'' Gormley said. ''The whole
state wants to know how this happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Raymond J. Zane, D-Gloucester, wants to know what files the
private psychologists reviewed and said any information about
additional victims should have been considered.
</P>
<P>
   But Terhune repeatedly said he did not know what documents were
reviewed by the officials who approved the release.
</P>
<P>
   The corrections department could fine, suspend or dismiss any
other state employee involved. State employees and the
psychologists could be subject to criminal action, Terhune said.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Christie Whitman supports Terhune and applauded his move to
admit the error and take action, said her spokesman, Pete
McDonough.
</P>
<P>
   ''The commissioner did the right thing today, going to the
committee and admitting there had been some mistakes in his
department,'' McDonough said.
</P>
<P>
   Schmidt also said Thursday that the New York City police
department has joined his office and other agencies in the hunt for
Alves.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
