<DOCNO> APW20000316.0199 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 20:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Irish Premier Lauds Poet Heaney  </HEADLINE>
By CARL HARTMAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Irish Prime Minister Bertie Ahern invoked the
verses of Irish poet Seamus Heaney on St. Patrick's eve to give a
hopeful view of Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Ahern appeared at the Kennedy Center with Peter Mandelson, the
British minister for Northern Ireland. They listened as actress
Roma Downey of TV's ''Touched by an Angel'' read from a Heaney
poem:
</P>
<P>
   ''The longed for tidal wave of Justice
</P>
<P>
   ''Can rise up and
</P>
<P>
   ''Hope and History rhyme.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Ahern read from prepared remarks: ''We who live in Ireland
do so at a time when hope and history do indeed rhyme in many
ways.''
</P>
<P>
   Ahern and Mandelson were speaking at a free performance to
promote a festival at the Kennedy Center called ''Island -- Arts
from Ireland,'' devoted to Irish music, plays, films, dance and
poetry. Heaney, who will appear at the festival in May, has
recently created an unusual best-seller in Britain with his poetic
translation of the old English tale ''Beowulf.''
</P>
<P>
   Mandelson also joined politics and art optimistically with
praise for the festival.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it will help give a tantalizing view of what Northern
Ireland could be like and I believe will be like,'' he said, after
promising not to give a political speech.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is a very big prize to be gained in Northern Ireland.
It's a prize of permanent peace, political inclusion for everyone
... and where there are aren't any second-class citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   Ahern and Mandelson were in Washington, along with Sinn Fein
leader Gerry Adams and Protestant politician David Trimble, for
talks with President Clinton.
</P>
</TEXT>
