<HEADLINE> Fortier Denied Bond During Appeal  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER (AP) -- An appeals court has denied a bid by Michael
Fortier to be set free on bond pending an appeal of his 12-year
prison sentence for failing to notify authorities of the Oklahoma
City bombing plot.
</P>
<P>
   The 10th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals on Thursday denied
Fortier's motion for bail saying the defendant had not raised a
substantial question of law or fact likely to result in a prison
sentence less than the time served by the expected conclusion of
the appeal process.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Fortier's lawyers filed an appeal arguing his
sentence is the result of a vindictive judge who erred by giving
Fortier a punishment well above federal guidelines for involuntary
manslaughter.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge G. Thomas Van Bebber sentenced Fortier to 12
years in prison and fined him $200,000 in May 1998, but the federal
appeals court in Denver sent the case back to Van Bebber because he
mistakenly used guidelines for first-degree murder.
</P>
<P>
   Van Bebber last October reduced the fine to $75,000 but handed
down an identical 12-year sentence using ''an upward departure''
that allowed him to sentence Fortier above the standard sentence of
4 years and 3 months for involuntary manslaughter.
</P>
<P>
   Fortier pleaded guilty to failing to notify authorities about a
plot to bomb the Alfred P. Murrah federal building. He also was
sentenced for helping to move and sell stolen weapons and lying to
FBI agents.
</P>
<P>
   Timothy McVeigh, a friend of Fortier''s, was convicted on
federal murder charges and sentenced to death in the April 19,
1995, bombing that killed 168 people and injured hundreds more.
Terry Nichols was sentenced to life in prison without parole after
being convicted of conspiracy and involuntary manslaughter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
