<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore, Bush Trade Barbs on Taxes  </HEADLINE>
By CALVIN WOODWARD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHEVY CHASE, Md. (AP) -- Democrat Al Gore criticized his
presidential rival's tax-cut plan Thursday as ''economic snake
oil'' that even congressional Republicans can't love. He said it
would leave social services begging or return America to the era of
ballooning budget deficits.
</P>
<P>
   Campaigning in Springfield, Ill., Texas Gov. George W. Bush took
the slam curtly. ''He wants to leave the money in Washington,''
said Bush, referring to the lack of broad tax relief in Gore's
agenda. ''He'll say anything to get elected.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore cast the campaign as a choice between policies that
underwrote the ''Clinton-Gore recovery'' and ones that gave America
the ''Bush-Quayle catastrophe,'' meaning the recession that hit
when Bush's father was president.
</P>
<P>
   ''How can somebody come before the American people with a
straight face and say let's get rid of what's working and go back
to what failed?'' Gore, the presumptive Democratic presidential
nominee, asked in a speech to the Amalgamated Transit Union.
</P>
<P>
   Gore repeatedly criticized Bush's proposed $483 billion,
five-year tax cut as a ''risky scheme.''
</P>
<P>
   Many times in two appearances, Gore invoked John McCain's
attacks on Bush during the now-settled contest for the Republican
nomination -- trying to show that it is he, not Bush, who
appreciates the public passion for campaign finance reform
unearthed by the Arizona senator.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also rattled off the criticisms that McCain had voiced
about Bush's tax plan -- that it reserves too much for the rich and
puts nothing extra aside for Social Security and Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am telling you, he should have been taking notes during John
McCain's campaign,'' Gore told an organization of neighborhood
groups, ACORN, in accepting its endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   ''He is so committed to this economic snake oil that ... he even
dismissed John McCain's campaign and said that he had learned
nothing from it and had no intention of taking any advice from the
McCain group.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's four-stop Illinois visit marked his return to the
fund-raising circuit for the first time since mid-December. He
headlined a $1,000-per-person event at the Cantigny War Museum in
Wheaton, aimed at grossing $100,000, and criticized the
administration's military policies.
</P>
<P>
   ''Since we were having the meeting in a war museum, I felt like
holding a news conference in from of one of those old World War I
tanks and saying, 'Look what Clinton-Gore brought you,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's record-shattering $73 million campaign fund has
been largely depleted by McCain's challenge. His team plans to
raise up to $10 million in the next two months.
</P>
<P>
   Gore staged a rare day of campaigning inside the Washington
beltway before taking a few days off. And it was inside the beltway
that he found his latest fodder for attacking Bush -- a decision by
congressional Republicans a day earlier not to move ahead with a
budget plan similar to Bush's.
</P>
<P>
   ''Now, if it is so risky that even the group that Newt Gingrich
ushered into the United States Congress will not vote for it, you
know it is risky indeed,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush says his tax cuts would not touch portions of projected
budget surpluses set aside for Social Security and Medicare and
would leave money to pay down the national debt. His plan would cut
tax rates for all income groups, bringing the lowest rate down to
10 percent from 15 percent now.
</P>
<P>
   Gore asserted Bush's plan leaves three choices: a massive raid
on Social Security, renewed deficit spending or an evisceration of
federal spending on health, education and other necessities. The
proper choice, he said, is ''None of the above.''
</P>
<P>
   ''He could put us way into the hole,'' Gore said. ''Back to the
Bush-Quayle years.''
</P>
<P>
   In an address to the Consumer Federation of America, Gore
endorsed efforts to stop pharmaceutical companies from winning
extended patent protections for genetic products.
</P>
<P>
   He tied the issue to his post-McCain emphasis on campaign
finance reform, saying the drive by companies for longer patent
protection shows how special interests can use their fund-raising
powers and political clout to get their way.
</P>
<P>
   In the speech, Gore also pitched enhanced protections for
patients in health maintenance organizations and criticized
congressional Republicans for holding up gun control.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
