<HEADLINE> Lawmaker Pleads in Hit-and-Run  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARRISBURG, Pa. (AP) -- A state lawmaker pleaded innocent
Thursday in a hit-and-run that left a pedestrian dead.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Thomas W. Druce was given a trial date of May 8.	   Druce, 38, a House
member since 1993, is charged with vehicular
homicide, leaving the scene of a fatal accident, insurance fraud,
tampering with evidence and several other counts.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican allegedly struck and killed Kenneth Cains, 42, of
Harrisburg as he crossed a street July 27. Druce allegedly took
steps to conceal the accident, failed to report it, had his
state-leased vehicle repaired and returned it to an auto dealership
the next week, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Druce has said he thought he struck a sign and did not know
anyone had been killed until January, when police began
investigating him.
</P>
<P>
   District Attorney Edward Marsico Jr. said he plans to seek a
one-year mandatory jail sentence on the charge of leaving the scene
of the accident.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters were barred from attending the arraignment.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve news organizations, including The Associated Press, wrote
a letter of protest to chief Judge Joseph H. Kleinfelter of Dauphin
County Common Pleas Court, saying the closure of the hearing was
unconstitutional.
</P>
