<HEADLINE> Guilty Plea in Border Arrest Case  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE (AP) -- An Algerian man suspected of ties to an alleged
bombing plot pleaded guilty Thursday to a charge that he illegally
entered the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Abdel Hakim Tizegha, 29, is scheduled to be sentenced here June
2 by U.S. District Judge Barbara Rothstein, the U.S. attorney's
office said in a news release.
</P>
<P>
   Tizegha was arrested Dec. 24 in suburban Bellevue, where he was
living, and accused of illegally re-entering the United States
while he had an outstanding deportation order.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators believe he may have ties to men in Montreal and
New York who have connections with Ahmed Ressam. Ressam is the
Algerian man who was arrested in Port Angeles in December after
arriving from Canada with explosives and bomb-making components in
his rented car.
</P>
<P>
   Ressam has pleaded innocent to conspiring to commit a terrorist
bombing, smuggling explosives, possessing an explosive device and
making false statements. He faces trial July 10 in Los Angeles.
</P>
