<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cuba Says No Plans To Open Borders  </HEADLINE>
By ANITA SNOW, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAVANA (AP) -- The communist government denied Thursday that it
intended to open up its borders to allow a mass exodus of Cubans to
the United States to show its anger at U.S. immigration policies.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign media had speculated about such a move after the
Communist Party daily Granma in an editorial Tuesday slammed the
U.S. Cuban Adjustment Act, a 1966 law that allows Cubans who reach
U.S. soil to apply for U.S. residency.
</P>
<P>
   Cuba says the law violates 1994 and 1995 migration accords with
the United States aimed at encouraging orderly, legal immigration.
</P>
<P>
   Under those accords, Cuba is required to act to prevent people
from leaving the island illegally. There were concerns it would
stop doing so and allow a flood of emigrants to head for U.S.
shores to protest the 1966 law.
</P>
<P>
   When the Cuban government briefly lowered its coastal borders
during the summer of 1994, more than 30,000 rafters crossed the
straits or were picked up by the U.S. Coast Guard.
</P>
<P>
   A repeat is not planned, the government said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''It doesn't make sense to anyone that Cuba is moving in that
direction,'' Granma said in its editorial.
</P>
<P>
   ''To the contrary, it is thanks to a special effort by our
country in controlling its borders'' that more do not leave
illegally, Granma said.
</P>
<P>
   The paper acknowledged that many Cubans think opening the
island's borders would be an appropriate way to show anger at the
failure to return 6-year-old Elian Gonzalez, whose father is
demanding his return to the island.
</P>
<P>
   Under the accords, most Cubans trying to reach U.S. shores but
picked up at sea by the U.S. Coast Guard are automatically
repatriated to Cuba. But, under the 1966 act, those who reach U.S.
soil are allowed to stay.
</P>
<P>
   Cuba says the law encourages illegal and dangerous forms of
immigration by Cubans.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban exiles in Miami claim that those who hazard the crossing
are seeking freedom.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-16-00 2120 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000316.0209 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 21:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cohen: No China Attack Plan Evidence  </HEADLINE>
By ROBERT BURNS, AP Military Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Defense Secretary William Cohen said U.S. military
intelligence officials do ''not see any evidence of preparation for
an attack, any imminent attack'' on Taiwan, though China has
threatened to invade.
</P>
<P>
   ''What we do see is a war of words,'' Cohen said at a news
conference Friday morning local time.
</P>
<P>
   He urged both sides to stop the ''verbal jousting'' and ''back
away from this confrontational pose.'' He said that if China
continued a military buildup that was threatening to Taiwan, ''that
will only serve to increase pressure'' in Congress to sell more
arms to Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   At a delicate moment in U.S. relations with China and Taiwan,
Cohen is using visits to Japan and South Korea to express American
resolve to maintain stability in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Recalling tensions four years ago, when China held exercises in
Taiwan Straits during election time, Cohen said this time Beijing
appears ''to be trying to effect the outcome of the election (on
Saturday) with a show of words'' rather than a show of force.
</P>
<P>
   During a visit to Atsugi on Thursday, Cohen was asked by
reporters about Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji's warning to Taiwan on
Wednesday not to vote for a pro-independence candidate in the
presidential election. Zhu asserted that China would invade before
allowing Taiwan to become independent.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, in the days leading up to Taiwan's last
presidential election, the Navy had two carriers in the vicinity of
the Taiwan Strait in response to Chinese military exercises in the
strait. Now it has none.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen said China's threat to use military force against Taiwan
is an obstacle to settling the reunification issue.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have indicated to the Chinese, as we have to the Taiwanese,
that we expect their differences to be resolved peacefully, that
the threat of the use of force is counterproductive,'' Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen restated the long-standing U.S. one-China policy
supporting Taiwan with defensive arms while opposing its
independence.
</P>
<P>
   ''We believe that Taiwan should not seek independence,'' Cohen
said. ''We do not support it, but we do not support the use of
force on the part of China, either. So the comments about the use
of force can only be seen as contrary to our policy.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Cohen gave a pep talk to U.S. sailors at a naval
base near Tokyo and met with top Japanese government officials to
reinforce the Clinton administration's pledge to keep a highly
visible military presence in Japan -- including the USS Kitty Hawk
carrier battle group based at Yokosuka.
</P>
<P>
   The message behind Cohen's visit to Tokyo and Seoul is that the
United States is determined to keep 100,000 troops permanently
based in the Asia-Pacific region as a deterrent to conflict.
</P>
<P>
   On a stop Thursday at Atsugi Naval Air Facility, Cohen saw rows
of idle F/A-18 fighters sitting in the rain -- evidence that as
China-Taiwan tensions grow more intense, the Pentagon is intent on
avoiding military provocations. Atsugi is home to the air wing
assigned to the Kitty Hawk, which is in port.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen also used his visit to Atsugi to push for a solution to a
persistent irritant in U.S.-Japanese relations -- air pollution
around the base, where 3,000 U.S. servicemen and their families
live.
</P>
<P>
   Japan announced Thursday that it would expedite a solution, and
it pledged to provide temporary off-base housing to as many as
request it while steps are taken to reduce the level of toxic
emissions from the Shinkampo incinerator, a privately owned plant
that sits just outside Atsugi's gates.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Navy has complained about the pollution for more than
10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Japan agrees that air pollution surrounding Atsugi is ''a
problem affecting the health'' of American as well as Japanese
residents in the area, said Tsutomu Kawara, chief of the Japan
Defense Agency.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are most appreciative,'' Cohen said. ''This is something
that affects the health and welfare and well-being of not only
American citizens who are at Atsugi but also of Japanese
citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen and Kawara also discussed the status of negotiations on a
new five-year agreement under which the government pays part of the
cost of having 47,000 American troops on its soil. Japanese
officials have indicated they may want to reduce the $5 billion a
year that Tokyo pays under the current arrangement, which expires
in 2001.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-16-00 2121 </TRAILER>
