<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 21:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Rejects Italy Royalty Proposal  </HEADLINE>
By PAUL AMES, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- Italy's former royal dynasty suffered a
setback Thursday when the European Parliament voted down a demand
that Italy end the 54-year exile of the family's menfolk.
</P>
<P>
   Italian voters abolished the monarchy in a 1946 referendum. Two
years later the new republic's constitution barred King Umberto and
his male descendants from the country in punishment at the royal
families support for the Fascist regime of Benito Mussolini.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the European Union assembly, meeting in Strasbourg,
France, defeated by 256 votes to 173 a proposal that would have
condemned the exile as ''a cruel and unusual punishment with no
place in a modern Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   Victor Emmanuel, the son of Umberto and scion of the House of
Savoy, denounced the vote but told reporters at his home in Geneva
his campaign to return to Italy would continue. Umberto, who ruled
for just 26 days, died in Switzerland in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition to the motion was led by the Socialist faction in the
assembly, joined by the Greens, Liberals, Communists and even five
members from the center-right European People's Party.
</P>
<P>
   The European Parliament resolution would not have been binding
on the Italian government. But the resolution would have urged the
EU's executive Commission to take legal action against Italy at the
EU high court if action was not taken within 6 months to end the
Savoys' exile.
</P>
<P>
   A constitutional amendment that would allow the Savoys' back was
approved by the lower house of the Italian parliament in 1998, but
has since been snagged in a Senate committee.
</P>
<P>
   The vote Thursday was also a loss for the Habsburg family
dynasty, which once ruled Austria's vast central European empire.
They are not barred from entering Austria, but cannot run for
certain offices and are trying to reclaim property seized from the
family.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution would have obliged Italy and Austria to restore
to the ex-royals ''full civil rights, including the right to enter
freely.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
