<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 10 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Thursday, March 16, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Vt. House OKs Civil Unions for Gays
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MONTPELIER, Vt. (AP) -- The Vermont House approved legislation today that
would create the closest thing to gay marriage America has ever seen. If the
bill allowing gays to form ''civil unions'' becomes law, the state will have
gone further than any other in recognizing same-sex couples. The House voted
76-69 to forward the bill to the state Senate, where it is expected to win
approval by the end of next month. The legislation has the support of Democratic
Gov. Howard Dean.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Dow Soars a Record 499.19 Points
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The Dow industrials rocketed 499.19 points today in a
record-shattering rally as investors poured money into blue chips that had been
battered by Wall Street's frenzy for technology stocks. The Dow Jones industrial
average closed at 10,630.60. The 4.9 percent rise was not the best-ever daily
percentage gain. The technology-laden Nasdaq ended up 134.77 at 4,717.39, having
clawed back from an earlier loss of 127 points.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton To Pressure India on Nukes
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- While President Clinton does not plan to mediate a bitter
dispute between India and Pakistan over the Himalayan territory of Kashmir, he
will encourage the rival nations next week to curb their nuclear weapons
programs. The president leaves Saturday for a week-long stay in South Asia, a
troubled region often ignored by the United States and home to 40 percent of the
world's poor. It will be the first presidential visit to India in 22 years, the
first to Pakistan since 1969 and the first ever to Bangladesh.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Cuba Chides Elian's Fla. Family
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   HAVANA (AP) -- In a statement published today, the Cuban government said the
Miami relatives of 6-year-old Elian Gonzalez have repeatedly prevented the boy's
father from talking to him on the telephone in recent days. The nearly daily
accounting of Juan Miguel Gonzalez's attempts to communicate with his son was
published in the Communist Party daily Granma. It said the Miami relatives
typically argue with or hang up on the father, tell him the boy is not home or
is sleeping, distract the boy during his conversations with his father or simply
do not pick up the phone. Armando Gutierrez, a spokesman for the Miami
relatives, denied the Cuban account.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Ray Reports on FBI Files
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Independent Counsel Robert Ray said today he found no
credible evidence that first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton or senior White House
officials were involved in seeking the FBI background files on Republicans. Ray
said his office was ending the investigation with no prosecutions. The White
House has said the gathering of files was a bureaucratic blunder based on
outdated Secret Service lists of White House entry passholders.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
NATO Cracks Down on Kosovo Violence
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A NATO military exercise beginning Sunday in Kosovo will
send ''an unmistakable signal'' that a resurgence of ethnic violence will not be
tolerated, the Pentagon said today. The force, nicknamed Dynamic Response 2000,
will include 1,100 troops from the United States and about 900 from Argentina,
The Netherlands, Poland and Romania. Pentagon spokesman P.J. Crowley spoke a day
after U.S. troops cracked down on ethnic Albanian militants. Troops raided
hideouts along the border with Serbia, seized weapons and ammunition, and
detained nine people, military officials said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Drug Companies Charged With Conspiring
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Federal Trade Commission charged two drug companies
today with conspiring to keep generic versions of a popular blood pressure drug
off the market. The FTC charged that Hoechst Marion Roussel -- now known as
Aventis Pharmaceuticals -- paid Andrx Corporation to keep that company from
marketing a generic version of Cardizem CD, a widely prescribed drug for
treatment of hypertension and chest pain. Both companies denied any wrongdoing.
</P>
