<HEADLINE> France PM Unveils Tax Cuts  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS (AP) -- France's prime minister unveiled a package of tax
cuts and spending plans on Thursday, a program that could silence
criticism that the country's robust growth is not reaching all
sectors of society.
</P>
<P>
   Premier Lionel Jospin announced that a forecast $7.4 billion
windfall in tax revenues would be used to cut France's record tax
burden and boost public spending.
</P>
<P>
   His announcement on TF1 television came just hours after angry
teachers, parents and students paraded through the streets of the
country, in a nationwide protest billed as the biggest in five
years.
</P>
<P>
   ''The windfall belongs to all the French. It is the product of
their efforts and I think it is a positive ratification of an
economy policy that has been right,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Forecasts for the tax windfall are based on an upward revision
of the government's growth target for 2000. In the original budget
for this year, the official forecast was 2.8 percent growth but it
has been revised to between 3.4 and 3.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   A key measure in Jospin's package is a one-point cut in the
value-added tax, bringing the rate to 19.6 percent. All together,
the new tax measures announced Thursday bring the total tax cuts
planned for 2000 to $11.8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The extra spending includes aid to those affected by fierce
December storms and an oil spill, and extra spending on the health
service and urban renewal. The package allocated $148 million for
urgent needs in education in response to teachers' complaints.
</P>
<P>
   The teachers' protest was the latest in a series of
demonstrations and strikes by sectors of French society. On
Thursday, civil servants also took to the streets, protesting plans
to streamline the tax collection system.
</P>
</TEXT>
