<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 22:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AT&AMP;T statue: Golden Boy without a permanent home  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- No one wants the Golden Boy.
</P>
<P>
   For months, AT&AMP;T Corp. has been looking for someone to take in
its landmark statue, which is perched in front of the company's
Basking Ridge operational headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   The telecommunications giant has offered to donate the 16-ton
statue to the New York City Parks and Recreation Department in
hopes of giving the golden gargantuan a new home near its former
spot on Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   But so far, the Golden Boy remains a Jersey boy.
</P>
<P>
   Originally named Genius of Electricity, then Spirit of
Communications, the 24-foot-tall statue covered in 14-carat gold
leaf was made in 1916 by sculptor Evelyn Beatrice Longman at a
Brooklyn foundry.
</P>
<P>
   The statue, wrapped in thick electrical cable, holds an end of
the cable in one hand and lightning bolts in the other.
</P>
<P>
   Golden Boy stood above AT&AMP;T's corporate building at 195 Broadway
until 1980, when it was removed for restoration.
</P>
<P>
   When AT&AMP;T moved to a Madison Avenue building in 1983, so did the
statue.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Golden Boy was restored again and moved to the main
entrance of AT&AMP;T's operational headquarters in Basking Ridge.
</P>
<P>
   Why find a new home for the statue?
</P>
<P>
   ''We're doing this so more people would be able to view Golden
Boy,'' AT&AMP;T spokesman John Heath said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But the search for Golden Boy's new home hasn't been easy.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's just too large and too gauche,'' said Jane Tifft, a
member of the Washington Market Park board in New York. ''It's just
a tiny little park with teeny little children and a gazebo for
birthday parties and Lady Bug Day,'' said Tifft in Thursday's
editions of The Star-Ledger of Newark.
</P>
<P>
   The search began three months ago, when Materials for the Arts,
an agency of the New York City Department of Cultural Affairs, got
a call from AT&AMP;T, said agency spokesman Tim Doyle. The agency then
placed calls to about 20 city organizations to help find a new
place for the statue, including the Department of Parks and
Recreation, Doyle said.
</P>
<P>
   About four weeks ago, the Department of Parks and Recreation
began its search to find a permanent spot for the statue, said
department spokesman Bob Lawson.
</P>
<P>
   ''We go out and inspect to see which site would be appropriate,
then we go through a formal process and see if it's OK with
community boards,'' said Lawson. ''We've been looking at several
sites and having informal meetings, but no one's been coming to us
saying it's too gaudy.''
</P>
<P>
   Several companies and museums have expressed interest in giving
Golden Boy a permanent home, Heath said. But he declined to mention
the organizations or locations.

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
