<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flyers 1, Canadiens 1  </HEADLINE>
By ROB MAADDI, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Jeff Hackett made 38 saves as the Montreal
Canadiens tied the Philadelphia Flyers 1-1 Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Tocchet scored for the Flyers, who moved within five points
of the Atlantic Division-leading New Jersey Devils. Sergei Zholtok
had Montreal's goal.
</P>
<P>
   The Flyers were playing their second straight game without
captain Eric Lindros, who remained hospitalized Thursday night with
a post-traumatic migraine headache, the result of a concussion
suffered in a game two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Lindros, admitted to the hospital Wednesday, is expected to be
sidelined at least 10 days.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett made six saves in overtime, including a glove save on
Mark Recchi's hard shot midway through the extra period. Hackett
stopped a point-blank shot by John LeClair 30 seconds into
overtime, and a hard shot by Mark Eaton seconds later.
</P>
<P>
   He also withstood a late flurry in the final minute of overtime.
</P>
<P>
   John Vanbiesbrouck preserved the tie with a kick save on a shot
by Zholtok in the final seconds. Vanbiesbrouck, making consecutive
starts for the first time in a month, stopped 25 shots. He had a
nice scoop save on a redirected shot by Brian Savage with 1:07 left
in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Former Flyer Karl Dykhuis had the best chance to win it, but hit
the crossbar on a shot from the slot with 38 seconds left in
overtime.
</P>
<P>
   The Flyers took a 1-0 lead when Tocchet put back his own rebound
after Dan McGillis fired a shot from just inside the blue line with
7:22 remaining in the first.
</P>
<P>
   The power-play goal was Tocchet's 14th and second since coming
back to the Flyers in a trade with Phoenix last week. It was the
Flyers' first power-play goal in three games.
</P>
<P>
   The Canadiens tied it on Zholtok's 23rd goal of the season 2:39
into the third. Former Flyer Dainius Zubrus set up the goal with a
centering pass, which Zholtok redirected over Vanbiesbrouck's glove
as Flyers defenseman Luke Richardson appeared to slightly screen
the goalie.
</P>
<P>
   The Flyers had a chance to win the game in regulation, but
Daymond Langkow hit the side of an open net after controlling a
rebound off a shot by Valeri Zelepukin with just under three
minutes left.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia had a power play in the final two minutes, but did
not manage a shot.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett made four big saves in the first five minutes, including
a sliding stick save on Recchi one minute in, and a kick save on
LeClair minutes later.
</P>
<P>
   With Lindros out of the lineup, Keith Primeau centered the top
line.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
