<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 22:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Burdened By Ireland Impasse  </HEADLINE>
By KEVIN GALVIN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Saying he was ''burdened'' by the impasse in
Northern Ireland, President Clinton appealed to leaders in the
peace process Thursday to put aside their differences and work to
restore the British province's independent government. ''We have
the chance of a lifetime here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton addressed the annual dinner of the American Ireland
Fund, attended by such important figures in the peace process as
David Trimble, leader of the pro-British Ulster Unionists party,
and Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams, whose party is allied with the
Irish Republican Army.
</P>
<P>
   ''Whatever the differences, it's not worth another life -- not
one,'' Clinton said. ''It's not worth another day's delay, much
less a year.''
</P>
<P>
   The same day a top British official said he was ''growing
impatient'' with the stalemate in the Northern Ireland peace
process, U.S. officials cautioned against expecting a breakthrough
during St. Patrick's Day meetings with the visiting political
leaders at the White House and on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Adams, Trimble and others were meeting individually with
lawmakers in Congress on Thursday and Friday. Clinton was meeting
with them separately Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'd say this is more than just courtesy, but I also don't
anticipate any breakthrough,'' said White House press secretary Joe
Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the meetings and a holiday reception, Clinton was
welcoming Irish Prime Minister Bertie Ahern to the White House on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he was proud to have played a supporting role in
the peace process thus far. ''Tonight, I am more burdened by the
fact that I have not found an answer to the present stalemate,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I must confess as your friend that I still do not know the
answers,'' he said. ''But I do know life is fleeting, amd
opportunities come, and also go. We have the chance of a lifetime
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Britain's Northern Ireland Secretary Peter Mandelson suspended
the province's nascent coalition government last month because the
IRA refused to give up its weapons.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Mandelson urged both sides to use their visit to
Washington to restart the process.
</P>
<P>
   ''Stop walking away. Stop the silence. Stop the name calling.
Stop the blame game,'' he said at a news conference. ''Get back to
serious talks, serious business.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ''I am growing impatient with the parties. They need
to talk sensibly, treat each other sensibly and negotiate
sensibly.''
</P>
<P>
   Mandelson was meeting on Friday with Irish Foreign Secretary
Brian Cowen. British Prime Minister Tony Blair and Ahern plan to
meet in Lisbon, Portugal, next week.
</P>
<P>
   Mandelson's decision to shutter the administration came after
Trimble vowed to withdraw his Ulster Unionists party from the
coalition because the IRA had not begun disarming.
</P>
<P>
   Sinn Fein leaders noted that May 22 was the deadline for total
disarmament of the IRA and outlawed pro-British groups under the
Good Friday agreement overseen by former Senate Majority Leader
George Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   Unionists have refused to go back into the coalition government
before the IRA starts doing away with its weaponry. But the IRA has
never clearly said whether it will disarm. Sinn Fein, eager to
regain its two posts within the suspended 12-member administration,
argues the IRA might eventually disarm -- but only if unionists
allow the four-party coalition to work without obstruction.
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving for Washington, Adams said he considered the May
22 deadline now irrelevant because the government had been shut
down. Adams laid blame with those who he said ''confused and
subverted the entire process'' by making demands that were not part
of the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials were using their meetings with the Northern
Ireland leaders to press for a resumption of the coalition
government and to seek flexibility from Trimble, while urging Adams
to ensure that the IRA takes concrete steps toward decommissioning.
</P>
<P>
   ''The suspension was not caused by any failure of the
institutions themselves, nor by any violation of the agreement, but
by an internal political crisis focused on the issue of
decommissioning,'' the Friends of Ireland said in a statement
Thursday. The executive committee of the group, comprised of U.S.
lawmakers, includes Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., and House
Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-16-00 2248 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
