<DOCNO> APW20000316.0227 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 22:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Rise  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo share prices rose Friday morning, boosted by
a record surge on Wall Street. The dollar edged higher against the
yen.
</P>
<P>
   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 160.47
points, or 0.83 percent, to 19,413.70 at the end of the morning
session. On Thursday, the average closed up 174.63 points, or 0.92
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar bought 105.95 yen, up 0.47 yen from late Thursday in
Tokyo and also above its late New York level of 105.56 yen.
</P>
<P>
   On the stock market, prices advanced as high technology issues
and telecommunication stocks were leading the way after the Dow
Jones industrial average rose 499.19, or 4.9 percent, to 10,630.60
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   That shattered the Dow's previous record one-day rise of 380.53
points, set Sept. 8, 1998, but was not close to a record percentage
gain.
</P>
<P>
   Also in New York, the Nasdaq composite index rose 134.77 to
finish at 4,717.39.
</P>
<P>
   Also supporting Friday's gains was Japanese government optimism
on the economy.
</P>
<P>
   In a monthly report, the Economic Planning Agency said signs of
recovery are emerging in areas such as corporate capital
investment, through it said the nation's overall economic situation
remains severe.
</P>
<P>
   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the
first section was up 16.27 points, or 0.98 percent, to 1,661.84.
The TOPIX closed up 40.14 points, or 2.5 percent, the day before.
</P>
<P>
   In currency dealings, the dollar edged higher early Friday after
Japanese and U.S. Institutional investors bought the euro against
the yen.
</P>
<P>
   The euro drew investor interest after the European Central Bank
raised its key interest rate Thursday by a quarter-point to 3.5
percent.
</P>
<P>
   A higher interest rate tends to make a nation's currency more
attractive to investors.
</P>
<P>
   The euro was traded at 102.67 yen, up from 102.34 late Thursday
in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond fell
to 1.8250 percent from Thursday's finish of 1.8400 percent. Its
price rose 0.12 point to 99.78.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
