<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 22:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Thursday, March 16, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Vt. House OKs Gay 'Civil Unions'
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MONTPELIER, Vt. (AP) -- The Vermont House approved a bill today allowing gays
to form ''civil unions,'' the closest thing to gay marriage America has ever
seen. If the bill becomes law, the state will have gone further than any other
in recognizing same-sex couples. The federal government still would not
recognize such unions with regard to such things as immigration rights, Social
Security and federal taxes. Vermont's Senate is expected to approve the bill by
the end of next month.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Dow Soars a Record 499.19 Points
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The Dow industrials rocketed 499.19 points today in a
record-shattering rally as investors poured money into blue chips that had been
battered by Wall Street's frenzy for technology stocks. The Dow Jones industrial
average closed at 10,630.60. The 4.9 percent rise was not the best-ever daily
percentage gain. The technology-laden Nasdaq ended up 134.77 at 4,717.39, having
clawed back from an earlier loss of 127 points.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Cuba Denies Mass Exodus Speculation
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   HAVANA (AP) -- The communist government denied today that it intended to open
up its borders to allow a mass exodus of Cubans to the United States to show its
anger at U.S. immigration policies. Foreign media had speculated about such a
move after the Communist Party daily Granma in an editorial Tuesday slammed the
U.S. Cuban Adjustment Act, a 1966 law that allows Cubans who reach U.S. soil to
apply for U.S. residency. Cuba says the law violates 1994 and 1995 migration
accords with the United States aimed at encouraging orderly, legal immigration.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Seeks Delay for Law License
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- President Clinton asked a court committee to wait
until after he leaves office next year to consider disbarring him for his
testimony in the Monica Lewinsky scandal. On Thursday, the deadline for Clinton
to respond to complaints against him, his private lawyer David Kendall asked for
more time under Arkansas Supreme Court rules that allow extensions of a
''reasonable length.'' Signaling his intention to fight the complaints, the
president renewed his law license Feb. 29 for a $100 fee.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Ray Reports on FBI Files
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Independent Counsel Robert Ray said today he found no
credible evidence that first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton or senior White House
officials were involved in seeking the FBI background files on Republicans. Ray
said his office was ending the investigation with no prosecutions. The White
House has said the gathering of files was a bureaucratic blunder based on
outdated Secret Service lists of White House entry passholders.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Zimbabwe Guerrillas Threaten War
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) -- Militant black ex-guerrillas said Thursday they are
ready to go to war, and would even fight to overthrow President Robert Mugabe,
if his government moves to halt their seizures of white-owned farms. Veterans of
the bush war for independence and other squatters armed with spears, axes,
knives and guns have invaded 549 farms this month, but have since abandoned 116.
Mugabe announced Friday that the squatters could stay on land they occupied, but
his government is coming under increasing pressure to stop the takeovers, which
experts say could hurt farm production.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Suit Against Viacom Dismissed
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Viacom won a legal tussle with the other half-owner of the
UPN television network late today, removing a potential obstacle to its pending
merger with CBS. Chris-Craft Industries, which holds 50 percent of UPN through
its broadcasting subsidiary BHC Communications, had filed suit against Viacom
claiming it had violated terms of their partnership deal by agreeing to merge
with CBS. Judge Herman Cahn of the New York Supreme Court agreed with Viacom's
position that it did not yet violate the accord since its merger with CBS has
not closed.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Rise
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo share prices rose Friday, boosted by a record surge on
Wall Street. The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 176.95 points
to 19,430.18 in early trading.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gonzaga Beats Louisville 77-66
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) -- Gonzaga, the little Jesuit school that became the
darling of last season's NCAA tournament with its improbable run to the West
regional final, knocked off Louisville 77-66 in the first round tonight behind
Richie Frahm's 31 points. The Bulldogs (25-8) play the winner of Thursday
night's Northern Arizona-St. John's game in Saturday's second round. In other
games, it was Syracuse 79, Samford 65; Kentucky 85, St. Bonaventure 80; Oklahoma
74, Winthrop 50; Texas 77, Indiana St. 61; Auburn 72, Creighton 69; and Arizona
71, Jackson St. 47.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by BRADLEY FOSS
</SUBHEAD>
