<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-16 23:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judge Dismisses Swimmers' Motion  </HEADLINE>
By BEN DiPIETRO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONOLULU (AP) -- A state judge dismissed a motion Thursday to
delay the NCAA Swimming and Diving Championships to allow Hawaii
swimmers to resolve problems with the NCAA over their qualifying
times.
</P>
<P>
   Circuit Judge Gail Nakatani ruled in favor of an NCAA motion to
dismiss the swimmers' request for a temporary restraining order to
stop the championships.
</P>
<P>
   The women's championships began Thursday in Indianapolis. The
men's competition is scheduled to start March 23 in Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the ruling, a lawyer for the university was awaiting a
decision on appeal filed by the university to allow the nationally
ranked men's 400-meter relay team to compete. The university wasn't
a party to the TRO request.
</P>
<P>
   No time frame has been given to the university as to when the
NCAA will rule on the appeal, or even if it will, lawyer Jan
Gouveia said.
</P>
<P>
   The judge ruled the swimmers didn't prove they entered into a
contract with the NCAA when they signed documents outlining
requirements to maintain eligibility.
</P>
<P>
   The statements are ''lacking in the essential requirement of a
contract,'' the judge said. Even if they were considered contracts,
the judge said ''it's impossible to conclude the NCAA dealt with
the plaintiffs unfairly, unreasonably or capriciously.''
</P>
<P>
   Eric Seitz, lawyer for the swimmers, said his clients still
haven't been told why their applications to compete were rejected,
although athletic director Hugh Yoshida testified Wednesday there
were errors in paperwork sent to the NCAA.
</P>
<P>
   The judge was wrong to say the swimmers' signed statements
aren't contracts, Seitz said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Basically a contract, you're told on your first day of law
school, consists of certain elements. It consists of an offer, an
acceptance and something called consideration, you pay something,
you perform something, you do something,'' Seitz said.
</P>
<P>
   The offer from the NCAA, Seitz said, was that the swimmers could
participate in NCAA-sanctioned events if they agreed to take drug
tests and to meet other eligibility requirements.
</P>
<P>
   ''The kids signed. They agreed to do all those things and
they've done all those things,'' Seitz said.
</P>
<P>
   NCAA lawyer Linda Salfrank refused comment and a local lawyer
hired by the NCAA said he was prohibited by the organization from
speaking about the case.
</P>
<P>
   The swimmers expressed disappointment with the ruling, and
haven't decided whether to pursue further legal action.
</P>
<P>
   ''We just want to swim. We never have been told what we did
wrong,'' said Simon Thirsk, whose times in individual events are
among the 50 best in the world this year and who is a member of the
relay team.
</P>
<P>
   ''The judge has clearly said the NCAA doesn't need to answer to
any rules,'' Thirsk said.
</P>
<P>
   Swimmer Melanie Zauder said not being able to compete in the
championships deprives her of one of her two chances to qualify for
the U.S. Olympic team.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was going to try to qualify for Olympic team at NCAA
Championships, and now I don't have the chance, leaving me only
with one event with which to qualify,'' the U.S. Olympic trials,
Zauder said.
</P>
<P>
   Seitz said the decision shows the arrogance and heavy-handed
approach the NCAA takes to student-athletes it claims to support.
</P>
<P>
   ''It tells them that the NCAA certainly is not interested in
them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''They use this lofty language about student-athletes, about
athletic experiences being part of your education. The education
these kids got today was about something very nasty and very
negative. They learned the NCAA is a pretty rotten and disturbed
organization.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-16-00 2320 </TRAILER>
