<HEADLINE> Students Plead Innocent to Charges  </HEADLINE>
By LUIS CABRERA, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHIMACUM, Wash. (AP) -- Two middle school students pleaded
innocent Thursday to charges they plotted to shoot their
classmates, teachers and administrators.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Mascho, 12, and Jill Martin, 14, appeared in Jefferson
County Juvenile Court handcuffed at the waist with double links of
chain wrapped around their bodies. Bail was set at $50,000 for the
boy and $5,000 for the girl.
</P>
<P>
   Both were charged Wednesday as juveniles with conspiracy to
commit first-degree murder. The boy also was charged with taking a
motor vehicle without permission to travel to Tacoma, about 90
miles to the southeast, to allegedly buy weapons and recruit help
from his cousin's gang-member friends.
</P>
<P>
   Police say the boy hatched the shooting spree plan, and the girl
suggested refinements, including cutting phone lines, using gun
silencers and warning friends to stay away on the chosen day.
</P>
<P>
   ''She's a 14-year-old kid. He's 12. They're not going to kill
anybody,'' said the girl's lawyer, Craddock Verser.
</P>
<P>
   The boy's lawyer, John Hynson, said he would make a motion to
dismiss the charges at a pretrial hearing next Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The two students were expelled from Chimacum Middle School
earlier this month. They were described in court papers as unhappy
with how they were treated by fellow students and staff.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted, prosecutors will seek to keep them in custody
until they are 21.
</P>
<P>
   About 360 students attend the school in Chimacum, a small town
60 miles northwest of Seattle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
