<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shadow Cabinet Forms in Czech Rep.  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRAGUE, Czech Republic (AP) -- A legislator for the ruling Social
Democratic party introduced female shadow cabinet Thursday as a
counterbalance to the Czech Republic's male-only government.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's partly a joke, a bit of fun, but partly also an attempt
to give women a chance to be more visible in politics,'' Jana
Volfova told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   The shadow cabinet comprises eighteen ministers, including
former shot put world champion Helena Fibingerova, who heads the
sports ministry.
</P>
<P>
   Volfova, a women's rights activist, said the shadow cabinet was
a reaction to Premier Milos Zeman's recent statement that there are
not enough women in his Social Democratic party who could hold
cabinet posts.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is no feminist action, we simply want to prove the
premier was wrong,'' Volfova said.
</P>
<P>
   Zeman, who was also present at the news conference, said he has
always chosen his ministers according to their skills, not gender.
</P>
<P>
   During a visit to Prague this month, U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright only women to a discussion about their role in
Czech politics. Participants claimed she did so partially in
response to Zeman's statement.
</P>
<P>
   A number of female ministers served in Czech governments between
the fall of communism in 1989 and general elections in 1998, after
which the Social Democrats came to power.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-16-00 2326 </TRAILER>
