<HEADLINE> Syrian Minister: Talks To Resume  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) -- Peace talks involving Syria, Lebanon and
Israel likely will resume within weeks, Syrian Defense Minister
Mustafa Tlass said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''President Bill Clinton is making sincere and superhuman
efforts to revive the talks,'' Tlass told journalists in Bnashei, a
resort village 50 miles north of Beirut.
</P>
<P>
   Tlass said he expected talks to resume within weeks, but did not
elaborate. He was in Bnashei for lunch with Suleiman Franjieh, a
Lebanese Cabinet minister closely allied with the Syrian
government.
</P>
<P>
   Syrian-Israeli talks, which resumed in December after a nearly
four-year break, were postponed indefinitely in January. Syria has
said it won't return to the table until Israel pledges to withdraw
to the 1967 prewar borders.
</P>
<P>
   The recent appointment of a new government in Damascus sparked
speculation talks would resume soon.
</P>
<P>
   Syria is the main power-broker in Lebanon, which refuses to
conduct separate peace talks with Israel. Israel keeps 1,500
soldiers in southern Lebanon, but announced recently it would
withdraw them by July. Doing so could weaken Syria's hand in its
own negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Israeli warplanes fired missiles at suspected
guerrilla targets Thursday in southern Lebanon, Lebanese security
officials said on customary condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   In Jerusalem, an Israeli military spokesman confirmed the
strikes and said the jets returned safely to base.
</P>
<P>
   It was not known what prompted the attacks near Birket Jabbour,
10 milea from Israel's northern border. No casualties or damage
were reported.
</P>
<P>
   Tlass called the Israeli Cabinet's decision to withdraw even if
their is no Syrian-Israeli agreement ''one of the maneuvers and
trial balloons Israel launches to split the Syrian-Lebanese
track.''
</P>
</TEXT>
