<HEADLINE> Hamas Extremist Suspects Surrender  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NABLUS, West Bank (AP) -- Two suspected extremists surrendered
Thursday after Palestinian police surrounded a house in Nablus.
Palestinian sources said the men belonged to an extremist Hamas
cell involved in a shootout in Israel two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian security chief Jibril Rajoub and Nablus mayor
Ghassan Shaka negotiated with the men as about 200 police cordoned
off the area. The two surrendered before a deadline set by the
police ran out.
</P>
<P>
   Shaka said they were from Gaza. He said there was a large
quantity of weapons in the house, but could give no further
details.
</P>
<P>
   Israel television reported that Israeli intelligence tipped
Palestinian security about the two men.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian sources said the men are connected to Hamas
extremists discovered in the Israeli Arab city of Taibeh March 2,
before they could carry out attacks in Israel. Four Palestinians
were killed and one surrendered during a day-long confrontation
with Israeli forces there. Several bombs exploded in the house.
</P>
