<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iowa St.'s Sanderson Wins Matches  </HEADLINE>
By R.B. FALLSTROM, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Iowa State's Cael Sanderson, who last year
became the first freshman selected most outstanding wrestler in the
NCAA championships, is off to another fast start.
</P>
<P>
   The 184-pound sophomore cruised in both of his opening matches
Thursday. He led 19-6 before pinning Adam Schaaf of Millersville in
the first round. In the second round, he beat Dax Pecaro of North
Carolina-Greensboro 21-6 -- a technical fall that improved his
career record to 76-0.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, he was also top-seeded and had a 12-3 victory and a
pin the first day.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not worried about the streak at all,'' Sanderson said. ''I
haven't thought twice about it. I'm thinking about my next
opponent, my next takedown. Everyone here is a good wrestler, so
you can't overlook anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanderson's focus was evident in the second round, when he took
only five seconds to execute his first takedown. He took injury
time for a nagging ankle ailment in the third period while leading
18-6, but said it was nothing to worry about.
</P>
<P>
   Both of Sanderson's older brothers also won their first two
matches. Cody Sanderson, a senior and the No. 2 seed at 133 pounds,
beat Brad Wright of Ohio University 15-4 in the second round, and
Cole Sanderson, a junior and the No. 7 seed at 157 pounds, won two
narrow decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ''Cody and Cole, they kind of take a lot out of me,'' Sanderson
said. ''I think I'm going to have to back off watching them so
much.''
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma State, the only team other than Iowa to win the
championship the last eight years, held a comfortable lead after
the first day of the three-day meet. The Cowboys had 38 points and
a 4{-point lead over Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma State, which last won the NCAAs in 1994, kept all 10
wrestlers in the meet. Seven made it to the championship bracket
and the other three remained alive in the consolation bracket.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was a good day for us,'' coach John Smith said. ''The good
thing is we've still got all 10 in and we've got an opportunity to
continue to score points.''
</P>
<P>
   Iowa, No. 1 in the rankings, had nine wrestlers remaining with
six in the championship bracket. Iowa State was third with 30
points and had eight wrestlers remaining, six in the championship
bracket.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota was fourth with 28 points and eight wrestlers
remaining, followed by Oklahoma (25), Illinois (22) and Michigan
State (22).
</P>
<P>
   Iowa State, which tied for fourth last year, had 20.5 points and
a half-point lead over Oklahoma State after the first session.
</P>
<P>
   Six wrestlers entered the tournament undefeated, and five made
it through the first two rounds. Eric Juergens (133) and defending
champion T.J. Williams (157) of Iowa, Byron Tucker (174) of
Oklahoma, Iowa State heavyweight Trent Hynek and Sanderson all won.
</P>
<P>
   Williams won two matches by a combined 29-9 and Juergens had two
pins. Tucker won 14-3 and 21-9. Hynek won his first-round match by
technical fall but struggled in the second round, beating Chris
Miller of Brigham Young 3-2 in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Heavyweight Antonio Garay of Boston College, who had been 13-0
and the sixth seed, lost 10-6 in the first round to Russ Davie of
Cleveland State.
</P>
<P>
   Other top-seeded wrestlers generally had an easy go of it. Jody
Strittmatter of Iowa beat Nathan Navarro of Oregon State 10-1 at
125 pounds and followed with a 7-2 decision over Jeremy Sluyter of
East Stroudsburg. Defending champion Doug Schwab of Iowa (141) beat
Grant Hoerr of Wisconsin 13-3, Tony Davis (149) of Northern Iowa
beat Brian Roskovich of Ohio State 12-2 and Mark Munoz (197) beat
Dan Bednar of Ohio University 13-5.
</P>
<P>
   ''Seeds really don't matter here,'' Strittmatter said. ''You've
got to perform. Everyone starts out 0-0.''
</P>
<P>
   The exception was Brock Lesnar of Minnesota, who picked up Bart
Johnson of Boise State at the start of his first-round match and
then struggled the rest of the way in a 4-2 decision. In the second
round, Lesnar pinned Shawn Laughlin of Lehigh in 2:18.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
